<HEADLINE>I had to do my bit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* Scottish Red Cross Patron, Mary Young, 73, has worked for the
society for almost 60 years. She recounts her entry into the Red Cross.
MY mother knew a commandant at the time who had a unit in Glasgow, and
who thought she might like to start a small unit for daughters of her
friends. Things at that time were hotting up. I wasn't sure I'd like it.
But I recall my mother saying: ''I told Miss Finlay you would go.'' I
was 15. Then, along came the war.
A great many emergency hospitals including Mearnskirk, Killearn, and
Lennox Castle were set up on the periphery of Glasgow and they were
largely staffed by the Red Cross and members of the national hospital
reserves. Training was reduced to three weeks. A great many girls only
had the option of humanitarian services or working factories and being
called up. They chose the Red Cross.
I was a mobile VED at Portsmouth. Went in innocent, came out
experienced. I grew up. The youngest you could be a VED was 17 and a
half, and a lot of these girls were just out of school, some just out of
finishing schools, and they hit reality for the first time. But I never
heard anyone say ''I can't do that''.
You had to live with other people and share everything. There was
great camaraderie. You felt you were doing something for your country.
You were in the theatre, or doing routine care on the wards, or on
physio. It was risky, but it was amazing what you found you could do.
There were the odd times when people said: ''D'you think we'll ever get
home again?'' Sometimes it was the joke, ''Nighty-night, see you in the
morning if we're still here''. An awful lot of people remained in the
Red Cross after the war, others said ''Never again''.
Voluntary organisations are regarded differently than they were in my
day. I remember talking to a veteran recently, and I mentioned that the
Red Cross now provided counselling, and he said, ''What's that?'' I
can't repeat what he said when I explained. Then he added ''In my day
you just got on with it.''
You can't live in the past you must keep moving on. They say that VJ
Day will be the last big parade, and I think it will. One day our
generation will disappear. Man's inhumanity to man is appalling even in
the present day. Sometimes you think, och, I haven't done very much,
when you see what people have survived.
I've had more out of Red Cross than I've contributed. I hope it has
made me a more caring person. It's not what you can get out of Red
Cross, it's what you can bring. I've been places and done things I might
never have done. I don't regret anything.
But there are times I've been dropped right in it. You need to have
your wits about you. I was once left holding the baby. Its mother had
abandoned it. She said ''I need to go the toilet'' and I immediately
thought, someone should go with her. I'd been watching her for a few
days and I knew something wasn't quite right. But you can't patronise
people, you have to be so tactful.
''The first hour she went missing was harmless, we all had a shot of
holding the wee thing, but after two or three hours had gone by, we
called the police. They eventually found her in Leicester, four days
later. Ever since that day, when I'm asked to hold the baby, I keep one
eye on the mother. Some people have such deep problems, they just can't
cope.
</TEXT>
