<HEADLINE>SAS guided in bombers with lasers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN amazing array of state-of-the-art technology coupled with the
courage and tenacity of special forces, including Britain's SAS, allowed
Nato warplanes to strike with unerring precision.
An accurate map of Bosnian Serb positions had been built up over
months by a wide variety of intelligence gathering techniques.
SAS forward air controllers were moved into the mountains surrounding
the Bosnian Serbs earlier this year to report on the movements of troops
and heavy weapons.
American spy satellites provided Nato with accurate information of
missile and radar sites, command and control centres, and even
individual tank movements.
However, the orbits of the satellites can be predicted and equipment
camouflaged to avoid detection.
Consequently, the American U-2R spy planes, which fly at altitudes of
up to 70,000ft and are much more flexible, carried out vital detection
work picking up Bosnian Serb radar transmissions.
Further information was provided by Nato jets, including RAF Harriers
and Jaguars, flying regular patrols over Bosnia and using on-board
cameras to record Bosnian Serb positions.
Over the past two months, the swathe of information has been boosted
by the American unmanned spy plane known as the Predator, previously a
top-secret project. Its television and thermal-imaging cameras can pick
up details down to a foot from up to two miles away.
But when Nato and UN commanders gave the green light for the attacks
to start, much of the targeting was down to the SAS man on the ground,
equipped with hand-held laser markers. He illuminated the targets with
laser beams, which are picked up by the attacking jets so that they can
deliver their fearsome weapon load with pinpoint precision.
Meanwhile, America's premier spy plane, the SR-71 Blackbird, has been
brought out of retirement after six years because it flies so fast and
high it can elude missiles over hotspots such as Bosnia.
Justin Murphy, a spokesman for Lockheed, the manufacturer, said that
US Air Force crews training to fly the SR-71 had looked at its potential
over the war-torn Balkans.
The air force officially refused to say whether SR-71s would be used
in Bosnia, but Captain Nori LaRue, of the 9th Reconnaissance Wing at
Beale Air Force Base, said military strategists believe the SR-71, which
is more than 30 years old, ''would have higher survivability than other
planes in high-threat areas'' where there are surface-to-air missiles.
SR-71s were retired in 1989, even though they were the fastest,
highest-flying planes in the world, largely because of the high cost of
operating them.
Earlier this year, Congress directed the air force to prepare two
SR-71s for missions by today. A third SR-71 will be used as a trainer.
But it does not appear the Air Force will make the deadline because it
is behind schedule in training pilots to fly the SR-71.
As in the Gulf War five years ago, the alliance is again using video
clips to show its capability to wage smart, precise, high-tech warfare.
Within 24 hours of Nato bombs striking Serb targets, black-and-white
video clips were produced to prove just how accurate most of the hits
were. Alliance officials released 11 short scenes of bombing runs over
Bosnia, all of them taken by cameras aboard British, American, and
Spanish planes from which the laser-guided bombs were fired.
Minutes later the images were on television screens, beamed to the
four corners of the world from satellite transmission trucks outside
Nato's southern Europe headquarters. They went from the cockpit to the
living room in less than 24 hours.
''The clips pretty much speak for themselves,'' American Major General
Mike Short said as the lights were dimmed at a Nato briefing. Indeed,
the video footage needed little commentary.
One second a single-storey building was in the cross-hair of the
pilot's sight, the next second a streak of light arrived from the right
side of the screen and the building was gone in a silent puff of smoke.
In another ''smart bombing'', a series of one-storey buildings on the
right of a narrow country road was wiped out by precision bombs while
those on the other side of the road were left untouched. -- Reuter/AP
</TEXT>
