<HEADLINE>Two-month lay-off is relief for Levein</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRAIG Levein, the Hearts captain, believed his career was in danger
when stretchered off against Dunfermline in a Coca-Cola Cup tie at
Tynecastle on Wednesday.
However, a surgeon's verdict in Glasgow yesterday was that the
defender could be in action within two months. ''It was a tremendous
relief to hear the initial verdict,'' said Levein. ''I was concerned
that it was damage to the cruciate ligament I had suffered. That was
something I had gone through twice before, and the thought at the back
of my mind was that the surgeon might tell me that it was all over.
''At the moment he seems convinced that it was the medial ligament
which was affected, and that would mean a two-month lay-off. That is
great news for me, because I feel that I have five years left in me, and
to stop so soon would have been terrible.''
Levein, 30, reckons he could now be back in action for Hearts in
November and insisted: ''I want to be a part of this new Hearts set-up
and I know how important this is. OK, I shall be out for some time --
but that is so much better than I had feared.''
While Levein celebrated an escape from what might have been a
career-threatening injury, Everton's Duncan Ferguson was told that he
would require further surgery following a hernia operation towards the
end of last season. He faces another three months on the sidelines.
0
* CELTIC still await a decision on their troubled European
Cup-winners' Cup tie against Dynamo Batumi of Georgia, scheduled for two
weeks' time. UEFA officials Lennart Johanneson and Gerard Aigner were on
a fact-finding mission to the area and returned last night.
They were reporting on the situation in Georgia, Armenia, and
Azerbaijan, all fledgling members of the European Union. Last night a
spokesman for Europe's football officials said that a decision would be
announced late today.
It remains unlikely that Celtic will win their appeal to move the
match to a neutral venue, especially as two European ties took place
there last week without trouble.
* IF Rangers are not firing on all cylinders at this time, their
Champions' League rivals, Borussia Dortmund, are having an even tougher
time. After three matches of the Bundesliga, they are thirteenth with
two points.
In midweek, Borussia allowed newly-promoted Hansa Rostock to battle
back from 2-0 down to win 3-2, and coach Ottmar Hitzfeld knows he needs
to see a rapid improvement with the start of the Champions' League
looming.
</TEXT>
