<HEADLINE>Blowing whistle on bookings</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE recent Coca-Cola Cup tie between Falkirk and Aberdeen produced an
even larger crime count than was first thought.
Falkirk keeper Tony Parks was sent off for deliberate hand ball
outside the area. Referee Willie Young had earlier cautioned Falkirk's
John Clark, and he was later joined by team-mate Steve Kirk and
Aberdeen's Theo Snelders and Peter Hetherston.
However, it has emerged that yellow cards also were dished out to
Maurice Johnston and Billy Dodds, who were called into the referee's
room at the interval and booked for their part in a melee which broke
out as the teams left the field at half-time.
And after the final whistle, Falkirk captain Joe McLaughlin became the
seventh player booked after an alleged incident with Dodds as the teams
headed for the dressing rooms.
THE SFA have been given #25,000 in sponsorship from the Bank of
Scotland, with the money going to help stage a Four Nations' under-17
tournament at Forthbank Stadium later this month.
* MOTHERWELL'S teenage striker Lee McCulloch has been named in the
Scotland international youth squad for the matches against Estonia and
host nation Lithuania later this month in the European Championship.
Squad:
Anthony (Celtic), Archer (Nottingham Forest), Brebner (Manchester
United), Craig (Aberdeen), Ferguson (Rangers), Gaughan (Ipswich), A Gray
(Leeds United), D Gray (Dundee United), McCluskey (St Johnstone),
McCondichie (Celtic), McCulloch (Motherwell), McShane (Rangers),
Mathieson (Rangers), Pollock (St Mirren), Rice (St Johnstone),
Scrimgeour (St Mirren).
* TOMORROW'S Old Firm reserve game at Ibrox will kick-off at 3.0. The
rear of the Broomloan Road Stand will be open for Celtic fans with the
Govan and Copeland Stand for Rangers supporters. The Main Stand will be
closed.
</TEXT>
