<HEADLINE>Scots sit on the sidelines</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE European Rugby Cup, the ambitious new competition initiated by the
Five Nations, will kick off on October 31 and climax in a grand final on
Sunday, January 7.
Scotland and England will join the tournament next year, SRU director
of rugby Jim Telfer underlining again yesterday that Scottish
representation will be by at least two district sides and not clubs.
Last season Stirling County and Watsonians were invited to take part but
have, apparently, bowed to the SRU's wish that clubs should take a back
seat.
This year leading teams from Wales, Ireland, France, Italy and Romania
will take part, the opening two matches featuring Faru Constantza
against Toulouse in Romania and Milano against Leinster in Milan.
''This is an historic and important day for rugby in the Northern
hemisphere,'' said Fred McLeod, the Five Nations' chairman. ''Once the
tournament is established in the rugby calendar we are confident it will
have wide-ranging appeal.''
Bernard Lapasset, president of the French Federation, believes the new
tournament will be complimentary to the Five Nations' Championship, and
will help the development of club and provincial rugby throughout
Europe.
The inaugural tournament will comprise 12 teams from five countries:
Faru Constantza from Romania, Benetton Treviso and Milano from Italy,
Toulouse, Castres and Begles from France, Munster, Ulster, and Leinster
from Ireland, and Cardiff, Pontypridd, and Swansea from Wales.
In the opening stages, each team will play two matches in a designated
pool, with the four top-placed sides going through to the semi-finals on
December 30. The final, provisionally arranged for Cardiff Arms Park,
will take place on Sunday, January 7.
Pool A -- Toulouse, Benetton Treviso, Faru Constantza. Pool B --
Cardiff, Ulster, Begles. Pool C -- Pontypridd, Milano, Leinster. Pool D
-- Castres, Munster, Swansea.
</TEXT>
