<HEADLINE>Nicol's eastern promise</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Peter Nicol, the No.3 seed, reached the quarter-final stage
of the Hong Kong Open yesterday when he defeated Paul Johnson, of
England, 15-10, 13-15, 15-10, 15-11, setting up an intriguing match
against No.5 seed Chris Walker.
As expected, world champion Jansher Khan had little difficulty against
Mark Chaloner, beating the Englishman in straight games as a typhoon
raged outside.
Organisers were given the go-ahead by local authorities to play the
second-round matches on the condition that spectators would not be
allowed into the arena during Typhoon Kent, which lashed the territory
from late morning.
''I played better than in the first round,'' said Khan. ''My short
game has picked up and I was taking my volleys better.'' He now has a
quarter-final match against Del Harris, who defeated Mark Cairns in four
games.
Australia's Ronney Eyles, the No.2 seed, was given a tough work-out by
Federico Usandizaga, of Argentina, before winning.
</TEXT>
