<HEADLINE>Armstrong fit to face GHK back row's return</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GARY Armstrong, the Jed-Forest Scotland and Lions scrum half, will not
be the only long-term casualty on the comeback trail at Riverside Park
tomorrow. Jed's guests in the Tennents premiership second-division
match, GHK, will field a complete back row of returning absentees --
Murray Wallace, Andy Ness, and Derek Busby.
Even a few weeks ago, the odds would have been astronomically long
against such a trio coming together. Ness has missed the past two
seasons because of a career-threatening knee injury, Wallace has played
little rugby in that time, and the best of Busby, the Scotland under-21
captain all of nine years ago, seemed to have long passed. But they have
won through to the doubtful honour of trying to keep Jed's irrepressible
scrum half in check.
Armstrong, who was out of rugby for all of last season because of knee
damage, returns full of renewed enthusiasm.
0
GHK introduce their South African recruit, Cecil du Plessis, at lock,
and other Southern Hemisphere players, mainly New Zealanders, pop up all
over the place.
Watsonians could even have an all New Zealand front row against Gala
if they opt for Stuart Mather, Si Farland, and Mike Stanaway from their
nominated squad. Mather, whose brother Cameron also is in the squad, and
Farland are newcomers to Scottish rugby.
Similarly, two of their compatriots, Craig Foster and Keryn Martin,
both from Wellington, make debuts for Ayr against Wigtownshire. Two
more, Dean Sheppard and Chad Eagle, have been introduced in the Currie
XV to meet Kelso, and yet another, Darren Lloyd, has his first run for
Boroughmuir at lock against Edinburgh Academicals at Meggetland.
Boroughmuir have omitted Bryan Easson, the North and Midlands fly
half.
Instead, his district colleague, Andy Knight, has been switched from
scrum half to stand-off, his role in the Dutch Euro Cup tournament in
Leiden earlier this month.
Murray Fraser, the former Highland and Edinburgh Academical centre now
playing scrum half, and John Manson, who was capped last season while he
was with Dundee, make league debuts for Stirling County in the start of
their championship defence against Hawick at Bridgehaugh. But not one of
the three Craig brothers is in the Hawick XV.
Richie and Mark, formerly with West, and James, the Scottish Schools'
exciting wing last season, experience the harsh reality of having to
play junior rugby to see whether they can make the grade.
Heriot's have five newcomers in the team to meet Melrose, though all
are home grown -- Phil Smith from Dunfermline, Anthony Glasgow from GHK,
David Officer from Edinburgh University, Fraser McMillan from
Musselburgh, and Tam McVie from Edinburgh Academicals.
Two of the Redpath brothers, Bryan and Andrew, are back in the Melrose
team. Craig Joiner resumes after injury.
LEEDS full-back Alan Tait has been named captain of Scotland's side
for the Emerging Nations section of the Halifax Centenary World Cup.
Tait, who has won 14 Great Britain rugby league caps, represented
Scotland eight times at rugby union before turning professional.
''To be asked to lead my country is one of the biggest honours of my
career,'' he said. ''It is the equal of being chosen for Scotland at
rugby union and being picked for Great Britain at rugby league.''
Leeds' football co-ordinator Hugh McGahan said he felt Scotland had
made a wise choice. ''Alan is very experienced and I feel he will rise
to the occasion,'' he said. ''Becoming a dual international is a very
big honour for him.''
</TEXT>
