<HEADLINE>Accies set up fund</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH Academicals, who yesterday renewed their commercial
partnership with Glenmorangie for the sixth successive year, will have a
trust fund in place for their players this season.
Accies, fresh from their 96-0 victory over the Swedish national side
last weekend, begin their premiership challenge against Boroughmuir at
Meggetland tomorrow, and yesterday, club president Charlie Jackson
declared that despite the recent loss of top players, they still had
managed to retain a top three placing last season.
Jackson, who also revealed that Academicals would soon appoint a
commercial manager, said that the trust fund established this season
would not provide salaries for players, but would go some way to
providing a form of recompense.
The club has attracted a number of players to Raeburn Place for the
current season, including George McKinlay (Edinburgh University), Aidan
Dow (GHK), Ross Barber (Scottish Schools), Kevin Troup (London Scottish)
-- who remains from the tail end of last season -- Colin Allan (Dundee
HS FP) and Duncan Graham (Edinburgh Wanderers).
In addition, Duncan Wilson and Malcolm McVie have re-enlisted at
Raeburn Place and it was also revealed yesterday that 1990 Grand Slam
captain David Sole will augment his Raeburn Place coaching duties with
managership of a new under-21 squad.
* GALA have enlisted three overseas players -- Mark Stumbles, a
25-year-old centre from Dunedin, New Zealand, and two South Africans,
lock Matthys Stoltz and scrum half Arnoldus van Rwooyen.
Stumbles, who has played for Otago B, was at Netherdale last night for
the official announcement of the club's three year sponsorship agreement
with McEwan's, though he is not in the Gala team to meet Watsonians
tomorrow.
</TEXT>
