<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Not a breeze for Scots</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601230</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FRUSTRATING day for the Scots seeking qualification for the British
team for the 1996 Olympics was highlighted at Weymouth yesterday on a
two-man 470 class course as Helensburgh's Andy Richards and Ian Park led
to the first mark after their only start of the day only to have the
race abandoned as the breeze supposedly faded.
''It was especially annoying not just because we were in front but
because, though it was a light wind, it was probably the most settled
direction we've this week,'' said Richards.
It was a waiting day for seven of the nine classes as the land breeze
refused to give up to the preferred sea breeze forecast for mid
afternoon. In the Laser class, only Mark Littlejohn (Sussex) managed to
master the very shifty unsettled breeze to win, while both of his top
three rivals failed even to break into the top eight places.
Youth Champion Ben Ainslie leads but Littlejohn still carries a
twenty-fourth place in his score which he will be able to discard after
nine races.
In the Teacher's Round Britain Challenge Jon Fitzgerald's Scots crew
lost out to Ireland's David Hart overnight and now lie second with a
three-mile deficit. Results:
Olympic sailing trials results:
Laser class: Race 8 -- 1, M Littlejohn (Lancing); 2, A Oddie
(Warsash); 3, P Goodison (Ulley); 34, M Barron (Loch Tummel). Overall --
1, B Ainslie (Restronguet) 36.75pts; 2, H Styles (Downs) 40.75; 3,
Littlejohn 42.75; 18, Barron 134.
Soling Class. 16 wins -- A Beadsworth, E Owen, C Law; 14 wins -- G
Charles.
Teacher's Round Britain Challenge: Leading positions -- 1, Ireland II
(D Hart) 389 miles to go; 2, Scotland II (J Fitzgerald) 391 miles; 3,
England II (D Alan-Williams) 392 miles; 8, Scotland I (P Jeffs) 415
miles.
</TEXT>
