<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prost behind the wheel</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601231</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALAIN Prost smiled with satisfaction yesterday after having completed
a second day of testing for British Formula One team McLaren at
Silverstone.
The former world champion driver, in his first serious F1 run since
the death of Ayrton Senna, sped round 42 laps of the circuit and said he
had thoroughly enjoyed the drive. However, he would not be drawn on his
plans for the future, despite suggestions he was poised to make a racing
return next year.
''When I started I had a strong feeling and some emotions because
being with this team is like being with my family again,'' said Prost.
''I am quite pleased about it all, especially my physical condition, and
the car is better to drive than I thought it would be.''
Prost is undecided about his plans for next season, but has indicated
he will not race in F1 unless the conditions are perfect for him to win
grand prix races and challenge for the championship.
''In order to race next year I will have to be in a 100% situation,''
said the Frenchman. ''I need to be very confident and comfortable and
that means I need a good car, good engine, big motivation, and a lot of
support from the team and sponsors,'' he said.
''If there are any of these things missing, you cannot do it. I have
no contract with McLaren. I will just do the tests on a free basis and
that is the most comfortable situation for me. I want to help.''
</TEXT>
