<HEADLINE>Athletes' golden chance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601232</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BERLIN'S historic stadium, where Hitler avoided presenting Olympic
gold to Jesse Owens, because he confounded his Aryan doctrine, will be
the venue tonight for a jackpot meeting, in which three black sprinters
-- Linford Christie, Michael Johnson, and Gwen Torrence -- are among
five athletes chasing athletics' biggest prize: #165,000 in gold
bullion.
Owens, who won four Olympic golds in 1936, ended his career pursuing
security by racing horses, dogs, and motor bikes. But tonight five
athletes: Christie, Johnson, Torrence, Sonia O'Sullivan (Ireland, 5000m)
and Natalia Shikolenko (Belarus, javelin) have the chance to assure
their futures with victory in the last so-called Golden Four meeting.
Winners in all four matches share 20 one-kilo gold bars.
Christie, too-miraculously recovered from his world championship
collapse, faces world champion Donovan Bailey, Mike Marsh, Jon Drummond,
and Frankie Fredericks.
The forecast wet-and-cold conditions will not help O'Sullivan, who
meets world record holder Fernanda Ribiero, and Yvonne Murray, in a
5000m world record attempt.
Murray will decide after this whether to face fellow Scot Liz McColgan
in a half-marathon debut in the Great North Run a fortnight on Sunday.
McColgan, meanwhile, has confirmed she will contest 10,000m races in
Edinburgh and Portsmouth next month.
Mel Neef has secured a lane in the Berlin 400m, but Tom Hanlon, who
clocked 7-56.71 in a flat 3000m last week, has failed to gain inclusion.
Meeting director Rudi Thiel said that he has arranged a meeting over
5000m between world record-holder Haile Gebreselassie and Kenya's 3000m
steeplechase world record-holder, Moses Kiptanui.
</TEXT>
