<HEADLINE>Seles still on course</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601236</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONICA Seles' comeback remained on course at Flushing Meadow yesterday
when she easily accounted for Erika de Lone 6-2, 6-1 in the second round
of the US Open.
Seles, the two-time champion, so tight in her first match in New York
that she had to massage her face to loosen up, appeared more relaxed
before a large and encouraging Stadium Court crowd.
''I wasn't even 20% as nervous this time,'' said Seles. ''The only
thing that was bothering me was the wind.''
After a tentative start, Seles began swinging away later in the match
and produced 21 winners with her powerful two-fisted strokes, compared
to just five for her opponent.
De Lone tried to give Seles a workout and even broke the second seed's
serve once early in the first set. But three years at Harvard did not
teach the American anything she could use against the player who had
thoroughly dominated women's tennis before she was stabbed in the back
in April of 1993.
While the No.2 seed breezed into the third round, two seeds tumbled
out of the tournament. Zina Garrison Jackson had a surprisingly easy win
against No.10 seed Lindsay Davenport, while the Czech, Daniel Vacek,
eliminated the eleventh seed Sergi Bruguera 6-2, 6-3, 6-4.
Women's No.5 seed Jana Novotna lost only three games during her 6-1,
6-2 victory against Sweden's Asa Carlsson, but Kimiko Date, of Japan,
had to work hard to overcome American Lisa Raymond, Date winning 6-2,
1-6, 6-4.
Former Wimbledon champion Conchita Martinez made short work of
Kimberly Po, winning in straight sets, Lori McNeil, who defeated Steffi
Graf in the first round of the Wimbledon women's singles last year, lost
a last-set tie-break against Elena Makarova, and Germany's No.11 seed
Anke Huber beat the home country's Anne Miller 6-0, 7-5.
Tim Henman, Britain's sole survivor in the singles, lost in the second
round to American Jared Palmer, 6-4, 6-7 (8-10), 6-3, 6-1.
</TEXT>
