<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Britain well beaten</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601237</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORLD champions Australia yesterday defeated Great Britain's women 4-1
in Sydney, another blow for the tourists who have been hit by injuries
and illness.
Five Scots figured in the match. Susan Fraser, Rhona Simpson, and
Pauline Robertson started, with Diane Renilson and Susan MacDonald
making their appearance as substitutes.
The home side scored three times in the first half, with Alyson Annan
opening their account in two minutes. Then came two penalty corner
conversions by Jenny Morris, the third goal proving something of a
disaster for the British players.
Their defence were penalised with a penalty corner, and while the
umpire was explaining the award, the Australians took the corner and
scored.
The intial shot was saved by keeper Hilary Rose but she was injured in
the process and had to be taken to hospital with a neck injury.
Tina Cullen was the scorer of the British consulation goal 12 minutes
after half-time.
</TEXT>
