<HEADLINE>Easy Dollar for backers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601238</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EASY Dollar could prove the value bet in what promises to be an
intriquing battle for today's Temple Fortune Stakes at Kempton.
The three-year-old is not the best horse in the field for this
well-contested Listed event, with the weights headed by the Group-class
Bin Ajwaad and Realities, but that pair are best ridden from behind, a
remark which also applies to the other obvious form choices Peace Envoy,
Star of Zilzal, and Lap of Luxury.
Settling that quintet will be no easy task and each will be at a
disadvantage in having to quicken from behind in what is likely to be a
moderately-run race.
They are all set to play into the hands of Paul Eddery on Easy Dollar,
who is unlikely to be challenged for the lead and will be able to
dictate his own pace.
Picking the winner of the conditions race and the fillies' event
involves a degree of guesswork, with only three of the 13 runners in
those two races having run before.
Murheb's two efforts to date make him look vulnerable, with the
Michael Stoute-trained Double Leaf the most likely candidate on
pedigree.
But in the fillies' race just over an hour later, it could pay to
stick with last month's course winner Kirov Lady, well suited by this
step up to seven furlongs.
Frankie Dettori bypasses Kempton for Haydock where he should land the
opening maiden on Double Bluff.
* SHADOW Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, The Herald's Saturday racing
columnist, will present the Ayr Gold Cup to the winning owner after the
race on Saturday, September 16.
* SAMAH, the horse responsible for twice landing hefty gambles, did it
again yesterday with a near #100,000 York coup.
His backers plunged in to force Samah's price down to 7-2 favourite
from a generally available 9-2 in the trophy race.
An estimated #94,000 in major bets was taken out of the ring, with one
bookmaker reporting an off-course bet of #2000 to win #10,000.
</TEXT>
