<HEADLINE>Barnes poison tonic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NON-GOLFING citizens of Aberdeen may have been baffled by the
appearance on a 40-foot banner stretched across Union Street which
proclaimed: ''Barnes is Back.'' Inquiries would have revealed that the
reference was to the Shell Scottish Seniors Open, which begins today at
Balgownie.
Yet that teaser, allied to the sponsor's television, radio, and
newspaper advertising campaign could well have ended in tears. When
Brian Barnes -- for it is he -- flew from London on Tuesday his left
leg, recently operated on for thrombo-phlebitis, had swollen.
He completed a practice round on Wednesday and then consulted a local
specialist who, after tests, was concerned at the condition of Barnes'
blood. ''It was,'' Barnes said, ''touch and go whether I would be
allowed to play or spend seven days in hospital on a drip.''
Warfarin, a form of rat poison, was prescribed to thin his blood, and
Barnes took part in the pro-am preliminary to the #100,000 event.
As it is, he has been forbidden to fly home after this event and not
before late next week to rejoin the US Senior Tour. There, the new
British champion, who is seventy-sixth on the money list, needs to make
the most of a few more invitations to finish no worse than thirty-first
to avoid the rigours of the next qualifying school.
Barnes, 50, has made a marvellous start to his new lease of golfing
life. Having won the season's most important title, he was second last
week and thus in only two outings, his earnings are #68,000 -- almost
double the amount of #35,000 he made in 1980, his most successful season
on the regular European Tour.
There will, of course, be no little competition for the #16,660 first
prize from the field of 78 playing 54 holes over the Royal Aberdeen
club's 6372-yard, par-70 links.
</TEXT>
