<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aftershock of bombing the Serbs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MLADEN GRBIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601240</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Mladen Grbin argues that the Nato action in Bosnia may strenghten the
cause of Serbian expansionism, and weaken the position of those opposed
to partition
THE initial surge of optimism in the wake of the Nato bombardment of
Bosnian Serb military targets may be premature, and there is already an
indication that Sarajevans are closer to reality in more ways than one.
Their experience teaches them that cautious cynicism might be a more
appropriate response. They say they have seen it all before.
Nato and the UN are very careful playing to their diverse audiences in
the theatre of war. They reassuringly point to the might,
professionalism and potential of the military alliance, while exercising
restraint, and explaining the importance of minimising collateral
damage. While this would be normally seen as referring to the civilian
population in and around the marked targets, it would appear that it may
include the operation itself, as the whole exercise contains a number of
serious risks, and a paradox.
In its initial unwillingness to show clear intent to check instability
in the Balkans, and back it up with a credible military threat, the
so-called international community is still showing symptoms of weakness,
despite robust statements, such as that of Nato Secretary General Willy
Claes. The balance between collateral damage and collateral credit is a
very fine one, and in the context of the latest action, the consensus on
to how to approach the Balkan conflict is beginning to show hairline
cracks.
Historically, the security and stability of the Balkans was perceived
to lie in maintaining the political and military structures created by
Tito, and on the principle of the Warsaw Pact and the Nato Alliance
having a shared interest in the area. In the wake of the monumental
changes in Eastern Europe since 1989, this perception became greatly
disrupted and the initial reflex was to pass the role of Yugoslavia to
its apparent successor in Belgrade, in the person of Slobodan Milosevic,
without a full appreciation of the internal political dynamics in former
Yugoslavia, and Milosevic's desire to create a Greater Serbia in its
stead.
Under an ill-advised ''stick-in-time'' policy, a substantial section
of the international community was confident that Serbia -- or Greater
Serbia -- would be able to respond to the new security and stability
demands. In the event, it has been shown that the myths, still being
perpetrated in some quarters, of the fighting ability of the Serbs,
based on the experiences of the Partisan resistance to the Nazi
occupiers and the Quisling regimes, were not a sufficient basis for this
assumption.
Nationalist fervour, initially in Serbia, and then spreading like a
bushfire throughout the region, very quickly segmenting into smaller
power centres, created a precondition for mayhem and tragedy, while the
international community did not recognise that Serbia was neither
politically nor militarily able to fill its new role. There is abundant
evidence of this in the war of attrition and territorial expansion of
the last four years which has resulted in a massive destruction of life,
of communities, the forced transfer of populations, and genocide.
A substantial part of British foreign policy, which for a long time
believed in the viability of the Serb agenda, was one of the victims.
The full consequences of such a stance on the part of the Foreign Office
are not as yet fully evident, but it would be safe to assume that in any
future, global-security arrangement Britain will be considerably
marginalised, since it is British policy that largely allowed the mayhem
in the region. Former Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd's forced consensus
on his European partners will have equally damaged Europe's ability to
have a collective say on foreign policy matters.
The newly-revived American resolve is driven by complex internal
issues, not least the congressional pressure on the US administration to
lift the arms embargo imposed on Bosnia and Herzegovina. It seems to be
paying off even now, as the Republican Congress leader, Bob Dole, has
already indicated that he may relax his demand for a vote in Congress
which would reverse President Clinton's veto on the matter. With the
presidential primaries in sight, the President should be content.
On the ground, however, the initial approaches of 1991 seem to have
been continued through Deputy Secretary of State Richard Holbrooke,
checking on the benefits of Nato action in Belgrade. Holbrooke is
spearheading the American initiative to achieve a peaceful solution,
where the details of the peace plan have not yet been made public. This
allows the initiative manoeuvring space, so much so that Milosevic's
proxies in Bosnia Herzegovina, Mladic and Karadzic, are now voting,
through Milosevic, at the table in Belgrade.
The Nato intervention achieved a limited success in terms of actually
hitting a number of communications and military installations. However,
it has also provided apparent leverage, primarily against the Bosnian
government and President Alija Izetbegovic, and has given President
Milosevic a pivotal role in the percentages end-game -- the partitioning
of Bosnia Herzegovina along elusive ethnic lines.
As the architect of the drive for the creation of a Greater Serbia,
Milosevic is no different from his wayward Bosnian Serb proxies, and he
will insist on contiguous Serbian territory, the borders of which have
been well marked by the blood of countless non-Serb Bosnians. The
ratification of territorial gains through well-catalogued unacceptable
methods, including genocide, also brings indicted war criminals, Radovan
Karadzic and General Ratko Mladic, into the negotiating process. Mladic
now knows very well that as part of this process he has sufficient space
to barter for non-removal of the artillery besieging Sarajevo, and
therefore, even before the end of military intervention has been
declared, the political space for the Bosnian Serbs is gradually
widening. Just the opposite of what the military intervention was meant
to achieve.
A peace based on the assumption that it can be achieved through
partitioning Bosnia Herzegovina, the redrawing of maps, the acceptance
of forcible migration, and further population transfers (as may be
suggested in the case of Gorazde) is no precondition for peace but
rather for further instability, which may spill over Bosnian borders.
If any territorial rearrangement results in the Posavina region in
north-east Bosnia (presently held by the combined Bosnian and Croatian
forces, guarding the narrow corridor between eastern and western
Serb-held areas of Eastern Slavonia, Baranja and Srijem, with the city
of Vukovar) being more firmly seen within the borders of Serbia, this
alone would create a most dangerous precedent in tampering with
recognised frontiers. It could in fact create a far more serious problem
in the Balkans than witnessed so far, particularly if the new role
accorded to Milosevic encourages him to pursue his original expansionist
aims. The partition of Bosnia Herzegovina would also have a dangerous
potential for provoking renewed conflict between the Croat and the
Bosnian communities.
Whilst Sarajevans might welcome the short respite, their cynicism is
certainly not misplaced, and their strong sense of reality will enable
them to fight another day.
* Mladen Grbin is a research associate at the University of Glasgow.
</TEXT>
