<HEADLINE>Starting sunny-side up</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LEILA FARRAH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first nosebag of the day is usually the worst. The spirit is weak
and the flesh unwilling to handle anything but the minimum of utensils:
''The critical period in matrimony is breakfast time,'' wrote A P
Herbert of this hour when fuses tend to be short and dispositions
unsunny.
The saying goes that the way to healthy eating -- and weight control
-- is to breakfast like a king, lunch like a prince and dine like a
pauper, but for many the largest meal tends to be the last when calories
are not burned and become stored as fat in the body.
Breakfasts can be a sensual experience with the first taste of food on
the tongue after eight hours free of downward traffic.
Memories of strong, true tastes of good quality produce are usually
linked to waking up in happy climes. Like my memories of the Japanese
miso and raw fish, the Gleneagles morning tray, a few farmhouse Aga
offerings, and my childhood brekkies of France with a steaming bowl of
cafe au lait into which entire halves of new baguette from the corner
patisserie spread thick with Normandy butter would be plunged and often
disintegrate.
A bowl of porridge is still the breakfast DIY panacea (notably the
ambrosian, organic Mornflake now available in Tesco); the
health-conscious might include kippers, fruit, yoghurt, skimmed milk,
juice, muesli, and honey.
The call of the heavy fry-up is heard, cocking a fierce snook at
politically-correct noshing. This ever-seasonal combination of cooked
meat, carbohydrate, and (unfortunately) oil, delivers an almost instant
burst of energy. With National Breakfast Week set to start on September
11, I went in pursuit of an energy burst and embarked on a shameless
(and sadly kipperless) festival of cholesterol.
THE MALMAISON
278 West George Street, Glasgow G2 4LL
0141 221 6401 -- (Full Scottish Breakfast #10, 7.00-10.00am)
* THEY'RE big on French pastiche here, with Directoire greeting you
through the imposing doorway, and the basement restaurant painstakingly
bistroed-out to suggest an environment that Erik Satie or
Toulouse-Lautrec might patronise.
Darkwood partitions, wall-to-wall winebottles, a rash of mirrors,
white tablecloths and simple white china stretch the point. Despite a
full house the previous night, at 7.30am I am waited on in grand
solitude but with an iffy opening of grimy cup rim, and fluff in the
milk jug, and a lone Twinings Assam tea bag yielding an anaemic fluid.
The buffet table to which your #10 offers unlimited visits is swathed
in red gingham (naturellement) and offers brie, melon slices, French
yoghurt, dried fruit and prunes (''People who have prunes for breakfast
are never late for work,'' Des Dawson once assured us), croissants,
bagels, petits pains au chocolat, and fresh fruit salad on ice.
This is a sparklingly chilled affair of strawberries, raspberries,
kiwi, pears, pithless orange segments and melon. The toast is good and
malty -- no marmalade on the table but bijou potettes of strawberry jam
by Bonne Maman -- and the fry-up respectable but nearly ruined by a
torrential salt grinder.
Black pudding, two rashers of smoked bacon, two eggs, half a tomato
and dryish Lorne sausage is despatched to a medley of chamber music,
Dixieland and ''bal musette'' accordion.
Other life begins to surface: an Englishman demands marmalade
(originally the set orange compote prepared by her French chef for the
imprisoned and sickly Mary Queen of Scots, then a ''Marie Malade'') and
businessmen are peeking over the partition talking about ''feelgood
factors''.
The temptation to buffet-freeload is mitigated by one's
conspicuousness in so doing; a single wee pot of imported French
''yaourt'' stuffed with sweetened segments and lemon rind (appropriately
termed ''zeste'') suffices to cleanse the palate before emerging into
the sunlight blinking from this otiose intimacy.
THE BALCONY
Frasers Department Store, Buchanan Street
(Breakfast #1.35, served 9.30-11am Mon-Fri, 9am-10.30 Saturdays)
* PAST the impeccably groomed make-up consultants, up the sweeping
staircase and through designer frocks to The Balcony, a self-service
restaurant on the first floor done out in standard-issue beige and
lacking natural sunlight.
Here #1.35 will buy five items from a choice of pork sausage, bacon,
black pudding, tomatoes, mushrooms, hash browns, fried egg or beans. Tea
or coffee are extra. Although I'm first in the queue, the wee mushrooms
are already looking tired under the heatlamps: but the counter staff are
cheery and helpful.
The anonymity of self-service seems to promote unseemly haste and the
shovelling can -- and does -- begin in earnest, it taking three minutes
flat to get outside of a crisp hash brown, juicy tomato, bland fried
egg, cold slice of bacon, beans, and meagre black pudding.
Perhaps I chose unwisely. It was, however, more sedate than the
public-thoroughfare format of McDonald's which at 8.20 that morning
sounded off like a munitions factory, abrasive coffee laying siege to
one's intestine, abetted by a sausage and egg McMuffin unsurpassedly
synthetic of taste).
COIA'S CAFE
473 Duke Street, Glasgow G31 (554 3822)
(Breakfast #2.50 before noon, then #2.95)
* THEY'RE quick on the draw here with a profusion of fried foodstuffs
fighting to stay on the plate. This is the genuine article in a bustling
family-run Italian cafe established 70 years ago amid flock wallpaper,
neon signs, dominant televisions, paintings, food hygiene certificates,
cigarette and Swiss chocolate sales.
It's a local landmark, filled with shoppers chowing down and elderly
ladies munching ice cream. Excavation yielded fried bread, tattie scone
(both a little heavy on the oil factor, for some an indispensable part
of the ritual), sausage, bacon, rich black pudding, beans and a cuppa.
No hunger pangs until six hours later.
THE LIVING ROOM
Byres Road (339 8511)
(Veggie Megabrekky #3.95. Noon till 5pm)
* THE meatless version at last! A new coat of brighter paint, fresh
flowers, white tablecloths and removal of the backroom bar and
wrought-iron conceits has brightened up this eatery which had always
seemed a chamber from Beauty and the Beast.
As at Great Western Road's The Bay Tree which does an excellent vegan
breakfast, the Veggie Megabrekky is available here only on Sundays when
the Living Room becomes the place for couch-tattying en masse, students
and trendies reclining in wee armchairs and sofas, with Sunday papers
provided, somnolence inhibited only by the upbeat music on the sound
system.
I toy with the toast and negotiate the oval dish laden with non-meat
goodies: a fried free-range egg, potato scone, mushrooms, a crestfallen
half tomato, leaving till last the moist and spicy fruit pudding washed
down with fresh orange juice as a sort of built-in dessert course.
</TEXT>
