<HEADLINE>Where colourful ideas take root</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601246</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE mellow fruitfulness bit is alright, it's the mists that tend to
put a dampener on the autumn season after the long bright days of
summer.
However, there's autumn magic to be found in a trip to the wonderful
world of the Findlay Clark Garden Centre. The visitor is immediately
greeted with autumn joy. I am not talking here about the helpful staff,
but the profusion of pots of the indispensible sedum Autumn Joy at the
entrance.
Autumn sedums are a really useful late flowering perennial with
attractive succulent foliage and flat heads of pink flowers. They look
great in patio containers or in borders along with the autumn flowering
crocus Lilac Wonder.
You will be spellbound also by the dazzling array of shrubs for autumn
and winter colour, and the wide range of bulbs -- all part of the Autumn
Magic seen at Findlay Clark.
Alan Docherty, the centre's buyer, says: ''Special mention this autumn
must go to the newer daffodils such as the butterfly varieties at #5.99
for 40 mixed bulbs.
''We also have lovely old fashioned hooped petticoat daffodils, which
are a miniature variety with a large trumpet and small petals at the
back. The variety Golden Bells has many flowers on one plant and is very
easy to grow in rockeries, tubs or window boxes. These sell at #1.99 for
a pack of five.''
The magic spell continues with the Christmas flowering hyacinths and
paperwhites. To be able to enjoy the warm scents and glow from these
bulbs you need to be planting up in the next three weeks or so.
This weekend Findlay Clark's is going Dutch and offering half-price
Christmas flowering Delft Blue hyacinths, planters and bulb fibre for
you to make up at home. As with other bulbs at Findlay Clark, you can
buy them loose or in packs. There are 80 varieties of miscellaneous
bulbs, 40 varieties of tulips and many kinds of miniature rockery bulbs,
including the narcissi Bridal Crown.
For the more adventurous, Findlay Clark has a choice to match the
Dutch bulb fields that include the Snakes-Head Fritillaria and the Crown
Imperial lily, as well as giant ornamental garlic and the interesting
Dogtooth violet with its pagoda shaped yellow flowers.
Daffodils come in large sacks or in cram-a-bag (three sizes), where
you can pick and mix from the stunning selection of Taylors Bulbs. These
include the fragrant variety Sir Winston Churchill, which is sure to be
a big hit next spring. For those bewildered by the choice there are
Patio tub boxes at #5.99 with six different species of dwarf bulbs --
daffs, narcissi, tulips, two hyacinths and a crocus. There are also
packs of 60 assorted tulips for #4.99.
For a splash of colour and interest on the patio this autumn and
winter you have to look beyond bulbs. What about ornamental cabbages?
These are very effective grouped together in one container.
Chrysanthemums will flower to the first frosts, and winter flowering
pansies, gentians and the blue flowers of the hardy plumbago planted
with winter foliage will brighten up the dull days to come. Six
varieties of bedding plants for winter foliage, sold in a pack, can
dispel the hangdog look your hanging basket usually has in winter.
Winter-flowering jasmine, with its yellow scented flowers, is being
sold in unmissable yellow pots in the covered section. There are golden
shrubs of euonymus Emerald'n'Gold and Emerald Gaiety at #4.99, Elaeagnus
at #8.99 and Choisya Ternata 'Sundance', and the white gold of the Aztec
Pearl.
Scented shrubs such as mahonias, and the almond-smelling viburnum can
be used to create a more fragrant garden on long evenings.
After this year's glorious summer you may also want to extend the
effect of a warmer Meditteranean or more exotic climate all year.
Findlay Clark has a range of exciting architectural plants such as the
Photonia Red Robin, elegant box trained Topiary Yew, and exotic triple
ball Juniper in the Italian cameo setting.
Some of the best sellers at Findlay Clark this summer have been the
cast aluminium furniture with a verdigris effect. Also the Jarrah
hardwood furniture from Australia. Cane suites with their more
adventurous designs and colourful fabrics have also sold well. Expect
even more choice next spring.
Remarkably successful, too, have been a solidly made Australian
flat-bed barbecue, running on gas, and costing around #300.
To go with the garden furniture people have been buying large colonial
style wood and canvas parasols to sip cool drinks under. If you want to
grab a bargain for next year then the parasol and base is reduced from
#114 to #79.95.
Alan Docherty tells me that Findlay Clark is eagerly awaiting the
arrival of bird tables from a new supplier Erin-Gardena in the next
week. There are seven styles priced between #30 and #50.
Erin-Gardena is keen to promote an interest in birds and 26,500
primary schools have registered in their Birdwatch Campaign.
That well known twitcher Bill Oddie and BBC 1's fully-booked
television programme are helping to back the campaign, which is linked
to the national curriculum Key Stage 2.
If you buy products from the Erin range at Findlay Clark you can
donate tokens to a school which can then save up for valuable
educational items, such as a computer. The centre stocks a range of
specialist peanuts, cedars, fat bells and packs of wild bird foods.
If you want to extend the pleasure from your garden right through
autumn and winter and into spring, the answer spells Findlay Clark
Autumn Magic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plenty to cultivate shoppers' interests</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Findlay Clark Garden Centre is only ten minutes by car from
Glasgow city centre and it's easy to find. Head north on the A879
Milngavie Road, and you'll see it on your left. There's parking for 200
cars.
The garden centre -- which is more than just that -- is open seven
days a week till 7pm in the evening.
Kids are welcome. There's child-size trolleys for them to push and
dairy ice cream from Nardini in Largs at the Famous Coffee House.
As well as the festival atmosphere of the current Autumn Magic
promotion, there are shops for the horse lover, golf enthusiast, water
gardener and pet owner.
At the Stirlingshire Saddlery when they say they have everything for
the horse and rider, they do mean it. Winter clothing is arriving now
for horses and humans from one to 101 years old.
Vast selections by Musto Barbour (including blue and green wellies),
and Drize-abone are stocked. Just in is the hip American children's
outdoor clothing by Chuck Roast, in Polartec fleece, sizes from six
months. Frogs shoes are great for dog walkers as well.
The Aladdin's Cave of Golf has lots of golf paraphernalia and a wide
choice of ladies and gents clothing. For the serious buyer, a practice
net is available, to hit some balls and try out your dream clubs. All
the major brands are stocked, including Ping, Calloway and Cobra, and
the golf shop also offers a part-exchange facility.
At the moment there is up to 20% off all golf clothing, as part of the
mid season sale. For the growing number of gardeners who wish to explore
the joys of ponds and fountains there are pre-formed pools from #24.99
and a wide choice of water plants and fish to stock them with.
Tanks of fish, including goldfish, comets and koi-carp await
selection, and of course there are all the pumps and other accessories
the water gardeners need. Those looking for an interesting gift will
find all sorts of goodies among the pot plants and the gardening books.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
