<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Waterford Foods snaps up The Cheese Company</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS,FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Cheese Company, which is a major user of Scottish-produced milk at
its plant in Lockerbie, has been bought over by the Irish-based group
Waterford Foods in a #128m deal.
The acquisition was announced yesterday in a statement to the Stock
Exchange and has been warmly welcomed by the management of The Cheese
Company.
Jim Bell, manager of the Lockerbie Creamery which has 180 employees,
said that the activities of the two companies were entirely
complementary and he forecast a good future for the Lockerbie plant with
the prospect of milk purchases rising from the present level of 190
million litres a year to 220 million next year.
The Lockerbie plant takes 45% of its milk from farmers on direct
supply contract. The balance comes from Scottish Milk, Milk Marque and
other major milk buyers.
Mr Bell spent most of yesterday briefing employees on the implications
of the takeover. He said that the overwhelming feeling in the creamery
was one of relief. ''There has been a lot of speculation about some form
of acquisition and people are glad that the period of uncertainty is
over and we can now just get on with the job,'' he said. ''All the
employees are very, very pleased.''
Waterford Foods is Ireland's biggest dairy company and already has
substantial interests in the UK and in overseas markets. It is a major
producer of Irish Cheddar, butter and yogurts. ''By becoming part of an
international dairy company whose shares are quoted on the Stock
Exchange we will be able to grow more rapidly than if we remained
independent,'' said Jim Bell.
Customers would benefit from gaining access to a broader range of
products from Ireland and the UK, he said. Farmers would also benefit
from access to these wider markets.
''Operationally we do not expect any significant changes. We will
continue to run as a business with a strong local identity.''
The Lockerbie plant is the second biggest in the current Cheese
Company operation which encompasses five creameries throughout the UK.
Its cheese pre-packing facility as Oswestry in Shropshire is the largest
in the UK, packing 45,000 tonnes a year.
Lockerbie specialises in Scottish Cheddar, Red Leicester and Double
Gloucester cheese. It also produces whey butter, concentrates and
powder. It supplies substantial volumes of cheese and butter in packs
and portions for the retail and catering trades.
The Cheese Company underwent a #96m management buy-out from Grand
Metropolitan in 1992. It is the largest cheese supplier to the UK retail
sector and in the year to October 1, 1994, had a turnover of #291m.
Managing director Roger Davenport will join the group executive
management of Waterford Foods.
* MEANWHILE, Scottish Pride has announced a temporary shutdown of its
cheese plant at Rothesay so that milk supplies can be diverted to the
liquid market. The company has experienced a fall-off in milk production
from the dairy sector in recent weeks as a result of the drought.
In England, Milk Marque has already adopted a policy of diverting
supplies into the liquid market.
Jim Hosea, chief executive of Scottish Pride, said that the company
was in a unique position, in Scottish terms, to correct imbalances. With
satisfactory cheese stocks in hand they had decided on a temporary
shutdown of cheese-making activities at Rothesay with effect from today.
Milk from farms on Rothesay will be shipped, at Scottish Pride's
expense, to its plant at Govan. Cheese production at Rothesay will
resume before the beginning of October.
Sixteen employees will be affected by the shutdown. Mr Hosea said the
company would be discussing ways of re-deploying them so that their
earnings were protected as far as possible.
He emphasised that the shutdown was ''a short-term balancing of
supplies in the face of a dilemma affecting the dairy products industry
nationwide.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A smooth operator</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN when it was a British manufacturer, in the four decades during
which right-hand drive cars were built at Slough, Citroen was always one
of the small fry, although many of its RHD products were sold in
British-influenced export markets.
Andre Citroen himself really meant business here, to the extent of
opening an exotic-looking showroom in Piccadilly, with an interior which
owed something to the appearance of Napoleon's tomb.
After the Second World War, Citroen was the only foreign-owned
manufacturer allowed to build its cars in the UK. Bearing in mind what
cult status is still enjoyed here by the 2CV -- even in the unlikely
surroundings of race circuits -- it is worth recalling that this car was
built here too, in its ordinary roll-top guise as well as in pick-up
form, and as the faintly more aerodynamic Bijou.
Times have certainly changed for Citroen. It recently notched up its
one millionth UK sale, and the significant fact is that nearly
two-thirds of those cars were sold in the last ten years. Citroen sells
more cars here than in any other country outside France.
The Xantia is the fastest moving model it has ever put on the UK
market, and more and more variations of it are appearing, such as the
1.8-litre SX automatic I have been driving, which comes at a showroom
price of #14,945.
Overshadowed in performance terms by the 16-valve versions which have
recently appeared, the 1.8-litre automatic soldiers on with the older
eight-valve power unit. Like many manufacturers, Citroen reckons that
acceleration and maximum speed are nowhere near top priority for owners
of automatic transmission cars, and much the same can be said for
economy.
As a result, Xantia automatic owners have to be content with a
1.8-litre which peaks at 103bhp, offers 0-60mph acceleration in about
13.5 seconds, a test-track top speed just over 110mph, and fuel
consumption returns like 47mpg at 56mph, 36 at 75 and 25mpg around town.
In fact, when you ponder on these figures, they are by no means
mediocre for the class. And the 1.8-litre version is pretty flexible,
even when linked with a four-speed automatic transmission. The
transmission makes agreeably smooth changes although, as with most of
these systems in a car with modest engine capacity and power, it has a
tendency to 'hunt' at low throttle openings, especially on hills. This
is something which longer acquaintance with the car ought to cope with.
On the road, I was expecting fairly laboured performance, especially
compared with a manual-transmission 16-valve, but this Xantia was more
full of pep than its basic specification suggests. Now and again,
though, I would snick the selector manually down a gear, to give it a
sharper response on hills.
Like all Xantias, this one looks like a compact car but has better
rear passenger space than many people expect, thanks partly to the low
seating position there, although that does not force an exaggeratedly
knees-bend sitting position. All the seats are comfortable, and there is
a fair-sized boot.
One feature which sets this mid-range Citroen apart from all its
rivals of other makes, of course, is the self-levelling hydropneumatic
suspension. The two immediate advantages of the system, especially with
a long-wheelbase car like this, are an absorbent ride and the natural
inclination of the car to keep on an even keel, even with a well-loaded
boot. It can be raised from its usual setting when asked to cover rough
or rutted roads, and I did try out this feature on a long-abandoned
one-time public road down in Ayrshire.
However, the other thing the suspension system gives the Xantia, in
its fine-tuning as well as in its fundamental layout, is unexpectedly
responsive handling. That is thanks in part to the slight amount of
built-in rear-wheel steer. Even this quite modestly specified and
quiet-running Xantia feels like a mature design when taken out on the
road.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mycofarm hits back over sheep vaccine</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE manufacturers of a vaccine aimed at protecting sheep from enzootic
abortion yesterday replied to critics who claimed that their latest
advertising campaign could lull producers into a false sense of
security.
Alvin Cerely, a director of Mycofarm UK, said that the problem was a
serious one with losses estimated at between #30m and #35m a year
nationally. Enzootic abortion (EAE) accounted for half that figure and
toxoplasmosis about one-third.
He accepted the comments of the Highland and Islands Sheep Health
Association that the use of EAE accredited female sheep, purchased as
part of a clean health routine, was one way to attack the problem.
''However, since EAE is a sheep-to-sheep disease the spread of
infection is always a risk, no matter how clean the original stock may
be,'' he said.
Vaccination against EAE and Toxoplasmosis offered many farmers the
opportunity to reduce abortion and related losses by a significant
amount.
Mr Cerely advocated a policy of purchasing EAE accredited females and
using the vaccines as a preventive measure. ''Abortion is a huge problem
on UK farms and must be attacked with greater urgency,'' he argued.
''Our survey results show that on average farmers do not begin to take
action against abortion until lamb losses reach 5%, by which time gross
margins will be set for a 10% reduction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>S&amp;N chairman fears devolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601251</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of Scotland's largest companies yesterday expressed its fears over
devolution.
At brewing giant Scottish &amp; Newcastle's annual meeting in Edinburgh's
Sheraton Grand Hotel, chairman Sir Alick Rankin told shareholders: ''We
believe it could have dangers for totally national and international
companies based in and operating out of Scotland.
''We believe it could have a backlash outside this country
(Scotland).''
Speaking after the meeting, Sir Alick was relatively non-specific
about the company's particular concerns about devolution, which would be
a likely consequence of a Tory defeat at the next general election.
He was, however, worried about the possible impact of the Scottish
Constitutional Convention's proposals for a Scottish parliament with the
power to levy income tax at 3p in the pound above or below the UK rate.
Sir Alick said: ''There could be a 3% variation in taxation. That is
not going to help people to work in Scotland as executives, or at any
other level of the company, if they think taxation is going to be
higher.''
He revealed that the Edinburgh-based company was also concerned about
the effect of devolution on sales of its products, as well as on
shareholders and employees.
Chief executive Brian Stewart is worried about the reaction to
devolution of trade customers and consumers -- presumably those outside
Scotland.
Less than one-fifth of Scottish &amp; Newcastle's profits are generated in
Scotland, which accounts for a similar fraction of its brewing capacity.
The annual meeting, which came only two weeks after completion of the
company's #425m acquisition of Courage from Australia's Fosters Brewing
Group, was attended by a record 387 shareholders.
Sir Alick told them: ''We are more than delighted by the strong growth
prospects which this (Courage) deal will undoubtedly generate.''
Scottish &amp; Newcastle's brewing division was renamed Scottish Courage
on the acquisition's completion, but the parent company name remains
unchanged.
New headquarters for Scottish Courage, which is currently being run
from the group head office in Holyrood Road, are being built near
Scottish &amp; Newcastle's Fountain Brewery, also in Edinburgh.
These should be ready by the spring and will house between 280 and 300
employees.
Sir Alick told shareholders that beer sales had responded positively
to the excellent summer. However, the extreme temperatures have held
back growth of food sales at Scottish &amp; Newcastle's retail and leisure
outlets.
Returning to the devolution issue, Sir Alick said after the meeting:
''We know that our markets have been developed off the basis of the
Union, and not every Englishman thinks it is clever for Britain if
Scotland splits off.
''It is very hard to see how there is a plus to it (devolution) but it
is easy to see how there are possible minuses.''
However, shareholder Leon Sidney Woolf, from London, was unhappy about
Scottish &amp; Newcastle's #50,000 contribution to the Conservative Party in
the financial year to end-April.
Begging to differ with Sir Alick's political views, Mr Woolf said:
''When you have got a weed in the garden you don't put fertiliser and
water on it every day.''
Lord Nickson, who ironically fought off the Elders/Courage bid for
Scottish &amp; Newcastle in 1988-89 as chairman of the brewing group,
retired from the board at the meeting.
Scottish &amp; Newcastle shares yesterday lost 3p to 594p.
</TEXT>
