<HEADLINE>Cairn Energy first-half profits race ahead to #8m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAIRN Energy has undergone such a radical transformation recently that
the company's first-half results fail to give a true picture of its
recent growth and future potential, writes ROBERT POWELL.
Over the last three months, Cairn's oil and gas production has trebled
to 8800 barrels of oil per day equivalent from 2700 as a result of new
acquisitions in the North Sea.
Revenue is therefore running at an annualised rate of over #30m,
although turnover for the six months to June 30 amounted to just #5.1m.
Furthermore, the Edinburgh-based company is about to drill a gas
exploration well in Bangladesh, which could lead to a 10-fold increase
in its energy reserves.
During the year year to date, Edinburgh-based Cairn has sold its US
interests at a tidy profit and pulled out of Spain at a small loss.
Meanwhile, with the help of a #16.9m rights issue, it has bought
Holland Sea Search Holdings for #17.3m and Clyde Petroleum (North Sea)
for #35.8m.
These two acquisitions have boosted Cairn's North Sea oil and gas
output, creating a cash flow that is being used to finance ambitious
exploration programmes in Asia. Cairn is particularly active in
Bangladesh, where it hopes to build a power station to burn some of the
natural gas it is confident of finding.
Cairn yesterday unveiled first-half pre-tax profits of #8m, up from
#616,000 previously. But the increase mainly reflected an exceptional
gain of #5.8m on the disposal of Cairn's Spanish and US interests.
There was no interim dividend and Mr Gammell warned shareholders not
to expect one at the year end either. ''We are basically still a capital
growth stock,'' he said.
</TEXT>
