<HEADLINE>Reckitt &amp; Colman hit by restructuring</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601253</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOUSEHOLD products group Reckitt &amp; Colman is busy integrating its
#980m acquisition of L&amp;F, the US household products group, acquired last
year from Eastman Kodak.
Costs associated with this, and reorganisation of the European
business, adversely impacted on interim profitability. In the first six
months of the year underlying sales were flat, but operating profits
from continuing businesses were 3.7% ahead.
At the pre-tax level, profits were just #600,000 better at #149.6m
before exceptional and non-operating items. During the period, the
company's Colman's mustards and Robinsons drink unit was sold to
Unilever for #250m.
Margins dropped slightly from 16.2% to 15.9%, but chief executive
Vernon Sankey said the fall was ''insignificant'' and he is confident
there is scope to further increase margins in the future as the
reorganisation benefits feed through. The interim dividend was raised by
7.1% to 7.35p per share.
In North America, L&amp;F's sales grew by 9%, helped by new product
launches. Integration of the L&amp;F acquisition is said to be proceeding
well, but Reckitt's sales suffered from destocking in the first half
following a change in its remuneration methods for brokers.
This will mean lower discounts to trade buyers in the future, with the
extra funds to be used for customer promotions.
Elsewhere in the group, good progress was made in the UK, France and
Germany in key product areas, and margins benefited from reorganisation
in manufacturing and warehousing.
There was a strong recovery in margins in Latin America, helped by an
improved performance from the Brazilian operations. The African
businesses were impacted by adverse currency movements, but sales growth
was strong in Asia, with Reckitt expanding into new territories.
The balance sheet showed the effects of the increased debt taken on
with the L&amp;F acquisition.
Mid-year gearing was 60%, with borrowings of #569m, but that is a
marked decline from peak borrowings earlier in the year of #820m.
Improved organic cashflow and proceeds from further disposals are
expected to reduce the gearing. However, interest cover is a healthy 6.7
times.
The benefits of the L&amp;F acquisition, restructuring in Europe and
increased marketing of key brands, is expected to lead to a much
improved performance in 1996 and beyond. The disposal of the food
business is part of an ongoing programme of non-core business sales,
aimed at releasing #400m over three years.
Household and toiletry products now account for 80% of Reckitt &amp;
Colman's sales -- up from 75% this time last year. This figure is
expected to grow in future as other smaller disposals are made and sales
are increased in the fast growing markets of the Far East.
North America accounts for a third of the business, with Europe
responsible for just over a third of sales. Emerging markets account for
one quarter of sales.
The interim profits were at the bottom end of expectations and so the
shares dropped 23p to 666p. The consensus forecast was for a pre-tax
profit figure of #158.3m.
</TEXT>
