<HEADLINE>Court rules in tenants' favour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PROPERTY company's bid to impose a 146% rent rise on 600 elderly
Glasgow tenants has been rejected by the Court of Session. In 1992, the
Western Heritable Investment Company tried to increase rents on their
pre-war houses in King's Park, Croftfoot, and Cardonald from #1420 to
#3500 per year.
A Rent Assessment Committee set the new figure at #1860 and now the
Court of Session has upheld the committee's decision. Local councillor,
Ms Louise Fyfe, said: ''This excellent judgment ends an ordeal which has
been upsetting for the tenants.''
</TEXT>
