<HEADLINE>Macfarlane's package</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601257</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE leading Scottish company which has never made a hostile takeover
is Macfarlane Group (Clansman), the packaging and printing group, which
turned in another set of excellent results yesterday.
The company's chairman and founder, Lord Macfarlane, prefers his
acquisitions to be willing sellers. Since he started the business in
1949, 87 firms have been acquired. As a result his empire is spread all
over Britain, from Aberdeen to the south coast of England.
Yesterday's results package was just what the stock market ordered. In
a day when most shares (outside the electricity sector) moved lower
Macfarlane added 4p to 212p.
Pre-tax profits for the first six months of 1995 jumped by 42.4% to
#10.1m on the back of turnover 52.1% higher at #79.9m. Earnings per
share rose 36.9% to 5.6p and the interim dividend has been increased by
23.9% to 1.4p.
First-half profits are within a whisker of the total for the whole of
1992. Around that time Macfarlane devised a strategic plan to double the
size of the business in five years.
With over #20m clearly in the group's sights for the full year, the
target should be accomplished two years ahead of schedule.
Sales were boosted by the sharp increases in raw materials prices and
by acquisitions. But trading was up in almost every area of the group's
activities. Raw materials prices appear to be stabilising now and
volumes are being maintained.
Lord Macfarlane proudly told me that the company had #12m of cash at
its disposal and no borrowings. Further acquisitions are planned and
there is a substantial capital investment programme in place throughout
the group.
The group runs a tight ship, but it is that unusual corporate animal
combining rapid growth with financial prudence. Part of the Macfarlane
philosophy is to follow a progressive dividend policy so that
shareholders, of whom there are nearly 2000, including most
institutional groups, share in the group's increased earnings.
Lord Macfarlane himself has a 4% stake in his company which is
capitalised at around #250m. He says the institutions appreciate his
financial commitment to the company, a point those who dump their share
options on the same day they acquire them should take to heart.
</TEXT>
