<HEADLINE>Not because of lofty ideals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601258</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
(An exception is made here to The Herald's rule not to publish
unsigned letters -- Ed.)
HAVING just read John Macleod's article (August 29) I am compelled to
put pen to paper, albeit anonymously for reasons which will be obvious.
I am one of those to whom belongs (according to John Macleod)
''lasting fame and glory'', the Kingdom of Heaven.
I am a woman of 40 years who has lived a heterosexual life having had
boyfriends (more than most because of the desperate struggle to convince
myself of my normality), having been married for 12 years and having
borne a child . . . but throughout my life, I have fallen in love with
women, well aware that the feelings I had for women were those that I
''should'' have had for men.
But -- I've never done anything about it (I suppose John Macleod will
find that laudable!) not because of lofty ideals or notions of
inheriting Heavenly Kingdoms, but because of cowardice and guilt --
all-consuming guilt which has made me feel all my life that the ''real
me'' must be a loathsome creature, to be kept hidden at all times.
Spontaneity is out of the question -- I must first consider what a
''normal'' reaction would be . . . Can John Macleod have any idea of the
anguish that I feel because I perpetuate this profound lie about myself?
Yet in all other areas of life I strive to be truthful, and value truth
beyond anything.
I weep as I write. To add to the guilt I already feel, I feel shame
that I will not sign this letter, and that by maintaining this silence I
am helping to give credence to the views held by John Macleod and his
ilk.
I have nothing but admiration for Michael Barrymore's courage and
honesty -- perhaps one day I might find some too. Meantime, here I
stand, most certainly celibate, but emotionally crippled and incapable
of (or afraid of) the briefest human contact -- in case I give myself
away.
Me (the real one),
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
