<HEADLINE>Cricketer's daughter hurt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601259</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND and Derbyshire cricketer Phillip DeFreitas yesterday pulled
out of the last two days of his county's fixture against Essex at
Chelmsford, after his daughter was injured in a scalding accident.
Five-year-old Alex was scalded on Wednesday night at DeFreitas's home
in Bretby, near Burton on Trent.
Derbyshire County Cricket Club secretary Reg Taylor, said: ''Owing to
a serious accident to his daughter, Phillip has asked to be released
from this match and it is unlikely he will play in the remaining two
matches.'' He declined to give any further details of the accident.
A spokeswoman for Birmingham General Hospital, Ms Christine
Ransome-Wallis, said: ''Mr DeFreitas's daughter was brought in last
night as a result of an accident at home. Her injuries are not that
extensive and her burns are less than 40%. She is responding very well
to treatment, although she is still poorly.''
She said the 29-year-old cricketer and his wife Nicky had been by
their daughter's bedside throughout the night.
</TEXT>
