<HEADLINE>Persimmon shares tumble as results disappoint</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE UK housebuilding industry has been in a depressed state for much
of the year, with a number of major players such as Tarmac deciding to
withdraw from the market in the absence of any sustained upturn in
demand, writes NICOLA REEVES.
Persimmon is the latest company to add to the industry's woes with the
publication of disappointing interim results. Pre-tax profit in the six
months to 30 June was #10.2m down from #11.3m previously.
This despite the fact that completions rose to 1676. First half
turnover rose to #115m from #91m but the cost of sales rose to #97m from
#75m. However, the interim dividend is maintained at 3.0p.
The company was gloomy about its prospects in the immediate future --
a fact which had City analysts scurrying to downgrade their full-year
profit forecasts.
Interim profits were expected to be #13m and so analysts are now
expected to reduce their annual forecasts by around #4m to #21m. The
shares sank 17p to 175p.
Persimmon said that steadily worsening conditions had hit margins and
knocked 10% off first half profits. The company is cautious about
whether the traditional September pick-up in business will materialise.
Trading conditions have steadily deteriorated since May.
Building analysts at brokers Smith New Court highlight recent data
which suggests that the industry has entered the second half with a
large number of houses still to be sold.
This raises the spectre of fiercer competition, more incentives and
margin pressure as the fiscal year end approaches. The broker has
recently reduced its forecast for housing volumes -- by 19% in 1995 and
14% in 1996 -- on the back of continuing bad news from the market.
</TEXT>
