<HEADLINE>ScottishPower boost as electricity bids cleared</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISHPOWER is the second major Scottish company to have cleared a
key regulatory hurdle this summer in pursuit of a significant takeover
target.
Scottish &amp; Newcastle has now completed its acquisition of the Courage
brewing interests, while ScottishPower has a few fences to jump before
it lands its prize.
But during the period of uncertainty in the run-up to yesterday's
clearance of all three bids in the electricity sector, Manweb
shareholders have been voting with their feet, either selling their
shares in the market or accepting ScottishPower's terms.
With six weeks still to go the Glasgow-based company already speaks
for nearly 20% of Manweb's share capital. Once Manweb unveils its
package of shareholder sweeteners, ScottishPower can increase its offer
to win over enough shareholders to carry the day.
But the values placed on the shares of Eastern Group by Hanson (975p)
and South Western Electricity by the US electricity company Southern
(965p) in agreed deals suggest that the ScottishPower bid is in the
right ball park.
Manweb shares jumped 93p to 971p yesterday after Board of Trade
President Ian Lang ruled that there was no need for an inquiry by the
Monopolies Commission. This still leaves them below the 981[1/2]p value
of ScottishPower's shares and cash offer.
With so many potential takeover opportunities available in the sector
it is difficult to see why any intending predator would choose to mount
a rival bid for Manweb.
ScottishPower's move to acquire Manweb has enhanced its standing in
the stock market, where its shares, up 1[1/2]p to 340[1/2]p, were 23p
higher than they had been before the bid was announced in late July.
ScottishPower, which is one of the most efficient distributors in the
sector, has chosen its target well. Manweb is a high-cost operator,
which may account for its low standing among both its customers and its
shareholders.
The recent strength of ScottishPower's shares has been enhancing the
value of its shares and cash offer to the point where a higher offer may
not be necessary. If the bid succeeds there should be further mileage in
ScottishPower, which will become the major stock in the sector along
with National Power and PowerGen, the two quoted generators.
The stock market's vote of confidence is unusual at this early stage
in a contested bid and contrasts with the performance of Hanson, which
has now won control of Eastern. Its shares have shed 3[3/4]p to
216[1/2]p since its bid was unveiled.
There was of course no way that any of the planned electricity mergers
would have resulted in the creation of a monopoly situation and hence no
case for a reference to the Commission.
This was recognised by Mr Lang himself and the Office of Fair Trading,
but not by the electricity regulator, Professor Stephen Littlechild, who
wanted only the ScottishPower bid referred.
The professor has got so much wrong in recent months that there should
be little surprise that the authorities no longer listen to him.
Had his view prevailed this would have resulted in the absurd
situation where ScottishPower's bid for one regional electricity company
in England and Wales would have been blocked while a foreign company's
bid for another would have been cleared.
Like too many cogs in the bureaucratic machine Littlechild seems to
think that the time-consuming process of investigation is productive.
His main concern was that if ScottishPower took over Manweb it would
reduce by one the number of independent operators he could monitor. In
so fragmented a sector as electricity distribution this is hardly a
major concern.
Professor Littlechild has had a bad year. He has shown no sensitivity
in regulating a sector where his pronouncements can have a major
influence on the share prices of the companies which constitute it. He
should be considering whether his position as regulator is tenable after
yesterday's rebuff.
