<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rolls-Royce has a tough time despite profits hike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE,CITY EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601262</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Rolls-Royce, the aero-engine
and industrial power group, which prompted a furore earlier this year
with plans to close its East Kilbride plant and transfer the work to
Derby and Bristol, boosted first half profits 75% from #40m to #70m
before tax.
But the improvement is largely illusory as it includes #23m from
disposals -- a decline in research and development expenditure as
anticipated, and a first time three month contribution of #9m from
acquisition Allison, the US manufacturer of military engines.
Chairman Sir Ralph Robbins says that while the half-year results are
encouraging, they indicate that market conditions remain tough.
The rise in sales from #1500m to #1607m was almost all accounted for
by Allison, while sales from continuing operations were flat, with a
small increase in aerospace sales offsetting a decline in industrial
power sales.
Flat sales of spare parts is causing concern to analysts, given that
US rivals GE and Pratt &amp; Whitney have both said recently that sales of
spares are healthier. The interim dividend stays at 2p. The shares fell
15p to 175[1/2]p.
Rolls-Royce's order book has risen from #5900m to #6500m, but this
also reflects the inclusion of Allison. However, a further #1200m of
orders has been announced but is not yet included in the order book.
Sir Ralph does strike an optimistic note, saying that the company is
encouraged by recovering airline profitability and is well placed to
access this long-term growth market through its broad and competitive
product range.
0  In the meantime, the market is likely to take a cautious view on
prospects as the ''tough'' times continue.
</TEXT>
