<HEADLINE>Diaspora from Dunoon</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601263</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I ENJOYED Jack Maclean's pleasant article on the Cowal Games (August
28). I was brought up in Dunoon and so I was fascinated by this
sentence: ''When the Yanks left Gareloch, it looked serious for the
little Bute town.'' Maybe I'm being a bit pedantic, but Dunoon is in
Argyll and the Yanks left the Holy Loch.
I realise, of course, that the weather probably caused Jack Maclean to
spend some time in the beer tents and possibly become a little
disorientated -- Dunoon is of course a long way from Heraghty's.
He also mentioned that Dunoon ''has bristled for years with national
politicians'' and mentions several famous Grammar School FP/MPs.
Another, possibly less interesting FP would be Lord MacKay of (I think)
Ardbrecknish, former MP and recent supremo of the ill-fated Scottish
Conservative Party.
''A strange place, Dunoon'' -- and it's not only politicians! I make a
mere selection from my Dunoon contemporaries and near-contemporaries.
They include: a Dr Who, a senior Glasgow sheriff, a university professor
and vice-principal, a brain surgeon, a national theatre actor, a
television news presenter and interviewer, a QC, a chief
procurator-fiscal, two burglars, a nuclear physicist . . .
The list could go on, but I shall mention only one other Dunoon FP --
The Herald's own wine expert/financial
expert/reviewer/leader-writer/distinguished former academic, etc.
A man of many parts -- and one of those parts is that he was once
prospective Labour candidate for Hillhead in the days of the notorious
absentee Tory MP, T G D Galbraith. Maybe Robert has already put Jack
right.
Tom Donnelly,
28 Partickhill Road,
Glasgow.
