<HEADLINE>Rail to pay for road upgrading</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601264</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE article on rebuilding the Kingston Bridge was most interesting and
revealing (August 28). What if that bridge had crossed not the Clyde,
but the railway into Central Station? Who then would have been liable
for the #100m bill mentioned in your article?
By 1999 the Department of Transport aims to upgrade all main road
bridges to carry 44 tonne lorries and, where these bridges cross a
railway, they propose to charge the costs to BR/Railtrack, a sum of
#400m being thought likely.
When railways were being built it doubtless seemed reasonable that the
promoters should be required to provide adequately for any roads which
they cut. Can it be reasonable, however, that this obligation should
continue in perpetuity?
The lorries for which this upgrading is required are enormously
heavier than those which used the roads 40 years ago, let alone the
horses and carts using them when the railways were built. Such lorries
also compete for the most lucrative traffic.
Why then should Railtrack be required thus to subsidise its
competitors? Why should we, the fare-paying public, have to pay more so
that road hauliers may make bigger profits? What is being asked of these
hauliers as a contribution to an investment made exclusively for their
benefit.
Indeed, in consequence, it is all too likely that, when costs like
these are involved, some railways may well be closed; there would simply
not be enough revenue coming from them to justify such large
expenditure.
Already this attitude to charging for work affecting the crossing of a
road by a railway has deprived the people of Alloa of a restored
passenger rail service. The Department of (Road?) Transport is demanding
such expensive additional measures at every level crossing, all
chargeable to the railway, that the scheme has been shelved.
The Government says it wants to see more traffic going by rail, it
plays lip service to the general view that our roads are too busy and
that more building is not an answer. How then can it allow its
Department of Transport to behave thus?
The privatising of BR is in chaos simply because the Government will
not first attend to the level of the playing field on which road and
rail meet.
George A Davidson,
Redcroft,
Prieston Road,
Bridge of Weir.
</TEXT>
