<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Electricity takeovers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601272</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR LANG has acted with crisp dispatch in freeing all three existing
takeover bids for English Regional Electricity Companies of any
reference to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission. Irrelevant to the
main issue but of political interest, his move will do his political
stock some good in Scotland where a head of political steam has built up
in favour of ScottishPower's southern venture.
On a wider aspect there are other interesting themes. First, the
decision maintains the liberal stance of British business life by
imposing no barriers (no matter how disguised) to foreign ownership of
British companies, even those in sensitive areas of operation. Secondly,
Mr Lang has decided that the first cast of the RECs is not seen as their
permanent mould. The Government probably erred when it did not break up
British Telecom but it may have gone too far the other way in the
fragmentation of the electricity and water industries; and that mistake
is being reviewed by the markets. (Though that may not mean
ScottishPower is home and dry, since there is still time for a
counter-bid, even if it is hard to identify its possible origins.)  The
judgment overrides the opinion of the electricity industry's regulator,
but it merely confirms the earlier decision in respect of Trafalgar
House's original bid for Northern Electric. It should not be read as a
simple slap in the face for the regulator who has not had a good press
for his efforts in recent months. He has, however, already done well by
users of electricity by his response to Northern Electric's defence of
its independence. His reactions then may make it possible for the new
purchasers to offer no extra or special financial inducements to
customers of the companies involved but in fact Professor Littlechild
had already improved their position. Customers may still hope for more
but none should deny the improvement he won them in the wake of the
first (and so far unrepeated) Northern bid.
There may be circumstances in which it would be appropriate to refer a
future bid or merger proposal in the industry to the examination of the
MMC. Each proposal needs consideration on its merits -- as is the case
in every industry -- and the regulator will still be expected to advance
his recommendations. The fact remains that the Government's function is
itself to make such decisions, though it will sometimes need the MMC to
reject or endorse its view of the national interest, and avoid charges
of partisanship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A service in decline</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601273</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE National Health Service, or at least that part of it which still
qualifies for the description of a service as opposed to a business, has
always been difficult to assess. Anecdotal evidence is not as good as
properly conducted research and perception is no substitute for
objectivity. Nevertheless, the proportion of people in Britain who have
strong feelings on the subject is large and definite in its opinion. The
latest nationally conducted opinion poll for a firm of private medical
insurers shows that the general feeling is of a service in decline. This
will please the insurers who paid for the survey but it should not
please the rest of us. A remarkable 95% of those surveyed felt that more
funds should be allocated while, worryingly for the Labour Party, only
51% felt that a change of Government would make any difference. In
addition, there is a clearly defined impression that the NHS is now a
two-tier affair.
Moving from the general to the particular might give some reasons. The
situation at Ninewells Hospital in Dundee, where the management has been
forced to admit that it does not have sufficient beds for seriously ill
cancer and kidney patients, is exactly the stuff of which despairing
opinions are made. In that hospital patients have had to be boarded out
to other wards which in effect means shuffling problems around to the
utter detriment of the patients involved. Worse, the situation appears
to have existed since last May with only now a proper recognition being
given to its gravity. It is unarguable that the NHS needed to be
reformed. Some of the reforms were sensible and creative but many of
them appear to have been ill-conceived and executed without thought or
preparation. If the system was working properly the new hyper-efficient
management teams should have been able to spot problems coming and
remedy them before seriously ill patients had to be treated like pawns
on a board. This has not happened at Ninewells Hospital, nor has it
happened at many other centres. That is why, if anybody need ask,  much
of the reform of the NHS is regarded with such distaste.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Former Allied Provincial director fined #15,000</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER director of Glasgow-based stockbroker Allied Provincial
Securities -- who helped keep another company in which he was involved
afloat through the issue of #1m of unsecured loans from a private
client's portfolio -- has been fined #15,000 by the Securities and
Futures Authority.
Strathclyde Police's Fraud Squad is now making inquiries into the
matter, but it is understood that no criminal charges have yet been
brought against Michael Duncan, whose employment was terminated by
Allied Provincial as a result of the dealings.
Allied Provincial, which admitted its internal control systems had
been deficient, was itself fined #100,000 and severely reprimanded.
Mr Duncan, who had been with Allied Provincial for about 30 years, was
also expelled by the Securities and Futures Authority -- a move which
effectively ends his stockbroking career.
The loans, made over a period of nearly 2[1/2] years to East
Kilbride-based biotechnical equipment company Fern Developments, were
outside the scope of the client's discretionary agreement.
When Fern ultimately went into receivership in November 1993, the
client lost all of the money. During its last year, Fern, which was in
financial difficulty throughout the 2[1/2]-year period, was only kept
afloat by the client's loans.
A tribunal of the Securities and Futures Authority, which regulates
members of all of the organised City investment markets, commented that
Mr Duncan had ''deliberately kept the client in the dark''.
However, while acknowledging that Allied Provincial had not connived
in the actions of Mr Duncan, the tribunal believed he had been aided and
abetted by the inadequate supervision and systems of Allied Provincial.
Although Mr Duncan conveyed some information to the client, the
tribunal concluded that the client was not made aware of the exact
nature of the payments to Fern or the inherent risk.
Mr Duncan's reports to his client misleadingly recorded the loans as
purchases of Fern's shares.
The Securities and Futures Authority also believed Mr Duncan had kept
his fellow directors at Allied Provincial in the dark and had
deliberately concealed from them that Fern was paying a salary to his
wife.
Allied Provincial, which brought the situation to the attention of the
City watchdog when it was discovered in November 1993, accepted it had
allowed misleading valuation statements and movement reports to go to
the client and had failed to properly protect the client's portfolio.
The stockbroking firm has taken steps to compensate the client. Its
insurance company is currently in talks with the client's solicitor,
regarding a settlement.
Following its recent takeover by Greig Middleton's parent company,
King &amp; Shaxson, Allied Provincial has been merged with and is now
trading as Greig Middleton.
Iain Mackay, an executive director of the enlarged operation, stressed
that no other clients had been affected by the dealings. He added that
steps had been taken to make certain that a senior individual could not
override controls.
A police spokesman said last night: ''I can confirm that Strathclyde
Police are making inquiries into certain allegations made against a
former employee of Allied Provincial Securities Limited.''
Allied Provincial was ordered to pay #35,000 towards the Securities
and Futures Authority's costs. Mr Duncan will have to pay #5000 towards
costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Worm that can easily turn in the other direction</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601275</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DON'T suppose anyone should be surprised that Ian Lang has waved
through all three bids to take over privatised electricity companies.
There are in Scotland, after all, plenty derelict monuments to his dry
disbelief in interventionism.
This set of bids represented a test of whether the Tories, after the
battering they have taken about fat cats and leaking pipes, are prepared
to lift a finger to ensure that consumer interest is protected. Mr
Lang's refusal to refer any of the bids to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission could not, in that respect, have been more eloquent. They
aren't.
I would not recommend flag-waving on behalf of ScottishPower.
Now that the signal has been given that ownership of the utilities
will be determined through takeover battles, the worm could quite easily
turn in the other direction.
Anyone who has failed to call for the referral of the ScottishPower
bid for Manweb, along with the others, will not have a political leg to
stand on, if and when one of the Scottish companies is threatened with
takeover from outside.
The principle of insisting that each and every bid must be fully
scrutinised by the MMC, as a minimum safeguard for the public interest,
does not allow for opt-outs which say: ''We'll make an exception of this
one, because a Scottish company wants to take over an English one!''
Personally, I do not take an iota of patriotic satisfaction from the
fact that the value of ScottishPower increased by so many millions
yesterday or the prospect of ScottishPower shareholders coining in an
extra pile of bawbees, through the management's cleverness in
identifying the potential for a few hundred more people unemployed on
Merseyside.
As every observer has agreed, there is nothing in any of these
takeovers for the consumer, far less workforce. The predators -- Hanson
and Southern of Atlanta, as much as ScottishPower -- do not feel obliged
to give even a nod in these directions; so confident are they of the
Tories' shared disinterest in them.
Anyway, what is a ''Scottish company?'' More than four-fifths of the
shares in ScottishPower are owned outside Scotland while fewer than 10%
are held by customers and employees. I don't imagine that the ownership
structure of Manweb is all that different.
Yesterday's Mori poll in the Times must have made even grimmer reading
than usual for Mr Lang and his friends. After a summer that has not been
all roses for the Labour Party and has been pock-marked by Mr
Mawhinney's offensives, the Labour lead is virtually untouched.
Apart from the more general diagnosis, that folk are irredeemably sick
of them, one of the main reasons for this must be the constant reminders
-- through story after horror story about the water and electricity
companies -- of just what a confidence trick upon the public the whole
privatisation programme has been.
The last claim on its behalf that the Tories cling to is that it has
delivered massive price cuts to the consumer. However, the more you look
at the evidence -- and perhaps we should have done so more closely
before now -- the thinner that boast becomes.
Figures provided by the House of Commons Library show that the average
household cost of electricity, based on the Retail Price Index, has
increased by 2.1% since privatisation. When I pointed this out recently,
I received a sniffy letter from the Electricity Association -- which
represents the privatised companies -- saying that it was only true if
one included Scotland, Northern Ireland, and VAT. I am happy to make
that clear, on behalf of Scottish consumers who pay VAT!
The other big Tory lie which we don't nail often enough was summed up
in an oft-repeated jibe from John Major in the House of Commons:
''Opposition members still relish the day when it cost the taxpayer #50m
a week to subsidise utilities so that Ministers could run them
inefficiently.''
In fact, telecoms, gas, and electricity all made consistently high
proifts for the Treasury before privatisation -- at a rate not matched
by the tax now taken from their privatised replacements. Mr Major does
not think twice, however, about falsely maligning these great industries
and the people who gave their working lives to make them successful.
If the English and Welsh water authorities had been allowed to charge
at the current rates -- up 50% since privatisation -- they would have
made a profit for the taxpayer too!
The battle to keep Scottish water in public ownership produced one of
the most important victories in recent years. Of course, as George
Robertson was pointing out this week, the structure is intended for
privatisation with the attendant price increases and share options. But
they certainly aren't going to manage that, this side of a General
Election.
When the other utilities, the family silver has been sold and is now
in the process of being resold. The consumer's defence will have to be
through regulation rather than ownership. But, as the takeover bidders
might note, there is plenty potential in that system for redressing the
abuses of privatised greed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ladbroke's earnings rise 23% to #56.5m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601276</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LADBROKE does not expect fully to complete its sale of Texas Homecare
for another year because of a dispute with the buyer, J Sainsbury, over
the final accounts of the DIY retailing business.
It relates to the accounting treatment of stocks, debtors and
creditors, which Ladbroke finance director Brian Wallace said was an
accountants' ''nightmare''.
Ladbroke has received the basic consideration of #290m, so can afford
to wait for the matter to be settled by arbitration. Mr Wallace
commented: ''We would like to increase the price and they would like to
reduce it. There is a lot of money involved.''
He was speaking on publication of Ladbroke's figures for the six
months to June, which show the impact of the National Lottery on the
betting activities.
Even so, a strong performance by Hilton International hotels boosted
group profits by 23% to #56.5m before exceptionals. The interim dividend
is pegged at 2.4p to improve cover.
Hotels raised operating profits by 35% to #65.8m but the division's
boss, Tommaso Zanzotto, is to step down next year.
Ladbroke chief executive Peter George said there had been no
disagreements, and no compensation for loss of office would be paid.
Rather, the role of chief executive of hotels had evolved differently to
Mr Zanzotto's expectations.
Mr Zanzotto himself said his job at Ladbroke, which began some 18
months ago, had essentially been completed. There has been some surprise
by analysts that Ladbroke has not made more acquisitions of hotels,
though it does have plans for more Hiltons.
In the first half, hotels benefited from firmer room rates and higher
occupancy. This rose from 67% to 74% in the UK, with London particularly
strong. Outside the metropolis there was an improvement of eight
percentage points.
Despite being in the final stages of a court case against the
separately owned Hilton chain in the US, the group is still hoping for a
marketing link between the two chains.
Operating profits of Vernons pools were more than halved to #2.7m,
while racing and casinos were down almost a quarter at #37.4m.
Ladbroke says it is not whingeing in the face of competition from the
lottery, but argues that there is not a level playing field because
liberalisation of the betting rules has not come through as expected.
It wants the Government to reduce betting duty and allow amusement
machines with prizes in betting shops.
Racing is being hit particularly by scratch cards and the good
weather, which has reduced the number of horses racing because of the
hard ground.
In addition, Sunday racing has been bad news for betting shops because
punters have flocked to the courses rather than their local betting
shops.
Less understandable was a sharp fall in credit betting. This involves
a relatively small number of big betting punters and they have
apparently found betting opportunities less interesting.
Ladbroke has made 300 redundancies but the problems facing betting are
clearly not susceptible to quick solutions. The group has been cheered
by the approval it has received from the Gaming Board for more casinos,
saying this will stand it in good stead for new licences in America.
There are rumours here that it is interested in buying Rank casinos
from Rank. Ladbroke shares gained 3p to 167p, where they look high
enough for the time being.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New alliance opens window of opportunity for television company. Flextech takes 20% stake in STV</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601277</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Television has announced a strategic alliance with the
US-owned cable television giant Flextech to secure a niche in the
growing market for cable and satellite television.
Flextech will acquire a 20% stake in STV for #64m with the express
approval of the Glasgow-based broadcaster's main shareholder, the Mirror
Group, which will be pushed into second place when the deal goes
through.
Flextech will pay #28m in cash and transfer to STV its 20% stake in
HTV, the Wales and West of England independent television station, which
is worth a further #36m.
Finally, Flextech and its associates will purchase #2.3m of STV
library material, including the Taggart series, and commission at least
#6m of new programmes from STV over the next three years.
This sophisticated piece of financial engineering, which gives
Flextech two seats on the STV board, must be approved by an
extraordinary meeting of STV shareholders on September 28.
The alliance with Flextech opens a vast window of opportunity for STV
to sell programmes to cable and satellite television broadcasters
associated with its new partner.
It also positions STV nicely to make a possible bid for HTV -- a move
which the Scottish company is believed to have considered in the past.
HTV shares rose 13[1/2]p to 219p yesterday.
''This is a very innovative and imaginative move,'' said Bill McCall,
an analyst with broker Tilney in Edinburgh.
He praised STV for seeing a coming decline in its traditional
television business and taking a bold step to keep ahead of the game.
The alliance with Flextech has already led STV into talks on
programme-making for two Flextech associates -- Hallmark Entertainments,
a US film production company, and Telewest, a cable network which
reaches 547,000 homes in central Scotland.
Flextech has equity stakes in eight UK cable television stations and
manages a further four. It also supplies programmes to several channels
of the BSkyB satellite television group.
The acquisition of a stake in HTV makes STV the fourth-largest
independent television company in the UK after Carlton, Granada and MAI,
and boosts its strength in programme-making and distribution.
The Scottish station already owns 20% of the breakfast television
channel GMTV, and has a 5% stake in the television news organisation
ITN.
''Through the strategic alliance with Flextech we enter promising new
markets in association with some of the biggest international media
groups,'' said STV managing director Gus McDonald.
A move into cable and satellite television is essential to secure
STV's potential for growth in an increasingly competitive market.
The number of households with cable or satellite television is
increasing rapidly, and digital television and the launch of a fifth
terrestrial channel will soon bring more competition on the air waves.
Nevertheless, Mr McDonald said: ''We see ITV audiences holding up
pretty robustly until the end of the century.''
He said the alliance with Flextech would certainly lead to greater
investment in programme production, on which STV spent #40m last year.
But the chief executive said future revenue growth was likely to be
steady rather than spectacular.
STV made pre-tax profits of #7.4m during the first six months of this
year on turnover of #48.9m.
Flextech, which is still investing heavily to build up its UK
operations, made a #7.9m loss on turnover of #15.2m.
Flextech chief executive Roger Luard described the purchase of a 20%
stake in STV as an ''important step'' in his group's expansion into
terrestrial broadcasting and programme-making.
Flextech will buy just over 12 million newly-issued STV shares at 530p
each. This price takes into account the value of the HTV shares and
represents a 14% premium on STV's closing price of 205p on August 29.
STV shares rose 17p to 499p yesterday on news of the alliance with
Flextech, which was up 3p at 438p.
Flextech will become STV's largest shareholder, displacing the Mirror
Group, whose 20% stake will be reduced to 16% with the issue of new
shares.
The Mirror Group was prevented from increasing its stake in STV under
the Government's new media ownership rules, published earlier this year,
and now appears resigned to playing a backseat role on the television
station.
But it still sees STV fitting into its overall media strategy and gets
a seat on the board for the first time. Mirror Group chief executive
David Montgomery will become a non-executive director.
Roger Luard and Adam Singer, the president of Flextech's main US
shareholder Telecommunications International Inc, will also become
non-executive directors of STV, giving up their present seats on the HTV
board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S little wonder that no-one will buy the West Coast rail line as
long as the Government thinks that railways should make a profit.
Three weeks ago I had to go to Aberdeen to collect a car for my son,
and I chose to go by rail. The fare from Johnstone, one way, was #32.50.
It was an enjoyable trip, with excellent service on board, but after
putting #10 worth of petrol into my car (the tank was empty) I drove
home in much the same time and realised that I could have carried three
others with me!
There is absolutely no way that people will move from road to rail
under the present system. It can only be more cars and roads all the
way.
Iain Morrison,
19 Greenhill Crescent,
Elderslie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
