<RECORDNO>976601280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF we were hoping that John Macleod (August 29) might actually take
time off from his usual anti-gay ranting to practise a little Christian
charity when it came to Michael Barrymore, we were obviously mistaken.
The reality is that Macleod is not a Christian, but is a man troubled
with Christian feelings and now driven to resolve them by assuming
Christian identity: unfortunately for us gay men (and, I suspect, for
God) he happens to have adopted a particularly narrow-minded, vicious
Christian identity and insists on flaunting it in public.
''Unnatural, dangerous, and evil?'' More a description of your
columnist, I fear, than a description of the many perfectly happy,
stable, and loving gay men and lesbians I encounter in my work.
Michael Barrymore is welcome to join us, if that's where his heart
truly feels at rest.
Dominic d'Angelo,
Editor, Gay Scotland,
58a Broughton Street,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sympathy from a heterosexual viewpoint</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MUCH as I admire the talent and literary style of John Macleod, I must
take exception to his comments on the homosexual scene (August 29). I
wonder if he writes at times with tongue in cheek to deliberately
stimulate discussion. My gut feeling, however, is that this is not the
case in this article.
Being heterosexual myself, I can only empathise with and hopefully
understand those who are homosexual whether they be lesbian females or
gay males.
John Macleod's assertions that homosexuality is simply a lifestyle and
a concept of modern times are erroneous. It is now accepted that between
5-10% of the population are homosexual, and that both our sex and our
sexual traits are predetermined prior to birth.
In earlier times homosexuals were grossly misunderstood, and were
hounded and persecuted by society in general. It is hardly surprising
therefore that they endeavoured to hide their identity as far as
possible, and this explains why in pre-twentieth century examples they
were hard to find.
John Macleod maintains that the homosexual life is unnatural,
dangerous, and evil, referring obviously to the prevalence of Aids among
the gay community. Recent world Health Organisation figures have shown,
however, that Aids is every bit as prevalent among heterosexuals, and
that promiscuity in either group is the overrriding cause.
The amount of publicity recently extended to homosexuals, both on the
media and by street parades of gay rights protesters, has caused much
righteous indignation and criticism. But it is apparent that they have
been conducted to highlight the rights of the gay community, and to
accord them the dignity, tolerance, and justice they merit.
For John Macleod to sit in judgment is both patronising and
sanctimonious, particularly for one who is a staunch member of the
Christian Church, which preaches, as its base, tolerance and
understanding, irrespective of sex, race, creed, or sexual proclivity.
For homosexuals to have sexual drive and desire for partners of
similar persuasion is surely not sinful or degrading, no matter how
alien it may appear to us heterosexuals. They should no longer be
pilloried or ostracised, but should be allowed to pursue their lifestyle
predetermined before birth, as long as this is carried out in the
dignity of their own homes and without courting publicity.
Dr John M Reid,
44 Eaglesham Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Reminiscence of the APT</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601282</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MURRAY HUGHES is, I think, wrong or over-brief on a couple of points
about the Advanced Passenger Train (August 25).
The abortive attempts to make an APT cover the whole distance between
Glasgow and London were surely not in 1981 but during the Arctic
conditions of January, 1982. They were not the only occasions on which
the APT carried fare-paying passengers. I remember travelling on it from
Euston to Glasgow in 1983 or 1984; very comfortable, but rather
claustrophobic, like travelling inside a high-speed caterpillar.
These latter-day runs do however seem to have been experimental and
unscheduled; I telephoned my wife from Euston to say I was travelling up
on the 4.30pm, only for her to be advised by Central Station, when she
asked them for the arrival time, that no such train existed.
Sebastian Robinson,
7 Kirklee Gardens,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>There must be a word for rage in the heather</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE hear of a great linguistic debate which took place in a BBC radio
studio somewhere in the Gaidhealtacht. A lady presenter is researching
some detail for one of the subjects which will be raised in a
forthcoming show.
The subject is the New Orgasm, which she had been reading about in one
of those glossy women's magazines. There is a slight problem. She cannot
be sure what is the correct Gaelic word for orgasm.
We do not know what this says about our Gaelic cousins, but no-one in
the radio station is entirely sure what is the Gaelic for orgasm. They
have to take recourse to Maclennan's Gaelic Dictionary where they find
the word is fraoch-feirge. Which translates literally as
''heather-rage''.
Not a single person, despite their deep knowledge of Gaelic, heather,
and life in general, can see where the bonny purple or white plant comes
into it. Nor the rage either.
Luckily there is an alternative Gaelic word for orgasm. It is deine
which translates literally as keenness or eagerness.
Out of this world
WE note that Bonnybridge's status as Scotland's capital of UFO
sightings is under challenge from Fort William.
The Lochaber News reports strange goings-on under the heading ''UFO
aliens to blame in power struggle?'' and tells us that ''alien
interference has not been ruled out following a massive power failure in
Lochaber''.
It was all down to an ''orange-coloured, cigar-shaped UFO'' which was
sighted over the Isle of Lewis at exactly the same time as the lights
were going out in Lochaber. A retired hydro electric board man
speculated that the aliens were tapping the power from the grid to
assist in their take-off.
Housewives in Fort William reported strange experiences: ''Without
warning, doors fell off cupboards and ashtrays and saucers performed
complete unaided revolutions.'' The Lochaber News quotes locals speaking
of ''strange droning noises, whirrings, and hummings''.
How, we ask, is this different from your average night in Fort
William.
Idiot proof
A COPY of a job application form for Clydebank College crosses our
desk. We have to commend the college for keeping things simple on this
form.
Fearing that some of these questions may cause confusion by being a
touch complicated for some applicants, Clydebank has supplied some handy
notes of guidance to explain the bigger words and generally clear things
up.
Question one is entitled ''Sex'' and asks if the applicant is male or
female. The point of this question, it is explained in the notes, is to
''determine the sex of each job applicant''.
Question two is headed ''Marital Status'' and asks applicants to
answer yes or no to the question: ''Are you married?'' This question,
the guidance notes inform us, is ''designed to establish whether or not
job applicants are married''.
Question five is headed ''Ethnic Origin: Are You White?'' The answer
is yes or no. The notes for applicants explains that this question
''establishes the number of job applicants who are white and who are not
white''.
Direct question
THE annual meeting of minds between Scotland's Euro MPs and the
Scottish churches was held recently in Dunblane.
Lothian MEP David Martin was making the point that no-one could
predict the number of countries that would be within the European Union,
but the certainty was that membership of the European Union will
increase. He speculated to the churchmen that there might even be an
application from the Vatican.
This didn't raise an eyebrow from the assembled clergy but it prompted
Ken Collins, MEP for Strathclyde East, to pass Mr Martin a note saying:
''I thought one of the criteria for entry into the European Union was
that the country in question had to have direct elections.''
Disco inferno
AN invitation arrives in a blood-stained envelope, inviting us to the
opening of Terror Under The Arches. This is an entertainment which can
be found in Midland Street, Glasgow, in a complex of dark, disused
railway arches.
Brought to you by the same people who created Alien War, a ''leisure
experience'' which consisted of being chased around dark tunnels by a
very authentic-looking big scary beastie, Terror Under The Arches
promises similar delights, except that this time the tunnels are
occupied by ''real people -- like serial killers''.
Thrill-seeking punters are guided around by a cowled monk, who is
presumably on hand to offer the last rites to victims. It is all pretty
scary. But not entirely unlike how it used to be in the 1960s when the
arches housed a well-known Glasgow disco called The Cave. Except for the
monks.
Above the rim
EAST Lothian District Council is so proud of its public loos that it
has issued excerpts of the comments left in the visitors' books which
they keep in their award-winning conveniences. One D McIngle of Oban
says of the North Berwick facility: ''Spent last night in Edinburgh
Hilton, toilets well-kept but not in this class.''
J Brunton of Edinburgh was moved to say: ''The standard of
civilisation and concern for public health on the part of a local
authority can be judged by the standard of its public toilets, thus East
Lothian District Council rates most highly (if not the highest in
Scotland).''
S McShane of Haddington writes of the loos in his or her home town:
''The toilets are lovely and clean. I will use them now, as I didn't
before.'' And Davina Coyle of Musselburgh says of the Honest Toun's
toilets: ''I recommend to everybody and bring all my friends.'' Makes a
change from going down the pub.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lilith, Adam House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN theory, the mythological Lilith offers marvellous opportunities for
the female dancer to cut loose in a frenzy of sexuality and unbridled
wickedness. Stories vary, but basically Lilith was Adam's first (highly
prolific) wife cast out by god from paradise becoming subsequently an
uncontrolled she-demon personifying predatory lust, relentless
infanticide, and all manner of midnight cruelty. Strong stuff.
Sadly, across recent Fringes Lilith has prompted some of the vilest
(most self-indulgent) choreography ever to scuff a stage. This version
is no exception. What exquisite torture there is in watching Avis von
Herder's skimpy leotard become an invisible thong between her writhing
buttocks. Rock-bottom banality follows, however, when choreographer
William Louther pitches Lilith as the essence of today's female
executive . . . Some feeble prancing in a suit, coupled with frantic
clutchings of a talismanic clipboard represent the vengeful business
fiend before -- inevitably -- clothes scatter everywhere and Lilith and
her leotard return to the thrustings and squirmings that sorely try its
elasticity and the onlooker's patience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Speechless, Acoustic Music Centre,</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601285</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SILENCE is not necessarily the same as saying nothing. For, as a
lengthy programme note reveals, the Japanese have a tradition of
non-verbal communication. Body language -- even the quality of the
silence -- is regularly used to convey a wealth of meaning. Not so
elsewhere in the world, and it is this tension between the implicit and
the outspoken which concerns choreographer Setsuko Usui.
In Speechless, four women in palest pink and white -- backed by a
sound score that moves between traditional Japanese flute-ings and a
kind of computerised drone -- express this difference in cultures
through dance that is attractive if not exactly riveting or clear cut.
The piece meanders somewhat and is certainly too long for what it has to
say -- the implication here is that less would have been more in the
end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A word</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601286</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
. . . in your ear, Michael. Punishment. Party conference time is
drawing near, as I'm sure you have not forgotten. Now, just close your
eyes and listen to the baying of those delegates. Red meat is what they
need, lots of it and the redder the better. Pity about our party colours
being blue. Somehow we've always seen the Tories as being a party red in
tooth and claw. It's natural.
Anyway, back to the subject in hand. You've been doing well on the
punishment front. Good, sensitive interviews on crime etc, though it's a
pity the sensitive caring bit got into the tabloids where they don't
tend to understand that sort of thing. Next time you're tempted to
spread it about a bit ask Gerry Warner's advice. Chap knows all about
sensitivity, or so he says. The point is, Michael, you've got to
concentrate on crime and punishment for the next couple of months
because it's just about all we've got. Look at the alternatives. The
police are dizzy with reform and the judges are just as dizzy, but
dangerous when roused. Water and the NHS are best avoided. It has to be
crime and punishment.  So, what are you going to put into Operation
Dostoevsky? Random drug testing in prisons is a good idea. Everybody
says that drug-taking in the prison population is getting out of hand.
Testing for drugs on a random basis is the best way of getting a good
understanding of what is going on. It also makes it easier to put
remedial plans into place when you've got an accurate idea of the
dimensions of the problem. Unfortunately, more is needed. Red meat is
fine for the party, even if it was a touch Middle Eastern to talk about
the punishment fitting the crime. But concerned voters need something a
bit more intelligent.
Involving the reformers is sensible. It's part of the promise to
listen, but remember that people like listeners only if they're prepared
to act on what they've been told. Give the delegates a good show at the
conference. Wave whips, manacles, stocks, anything you like at them. But
moderate it for everyone else. And remember, anyone who gets the balance
of punishment and rehabilitation right for the voters will inherit the
Kingdom of Heaven, politically speaking, that is.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Secrets of the Celtic Heart, Calton Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601287</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRIAN Mallon looks and sounds surprisingly like Richard Burton, and
the comparison is apt because he reads from Dylan Thomas with the same
depth and authenticity. But Mallon is capable of more. He recites his
own work, has translated medieval bardic poetry and things in Welsh.
Secrets of the Celtic Heart takes snatches of poetry from Taliesin to
the present and knits it together to tell a kind of non-narrative story.
Swinging from child-like glee to sonorous melancholy, Mallon maps out
the Celtic Heart, taking Wales to be its oldest and most consistent
home.
There are no folk cliches here. The themes are familiar, but the
presentation is original and superbly carried off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>IDX, St Bride's Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601288</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UH-OH . . . it's black bra and pantie-girdle time on the dance floor.
When in doubt -- and there's much to doubt in this piece from Carlson
Dance -- get the kit off. The audience will either look away in
embarrassment or ogle to pass the time. Either way they won't notice the
lack of anything resembling choreography.
The knee-pads and the trainers -- which make the legs of all three
girls look like unvarnished doorposts -- do suggest there might be some
joined-up action, or dance, as we like to call it. No fear. There's too
much red lippy to apply, too many other identities -- ie costumes -- to
climb in and out of, and some utterly ridiculous pratting around with
large pink-fur fabric phallic pouffees to waste time on anything but a
smidgeon of bimbo Eurocrash-ette.
Self-indulgently mediocre, with not even the wit to be bad enough to
achieve a certain kind of cult folly. Put the clothes back on and learn
some steps is my personal advice to this lot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hamlet, Greyfriars Kirkhouse</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALEXANDER LINKLATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SKILFULLY editing the play down to two hours and nine characters, this
young company still manages to give it a broad scope in the limited
space. The production is a good lesson in how to gun through Shakespeare
hard and fast without losing meaning or impact.
Paul Curran makes a believable Hamlet as far as shrewdness and
manipulation go, and it is a relief not to have to suffer any emotional
overkill. But scenes with the ghost and Gertrude consequently lack a
focus of feeling.
The rest of the cast members head in the opposite direction, sometimes
losing thought in the expression of furious extremes. But overall they
make impressive use of their spare resources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Specific Gravity/Heroides 12, St Bride's Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601290</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN the set -- a kind of mythic Greek tepee-come-shrine -- slewed to
one side and collapsed, Jonathan Burnett did not flinch. He carried on.
For that, anyway, well done.
As for Heroides 12 -- that is not well done, and having seen Burnett
appeal elsewhere in other works, one could wish it hadn't been done at
all. The text of Medea's fraught career comes at us first in a muckle
drench of impenetrable Sco-ats, then in Latin . . . meanwhile Burnett
has fluffed off his narrator's tunic to dawn the scarlet of Medea's
tragic drag. The audience sat, transfixed, like doomed and blinded
rabbits.
They were finished off by Specific Gravity a solo evocation of
relative densities. Sadly Emily Shaw seemed leaden throughout. Nick
Rothswell's live electronic music continued unphased by any of this. I
do hope this isn't the shape of future moves for Vestries-Cassiel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Carol Kidd/Annie Ross, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601291</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH only a couple of exceptions, Wednesday night's show by Scotland's
premiere jazz vocalist, Carol Kidd, was perfection. Or as near as
dammit. Accompanied by a highly polished trio led by pianist David
Newton (on sparkling, if somewhat passionless form), she was -- as ever
-- most affecting on the ballads. Her I Can't Get Started was utterly
ravishing while every note of This Love of Mine (a new addition to the
Kidd repertoire) was worth hanging on to.
Annie Ross also impressed most with slower numbers like the haunting
Where Do You Start, and the laid-back blues To Hell With Love -- a
number whose cynical lyrics were perfecly suited to her lived-in voice.
* Sponsored by Crabbie's Green Ginger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lord of the Flies, The Other Place, Stratford</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAROLE WODDIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601292</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN community theatre has ceased to be fashionable suddenly it's all
the rage at the RSC. Last summer, local Stratford townspeople were
coralled into employment in Nigel Williams's promenading Country Dancing
-- some also appear on the stage this season in Peter Hall's Julius
Caesar.
At The Pit in the Barbican, Wedekind's Spring Awakening has a cast
mostly taken by school-age teenagers and in Stratford, during the summer
holidays, Williams's fine adaptation of William Golding's terrifying
allegory on the veneer of ''civilisation'' thinly hiding the true nature
of the typical English (public) schoolboy has been played by a cast of
boys from local Stratford and Midland schools.
For my money it's by far the most successful experiment yet. But
whereas in Spring Awakening, youthful ardour, it seemed to me, didn't
quite make up for the play's technical demands (a minority view,
clearly, since many of my colleagues have dubbed it the hit of the
year), in the Golding, inexperience and a certain anarchic roughness fit
the story's atmosphere like a glove.
Director Elijah Moshinsky too has done a brilliant job harnessing the
energies of his young cast with a combination of spontaneity and
professionalism while there are some remarkable performances from his
leading characters. Marc Elliott's terrifying choir prefect Jack is
every inch an embryonic tyrant in the making, while Daniel Brocklebank's
quietly decent Ralph and Christopher Hudson's grammar school outsider,
the bespectacled Piggy, are effectingly helpless young democrats swamped
before the clever orchestration of Jack's popular dictatorship.
* Lord of the Flies runs at TOP to September 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Graduate Show, Graduate Gallery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601293</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS initiative is to be congratulated. Two recent Edinburgh graduates
have organised a show of work by 25 graduates from Glasgow, Dundee,
Aberdeen and Edinburgh in empty premises at 45 Frederick Street; a
central location if ever there was one.
The work is uneven, with too many deeply average, even awful, pictures
but there is also some really good stuff which I recognise from the
degree shows: Jennifer Whyte's black nudes, Georgina O'Neil's witty
animal screenprints, Cock a Hoop and Rawhide, Lindsay Crowe's sensitive
shadowy drawings of people and horses.
I particularly admired Sharon Ramsay's spirery street scenes, like
typographical Giacometti, and Tove Hirth's slender, reductive sculptural
figures.
The organisers have also commissioned window installations from Louise
Taylor and Jane Watt for the 40ft glass frontage. There are plenty of
empty shops in Edinburgh. Others could well copy this bright idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601294</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU are doubtless fed up with Ireland now. So is Ireland. When Mr
Dedalus shouted ''In that case, no God for Ireland!'' he was speaking
not just about God, but about Ireland. James Joyce was once asked by
that dreadful old terrorist, Eamon de Valera, to return to his old
island and he turned it down, for Joyce knew that Ireland eats its
young. And it has done so for centuries. The last quarter century saw
that as well, rather spectacularly.
There is something especially odd about going through, say, Newry, on
the border, and encountering burnt-out shops, their own shops, where
their own people live, and side by side some of the best schools in the
entire British isles, the magnificent gardens blooming, the literary
societies, the neo-para-military clubs.
I have been back to Ireland several times since the Peace Process, the
Ceasefire. I was in Belfast seconds from the decision of the Sinn Fein
to announce an end to the gunfire. And a few months later I found myself
again in Northern Ireland, in Belfast and Derry and Armagh city and just
across the border in Donegal.
I was in Donegal when the hunger strikes were on and let me tell you a
little about the hunger strikes. They were truly tragic . . .
Everybody remembers Bobby Sands; few remember Francis Hughes, Joe
McDonnell, Ray McCreesh, Patsy O'Hara . . . there were 10 who died.
Virtually no British observer understood the deaths at all, for they did
not know of the long, sad history of Ireland, when to shame a neighbour
an Irishman would starve to death upon his neighbour's doorstep.
A strange race the Irish, the Celts themselves. Had the Brits known of
this odd and self-wounding history they would have understood the hunger
strikes more and obviated the terrible tragedies of it -- and perhaps
the terrible years of conflict.
But what has characterised the years of this war has been the
unmistakable colonialism which the British would not dare to enact
anywhere else in the world. Mind, the United Kingdom has had its work
cut out: it has had a peculiar group of rather absurd Royalists jouking
about with banners and every sort of imperialist nonsense which the
British populace deserted 30 years ago.
Mainland Britain finds the Northern Irish Loyalists rather ludicrous
and an embarrassment. It finds their fervour especially in their
religion, positively surreal. It finds the Protestant settler community
not only out of synch' but rather vulgar in its simple bigotry. Yet it,
understandably, finds a slight slice of sympathy with the Orange masses,
for the Irish Free State was driven to a peasant state, led by a
clerical hierarchy with the collusion of a humourless Irish-American
with but scant regard for the wild streak of Celtic romance.
Yet the argument from the Republic has never been one to live with. W
B Yeats said it many years ago, when a senator in the Irish Republic. He
argued that those in the north must remain entitled to the rights they
enjoyed under British rule and if they were subjected to the newly
established, Roman Catholic-based laws there would be ''a wedge driven
into the heart of this nation''.
The faults lay many against the de Valerian oligarchy. We do not like
the laager mentality which we perceive in the Protestant community of
Northern Ireland: there is much to be shocked at in the Irish Republic's
theocracy, which continues in an aged, stuttering, and rather
Alzheimer-ish way. But this is not our island. The British have got to
put bags of gold into this island because it is simple decency to do so
to an island we have abused for so long. But keep out of the argument.
This is an argument between brothers, and, like brothers, they are
entitled to turn on those who try to intervene.
British journalists and politicians and other observers should know a
little bit more about the culture of this land across from us. When the
children of both communities start to think about their Irishness more,
and not in a tribal way, when the little girls of both sides take up
Irish Dancing, and the boys play Gaelic football and hurling, and the
flute bands play with the bodhran, when the Irish family kisses and
makes up, you will find a United Ireland, the way it should be.
And don't give me the old oil about either side delivering their
weapons. Ireland is an agricultural country rooted in dissent and
despair. There are guns everywhere, just as there is in deepest
Aberdeenshire. A farmer without a gun: an Irishman without a past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Witches and warlocks of the magic box</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601295</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SMALL pleasures: is it a function of the ageing process that more and
more of them are negative ones? While I was in Portugal last week (which
was a big pleasure) Janet Street-Porter gave the James MacTaggart
Memorial Lecture at the Edinburgh Television Festival, and when I read
the excited reports of her speech I felt simply contented. What bliss, I
thought, not to have to be there.
Every year, in fact, I feel grateful that life and work no longer
require me to attend the Edinburgh Television Festival. This annual
conventicle of the witches and warlocks of the magic box was once
described by one of its more pragmatic delegates as ''six days of
oblivion drinking and power bonking'', but in the late seventies and
early eighties, when I was writing about the tele-fest for first the
Scotsman and then The Herald, I didn't get any of that; just a serious
dose of tedium as the broadcasters pumped iron into their egos and their
obsessions, and an occasional adrenaline-rush to the typewriter as they
came up with a big idea.
The big idea was sometimes provided by the James MacTaggart Memorial
Lecture. I remember Ted Turner of CNN came in person to share his dream
(and our nightmare) of a round-the-clock international news service,
bringing the global village into our cable-stitched sitting rooms in
bite-sized reportage. But not this year; I've read every available
digest of Janet Street-Porter's speech, and its big idea as selected by
the press is spectacularly unoriginal.
Male, middle-aged, and middle-class -- this is her profile of the
executive sheikhs who are dragging the muse of British television into a
desert of low ratings and impoverished creativity. It was ever thus. Ms
Street-Porter, who is not so very much younger than I despite her
nostalgia for Johnny Rotten and the Pet Shop Boys, must surely remember
the days when Kenith Trodd and Dennis Potter regularly charged the
medium with the same Masonic tendency. And Trodd and Potter weren't even
women.
Still, it's the silly season -- or it was before the Bosnian Serbs
fired a shell too many -- and the Street-Porter peroration heavily
engaged the weekend press, who encouraged the suits to fight back. There
were lots of scoffs about the credentials which gave authority to
Janet's experience of the grassroots viewer ('My sister works in
Sainsbury's'') and many waspish remarks about her designer house and
membership of the Groucho Club. The Sunday Telegraph even devoted a
half-page editorial to taking her apart, along with the James MacTaggart
Memorial Lecture, declaring its intention to ignore ''the tangential
question -- who was, or is, James MacTaggart?''
At this point my disreputable enjoyment of its diverting ribbing was
interrupted by a flinch. Loyalty to my old trade of television
criticism, and by association to the medium itself, and by local
association to one of its most gifted practitioners, was affronted. So
was my affection for the English language. A memorial lecture is by
definition dedicated to the memory of someone who is dead. The
editorial's ''who was, or is, James MacTaggart'', which it amusingly
repeated, was either a joke in poor taste or a solecism.
But at least the Sunday Telegraph was accurate with the name of the
Scottish director, producer, and occasional writer whom television
honours most for his stewardship of the Wednesday Play, especially the
1965 season which included Dennis Potter's debut, David Mercer's And Did
Those Feet? and Nell Dunn's Up the Junction.
During those fertile years of original television drama James
MacTaggart pushed back the frontiers of innovation. He died suddenly in
1974, when he was only 48. His widow, Anne Donaldson, was for many years
the Glasgow Herald's London news editor and theatre critic; which makes
it all the more shaming that Saturday's edition of this newspaper thrice
gave his surname a Mc instead of a Mac.
If MacTaggart's preferences in television drama were male,
middle-aged, and middle-class then let's have more of them, even if the
Sunday Telegraph assumes his legacy is confined to the self-regarding
introspection of the Edinburgh Television Festival. ''What could be more
middle-class'', it enquired of Janet Street-Porter, ''than delivering a
pompously named lecture and having it reproduced in both the Guardian
and the Independent?'' Adding, with supercilious malevolence, ''The only
thing plebeian about her, apart from her tastes, are her vowels. We
suspect that Sainsbury's people would not like their children to grow up
speaking like that either.''
Probably not. Sainsbury's, as every shopper knows, is the West End of
the supermarket industry, which makes nonsense of the Sunday Telegraph's
sneer. But if you dish it out, Janet, you've got to take it. I'm less
intrigued by her stale complaint about the hegemony of the three Ms than
I am by some statistics about broadcasting women which, by comparison,
were under-reported. Despite the connection.
At another of the sessions I was glad I didn't have to attend
delegates were told that 70% of women in broadcasting were childless, as
against 34% of men. I'm happy, however, to ponder these figures, along
with those which showed that 53% of women over 40 had no children,
including most of the top executives (Liz Forgan, head of BBC Radio,
Denise O'Donaghue, founder of the independent company Hat Trick, Dawn
Airey, Channel 4's head of entertainment and arts, and -- ahem -- Janet
Street-Porter, voice of the woman in the check-out queue and head of the
new cable channel Live TV) while the big cheeses among male broadcasters
were much more likely to be parents.
In what context was this survey discussed? As I wasn't there I can't
report, but I can easily imagine: career women don't have children or
postpone having children because without the support systems of good
childcare facilities and flexible working hours children slow you down.
The usual catalogue of perfectly proper feminist grievances.
But there's another explanation which dare not speak its name, which
only feminists who have been reconstructed by maternity dare to whisper:
children take the edge of hunger off your ambition.
If there's a choice between spending six days in Portugal with my
daughter or spending six days networking at the Edinburgh Television
Festival, with or without the oblivion drinking and power bonking, there
is no contest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turning of the tide</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601296</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL psyches are strangely elusive things. National caricatures
and stereotypes, sustained by some meagre strands of discernible truth,
are one thing. But getting at a really convincing explanation of what it
means to be French, Japanese, or Scottish is always unfinished business.
If you could sit all Scotland down in one psychiatrist's chair, even a
whole phalanx of Dr Anthony Clares would, I suspect, retire bemused,
baffled, and bedraggled from the verbal fray.
National or ethnic identity is clearly something which matters deeply,
passionately to many people. In former Yugoslavia countless thousands
have died for it. Until a year ago, in Northern Ireland, similar
sacrifices were commonplace.
But what is all this bloodshed and dying for? What, apart from a deep
irrational fear and loathing of the other -- Bosnian Serb for Bosnian
Muslim, Irish Protestant for Irish Catholic and vice versa -- is this
powerful sense of collective identity all about?
Each group, inevitably, tries to emphasise the positive aspects of its
own image. We Scots like to think of ourselves as friendly. Witness the
oft-heard -- but dubious -- claim that there's not much racism north of
the Border. We regard ourselves as generous. Scots are supposed to give
proportionately more to charity.
And well-educated. The merits of our much-vaunted education system and
our huge appetite for newspapers are well-worn markers for that. And
creative. I sometimes wonder if there's anything we Scots didn't invent.
Stir in a pinch of soft-spoken, self-effacing modesty and the picture
begins to gel. Add in some inevitables, like Scotland's fragile location
on the very periphery of Europe. But douse them in our long-standing
taste for international adventure and the final result shines through.
What a braw lot we are, battling against some long, God-given odds,
compared with our loud-mouthed, conceited, introspective southern
neighbours!
We are not good at coming to terms with the more negative aspects of
our collective character. Allegations that Scotland consists of whinging
jocks and subsidy junkies leave us apoplectic and vengeful. Those
southern neighbours know only too well that, to expose the thinness of
our veneer of self-conceit, they need only recycle tales of Scottish
razor gangs, drunkenness, and urban poverty.
Within seconds, Pat Lally's in a lather and we all are reinforced, yet
again, in that pernicious syndrome of Scotland as victim, looking back
nostalgically to better days when the Clyde produced a third of the
world's shipping tonnage, looking forward apprehensively to a future in
which every bottle -- including those containing whisky -- is half
empty.
Let's face it. We Scots have a problem with success. It's not that we
don't, individually, enjoy the taste of it. But we do have a problem
acknowledging success in others. And too many of us seem to enjoy the
taste of having success snatched from our outstretched hands even more.
Too often we seem to prefer the We wuz robbed post-mortem to celebrating
achievement itself.
No section of the Scottish community is entirely immune from the
pernicious effects of this victim mentality. Since the war, Scotland's
indigenous business community surrendered control of sector after sector
to outside takeover. The reasons were a complex mix of stunted ambition,
management failure, poor investment, and lack of vision.
The result, climaxing in the 1980s hostile takeover boom, was a
progressive haemorrhaging of Scotland's indigenous corporate culture as
more and more headquarters closed down and control slipped south or
abroad. We filled the cracks with branch factories, distribution
warehouses, and inward investment. But the damage was done.
The flow of genuinely Scottish companies seeking a stock market
listing virtually dried up. The only real exceptions were new investment
trust vehicles. As we know from Scottish Enterprise research on
Scotland's business birth rate, the flow of new company starts slowed,
too, to rates well adrift of the UK average.
Now there are signs that the tide may be turning. Indigenous Scottish
businesses may be poised for something of a renaissance. Scottish &amp;
Newcastle, having sold its hotel chain at the top of the market, has
successfully diversified into holiday parks and has now taken over
Courage to become the UK's largest brewer of beer.
The creation of Scottish Courage, as we must learn to call it, is all
the sweeter since, not so long ago, S&amp;N was on the receiving end of a
hostile bid from Courage's Australian parent Elders IXL.
Yesterday the President of the Board of Trade Ian Lang cleared
ScottishPower's bid for the English regional electricity supplier
Manweb. The odds must now be firmly on the Glasgow-based group expanding
its interests into that slice of North-west England and North Wales,
nearly doubling its customer base in the process.
The deregulated bus sector is heavily Scottish-flavoured. Two of the
biggest companies are Perth-based Stagecoach and FirstBus, with its
strong Grampian connections.
The stock market listings famine of the 1980s has been replaced by a
modest but steady stream of new issues, from speculative hi-tech
companies like Calluna, The Vision Group and Memory Corporation to
established growth companies like the latest to announce its plans
earlier this week, Morrison Construction Group.
And Scottish Television, which appeared to have missed the boat in the
post-franchise round restructuring in that industry, has now emerged
with a new strategic vision and a new major shareholder in the cable and
satellite specialist, Flextech.
I might add -- but I risk another ice pick in the back for my pains --
that the opportunity now exists for a creative new future for Scotland's
indigenous broadsheet press.
These diverse developments do begin to look like the foundations for a
Scottish business renaissance. But is our collective constitution strong
enough to take a bit of self-generated success for a change. Can we cast
off the sack cloth? Bury the ashes? And recast Cassandra's tolling bell
into something more useful? Watch this space.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
