<HEADLINE>Free range excellence. June Tabor, Acoustic Music Centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ADAMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601297</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHE came in like a jester and left like an undertaker. The normally
stern mien initially had given way to comparative expansiveness. The
voice, too, was softer. Whereas the duet with Mark Emerson's sparse
violin playing made her singing almost brittle, the addition of Huw
Warren's piano made her more relaxed and let her sing different songs,
albeit along the usual themes.
She sang of love gone wrong, wrong and right. She sang bossa nova and
lampooned overpaid chairmen of public utilities. She made us laugh.
Then, with a finale merging a calm, unerring Will Ye Go to Flanders and
a terse Green Fields Of France, she proved her potency. Not a woman to
pick a fight with, but can she sing!
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Boyfriend, Adam House Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601298</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS production of Sandy Wilson's peppy 1920s-set musical comedy is
the perfect antidote to some of the gloom and doom of other Fringe
shows.
As performed by Bristol University's Strawberries With Cream company,
the slightness of plot and characterisation are played up, with a fair
amount of irony, and everything centres on the almost non-stop music and
the visual gags.
Every character is a caricature: from the goody-goody Juliet Mills
lookalike, pretty Polly Browne (an impressive performance from Natalie
Hand) through to the lecherous bourgeois bum, Lord Brockhurst (Martyn
Luke). The star comic turn, however, belongs to Andrea Hayden as the
hyper French maid, Hortense -- 'Allo 'Allo meets Joyce Grenfell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Adrian Davidson, Overseas House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CLARE HENRY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601299</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OVERSEAS House in Princes Street has recently established a good,
regular exhibition programme so I had expected great things. Not so.
Adrian Davidson has given himself the main staircase and filled it with
expensive, badly made, one-liner boxed mirrors.
Thus Apollo is a crude tyre, Venus a seashell, Demeter dried corn.
Eggs, dried marigolds and marbles fill the rest. Snow White with its
witty lipstick, laces and apple is the sole thing of note.
Upstairs the Green Room Gallery shows an assortment of equally
uninspired painting sculpture and crafts by eight artists. Some ceramic
sculpture in plaster and suede is truly, deeply ugly.
Anna Gillespie's stone carved celebration figure and Abigail Reynolds'
Lillies and Irises stand out, worth a look alone among a sea of
mediocrity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Grunge and glamour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MINTY DONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601300</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MINTY DONALD sees shades of pop culture icons in the sordid realism of
Scottish Opera-Go-Round's production of Puccini's La Boheme
PUCCINI earns the dubious accolade, in some of the snootier circles of
the opera world, of being dubbed the Andrew Lloyd Webber of the late
nineteenth century. There's certainly some justification for this
comparison: the seeming effortlessness with which he turned out a
succession of damn good tunes, the ease with which his more emotional
arias can be translated into show-stopping tear-jerkers, or his
unabashed enthusiasm for the big chorus number, all bear more than a
passing resemblance to the outpourings of the Lloyd Webber empire, and
no doubt contribute to Puccini's continued prominence in the popular
repertoire.
Scottish Opera-Go-Round's production of La Boheme, which begins a
seven-week tour of Scotland today, steers well clear of the schlock and
stagey showiness associated with the Lloyd Webberesque-end of the
Puccini market. No overblown sentimentality or inappropriately lavish
stage settings here. The practicalities of touring to such far flung and
rudimentarily equipped venues as Ullapool Village Hall and Thurso High
School alone, not to mention the complete absence of chorus and
orchestra, would rule out the possibility of oppulent staging, slick and
hi-tech effects, but more fundamental artistic concerns also push the
production in a grittier, less romantic direction.
Stewart Laing, who both directs and designs the production, making his
debut as an operatic director, is keen to point out the hard-edged side
of Puccini's work. Mimi's death, he argues, is understated and
unsensational, quite unlike the choreographed melodrama of Violetta's
demise in La Traviata. The sordid realism of Puccini's portrayal is, he
claims, frequently dismissed or overlooked. He believes that Boheme
provides an ''accurate representation of how young people behave . . .
of the world of one-night stands''.
This very contemporary emphasis on what Laing describes as the ''cult
of youth and recklessness'' is further reflected in his set designs: a
paint- splattered newspaper-strewn garret, bleak and squalid, empty save
for a rank mattress and the wine bottles stacked in every available
corner. Its references are as much to grunge, the aesthetics of the
squad, as any romantic nineteenth-century attic; the kind of
art-studenty flat that brings back hazy memories of parties you'd rather
forget!
Whether a deliberate attempt to woo a younger audience or not, Laing's
focus on the seedier aspects of Bohemianism paints an accurate picture
of the lifestyles of its original Parisian exponents. His attempts to
capture a sense of youthful abandon, with its attendant careless
cruelty, selfishness, and, in some instances, suicidal despair, reflects
both the behaviour of the first Bohemians, and of more recent examples
of hedonistic and self-destructive youth. Shades of pop culture icons of
the slacker generation: Ian Curtis, Sid Vicious, and Kurt Cobain.
Don't expect all doom and gloom, though. Nor, indeed, the pared down
minimalism of a great deal of touring theatre. Laing firmly believes in
''giving people a bit of a show''. He feels strongly that you cannot
ignore the basic glamour and theatricality of opera and is more than
happy to embrace it. Opera-Go-Round's Boheme will not be lacking in
visual stimulation. (Laing is, after all, still best known for his work
as a designer, and as one who is commendably, if somewhat notoriously,
fastidious in his attention to detail.)
The audience will be treated to proper scene changes: to a production
rich in scenic invention. Not in-your-face spectacle, but a design full
of subtle and witty touches which invite quiet discovery. It even has
its very own, appropriately low-tech, special effect. I don't want to
give the game away . . . go to see for yourself.
