</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Violet Verdi Masterclass, Festival Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>FRINGE</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601301</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VIOLET Verdi is demonstrating how a ballerina should hold her head in
a certain position. ''Mr Ballanchine used to say to use -- 'Lean on a
pink cloud and expect a kiss'.'' You can feel the audience grin with
delight. This is why they have come to watch Violet Verdi take class
with 11 dancers from Scottish Ballet. It is this intimate insight into
Ballanchine and his work -- she was, after all, one of his brightest
stars -- that holds us fast throughout the mechanics of plies,
battements and assemblees.
Dressed in a hyacinth shift with youthful front slit -- plenty of
leeway for illustrating steps -- Verdi still moves with delightful
lightness. Feet, in bright red shoes, dart through bits of difficult
business -- she doesn't just show, she explains why a move should be
just so, tying it in, as she goes, to Ballanchine's style of technique.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Emperor Quartet, Queen's Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601302</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE vitality so disappointingly absent from the Salzburg Camerata's
Haydn playing was abundantly present in that of the aptly-named Emperor
Quartet yesterday morning.
Though Haydn's own Emperor was not one of the works performed, the
later and perhaps even greater G major quartet, Op 77, No 1, formed the
climax of a richly rewarding concert that had opened with the emotional
ambiguities of the B minor quartet, Op 33, No 1, and of Britten's
valedictory Quartet No 3.
Programme planning is an art that these young British players had
clearly mastered in a way that the venerable Sandor Vegh and his
Salzburgers on Wednesday had not. Each work had something to say about
what followed or preceded it; each was played as if it meant something,
not only in itself but in the context of the rest of the programme.
Though not always quite perfect in detail, these were performances
alive in their response to the rhythms, harmonies, and, in Britten's
case, poignancy of the music. On paper, the last notes of Britten's
finale -- a movement subtitled La Serenissima, in tribute both to Venice
and to Death In Venice -- look serene. But in fact, as the performance
proved, they are not untroubled. This was almost the last music Britten
wrote and the playing conveyed not only its hauntingly elegiac tone, but
also the anger and isolation of a dying man.
In such a context, the volatile side of Haydn, rather than his
cheerfulness, seemed to stand out as the music moved through disturbing
modulations and swift-changing moods.
In Op 33, No 1, the interplay of minor and major keys carried the
right feeling of restlessness; in Op 77, No 1, the verve was more hectic
than benign.
* Sponsored by the Bank of Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
