<HEADLINE>Altogether, for one more week?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL,DIARY</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601303</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUMOUR has it that some trickster has been hovering outside the Fringe
office handing out blank fliers. All those who have ducked and jostled
through the gauntlet of eager barkers emerge confused. No hectic prose.
No list of one- word praises from parish mags. In short -- no show.
Actually the chap is advertising Week Four . . .
Suddenly it's like January again. The decorations are coming down, the
fridge is going back to low-fat yogurts and mousetrap cheese, everyone
turns into pumpkins by midnight. No, it's worse, it's worse. Because the
fun's winding down just as I'm getting the hang of it again.
Week Three is my ''season of misseds and hollow wistfulness''. Time is
conspiring to leave me wanting. I need at least three afternoons per day
-- or one second Tardis -- to catch up with my hopes. Come tomorrow I'll
be inconsolable. Thirty shows into one day just will not go --
especially when half of them left town a week ago.
It's hard to explain -- even to myself -- where this eleventh-hour
ravening springs from. The programmes that wander across the bedroom
floor tell me I should be sated by now. Relieved, even. No more
suffering for other people's art. No more imagining that brain cells are
audibly dying of boredom -- phut, phut, phut . . . behind the eyes like
popping corn.
I think what I crave, as much as anything else, is the Festival
audience. You never know who's going to turn up next to you. Settling
into my seat for C'est Magnifique, I was disrupted first by one woman,
then by another three, and finally by a straggler who had us all bobbing
and nodding just like . . . just like the female clowns in Embarquez-Les
. . .
I squinted sideways. It was them. No white faces, no red noses
obviously -- but the gestures gave them well away. The sorting out of
who sat where, the taking off of sweaters, the looking around, was like
a little commedia prelude to the mime and mayhem of Deschamps and Co.
I didn't do the Zimmermann Requiem -- but apparently funk diva Chaka
Khan did. Can we look forward to a cover version, released in time for
next year's 50th Fest? I also missed Sir Desmond Tutu. I went to the
first night of The Hard Nut, he popped in later in the run. Did he, I
wonder, leap to his feet with a characteristic ''Yippee!'' as the
curtain fell on some of the hottest snowflakes ever to dance up a storm?
But it isn't simply a matter of schmoozing after celebs. Some of my
Fringe highlights have been the queues before and after shows. Waiting
in a crush of bodies at Hill Street Theatre, I found myself underneath a
conversation between towering Americans. She -- with commendable insight
and great good taste -- was having verbal palpitations over Herald Angel
Yvette Bozsik.
He was quietly passionate about a show I hadn't seen, Like A Virgin.
He had, apparently, cried his heart out. Unbeknown to him, the play was
about a young girl dying. His own sister had been an early casualty of
leukemia. It had, he said, brought it all back to him. She started to
sympathise, he stopped her -- the tears had been good. The show had
surprised him into letting go and there, in the darkness, surrounded by
strangers, he had truly mourned. Such human dramas en route to the very
show . . .
Later that evening I passed a woman, just outside a converted church
that daily enshrines those Aussie hoofers, Tap Dogs. She looked wan,
dislocated. Thinking she too might be suffering from catharsis overload,
I turned back. Yes, indeed, she was feeling shaky. Her stomach was
leaving its moorings, she felt sick. Something she had eaten?
''Something I'd seen.'' The Tokyo Shock Boys had struck again. What a
farce.
But maybe the most uplifting audience I encountered -- and was part of
-- defied the slashing, drenching rain to watch Carmen Funebre in the
open air. Somehow the bleakness of the weather seemed the only true
backdrop for the sense of oppression, brutality and death that stalked
the space.
Watching the symbolic fires that just wouldn't -- couldn't -- catch
light against the downpour was so much more discomforting than any
roaring blaze could ever have been. It was as if all the sodden, grubby
suffering of faceless refugees had fetched up there, in front of us, in
a douce Edinburgh playground.
In the end all around me, faces -- some colleagues, others friends,
mostly yet again strangers -- glinted with mixed tears and raindrops
under the street lights. Hands rattled into pockets for the loose change
that would allow the company to eat a little better, maybe see some
shows in Edinburgh. It suddenly felt lucky, and marvellously free to be
an audience at Carmen Funebre that night.
Already, however, these audiences are melting away. The streets are
emptying. The seething throng of punk Elizabethan and haphazard jugglers
have been displaced by uniformed teenagers in stiff new blazers -- hard
to imagine them as one and the same. A Fringe fair makes a difference in
the young. Any day now and Jenners windows will be buttoned up with
tweedy coats in rusty shades.
I am seized with SAD-ness. Seasonal Affective Disorder, a real
affliction. As the lights go out and church halls return to Scout groups
and sales of work, I squirrel away my brochures and ticket stubs. Stroke
the hat-brim still spotted with rain from Carmen Funebre, stack up the
papers that will join the yellowing files of other Fests at home.
Week Four -- the first week of waiting for the whole clamjamfrey to
come round again. Oh woe! Mind you . . . Tap Dogs are coming to Glasgow
in October!
</TEXT>
