<HEADLINE>Workers in soup over homeless</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601304</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at a Linlithgow electronics factory dined differently
yesterday, when their canteen was turned into a soup kitchen to help
launch a campaign aimed at raising money to help the homeless.
Sun Microsystems decided to help the campaign as part of its community
involvement policy.
Cash raised will go to Jericho House, in Edinburgh, which provides
care and research into problems of homelessness, and where the late Lord
Hugh Douglas-Hamilton first began a campaign to raise #100,000 five
years ago, when he was involved in working at the homeless centre.
Already, #98,000 has been raised for the provision of day care and
primary health care facilities for homeless people in and around
Edinburgh.
Homelessness currently affects 39,000 people in Scotland, with 37% of
those affected suffering from mental problems, according to Jericho
House director Alan Mair.
He described the soup kitchen plan as an innovative approach, as it
would recreate for employees some of the realities of homelessness.
</TEXT>
