<HEADLINE>Sunburst of sound. NDR Symphony Orchestra, Hamburg, Usher Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601305</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Music
THAT'S it. He's done it again. Game, set, and match to Gunter Wand. In
the final 15 minutes of his first concert, last night, with the NDR
Symphony Orchestra from Hamburg, something extraordinary happened. At
the peak of what had, in any event, been the concert of this year's
Edinburgh Festival, the veteran German conductor, in the finale of
Schubert's Ninth Symphony, let fly with a great sunburst of sound from
his glorious orchestra.
No version of the last movement of Schubert's great symphony has ever
brimmed -- almost to bursting point -- with such light and energy.
Backed by some of the most committed and unanimous orchestral playing
heard at the festival since his own appearance last year, Wand produced
a searing performance that went beyond radiance, beyond optimism. It was
life-affirming; simple as that.
What an astonishing man he is. Tall, gangling, frail, hunched, and
with enormous arms that stretch almost to his knees, the aged,
85-year-old genius had to be assisted on to the stage. As he made his
way to the centre of the platform, he used the players' music stands for
support. Yet the music galvanised him. His body pulsed to the rhythm,
his huge arms produced incisive, firm, utterly confident strokes. His
NDR players followed him unerringly. They might not be the best band in
the world, but under this conductor they sounded it.
Throughout the evening, in totally wondrous performances of Schubert's
Eighth and Ninth Symphonies, some of the most integrated and disciplined
orchestral playing ever witnessed unfolded in the Usher Hall. Schubert's
song-like melodic lines, his bristling, animated rhythms, his
miraculously coloured harmonies: everything received such scrupulous
attention that the most familiar music carried the fresh shock of the
new.
And that shock extended beyond Gunter Wand's magisterial
interpretations into the sound he produced from the NDR Symphony
Orchestra -- a bottomless richness of string sound, capable of climaxes
of scorching intensity, as in the second movement of the Ninth, and of
delicate playing of exquisite beauty, as in the unforgettable version of
the tender cello theme of the Eighth.
As for his sense of rhythm, Wand generates playing of a virility that
would surprise from a conductor 40 years younger. What was heard last
night was so rare it is a genuine marvel. The great conductor and his
orchestra take the closing concert of this year's festival tomorrow
night. It is an event to be savoured.
</TEXT>
