<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ebb Tide, the Citizens' Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601306</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROBERT Louis Stevenson's late South Seas story is a swashbuckling
adventure with metaphysical overtones. In Robert David MacDonald's
adaptation it is cut sharply in two halves. Act One is all narrative. A
tale of reckless opportunism in which a degenerate captain commandeers a
ship moored in Tahiti and supposedly laden with a cargo of champagne,
with the intention of steering it off course and disposing of the booty
in Peru. On Kenny Miller's excellent set of slatted wood decorated with
a circle of yellow light bulbs (mirrored by blue bulbs on the ceiling
above) MacDonald presents the story like a forties movie matinee for
children, right down to the closing promise ''tomorrow's instalment
reveals all''.
Patrick Hannaway as the wayward captain turns in an appropriately
blustering piece of character acting, his voice a gruff, heavily
stressed, throaty growl, not unlike the bulldog in Tom and Jerry
cartoons. But, at the same time, there is a subdued, surly presence of
Paul Albertson playing Herric, an Oxford-educated seaman too honourable
to commit wholeheartedly to the buccaneering business. And it's in the
second half, when they inadvertently come ashore on a corrupting Eden of
a Pacific island, that his inward-looking, moody anxieties come to the
fore.
The sailors' adversary is Demant (Brenda Hooper) who rules the island
with an unyielding religious zeal coloured with a high-handed
imperialism that has little more to commend itself than the captain's
selfish greed.
Somewhere in here is the core of Stevenson's moral concern but, on
stage, where dialogue is everything, the motivations are too uncertain
and the arguments too eliptical for us fully to make sense of his
dilemma.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nelken, Playhouse, Edinburgh,</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>EDINBURGH FESTIVAL</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>976601307</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR once, don't wait until the last bell rings before scrambling to
your seat. Take time, instead, to drink in the sudden field of flowers
that is the Playhouse stage while Tanztheater Wuppertal is performing
there. Carnations -- Nelken -- hundreds and hundreds of them, so
delicately pink and white that it comes as something of a shock when
elegantly dressed figures start trudging through them carrying
armchairs, settling down as if in some grand hotel.
But here, at the start of Pina Bausch's disconcerting, crazy,
wonderfully uplifting work, there is an insoucient licence. This is
Liberty Hall where anything is allowed: even leaving the stage and
asking the audience to show you the exit . . .
We laughed, delightedly, at a man singing the words of Some day he'll
come along, the gestures like some sophisticated hand-jive to the music.
We giggle, when Jan Minarik solemnly tunes us into his heart beat. And
when the stage fills with fellas in fancy frocks, dancing like
two-year-olds we titter and guffaw. Until Minarik, stern, officious, and
disrupts the fun.
Dog handlers with Alsatians corner the field. A man is collared. He
has to show his passport.
Gradually a new mood creeps into the apparent child's play. A game of
Grandmother's Steps becomes fiercely tyrannical. A group of men hold
hands while reciting tactics for deflecting trouble.
Freedom, innocence, youthfulness, has somehow slipped over the
horizon. A series of ritualistic, repetitive moves -- conjure the
enforced obedience of an authoritarian state. The petty humiliation
mooted out are so ludicrous they heighten the sense of oppression.
Yet, Nelken radiates a marvellous optimism, an encouraging resilience.
People have been pushed to all manners of extremes. There are some fly
moments when the company protest at the rigours of performance, and of
Bausch's directions! There are moments that hit hard, even for those of
us up in the circle. But all this is merely a precursor to a celebration
of hope.
Ultimately Nelken is about the freedom of spirit, the value of choice,
the relevance of art.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
