<HEADLINE>Summer madness as tour firms battle it out. Flights of fancy: Margaret Vaughan describes how Britain's biggest tour operators are vying already for next summer's customers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARGARET VAUGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601308</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAYBE the heat has gone to their heads. Either that or the sangria,
retsina and a severe overdose of Turkish caffeine has befuddled their
marketing faculties. How else, Muir Anderson wonders, to explain why the
UK's biggest tour operators yesterday launched their holiday brochures
for next summer?
There are, after all, still two months of this season's left to run.
They are still lumbered with this summer's leftovers. They know wily
customers are waiting, still, for low-cost deals this year: ''It's
absolutely crazy,'' says Anderson, the Scottish spokesman for ABTA, the
Association of British Travel Agents.
''You would think, wouldn't you, that they would be concentrating on
clearing out all the holidays still unsold this year? Not to mention the
coming winter's offerings.'' But, no, while travel agent's windows are
festooned with day-glo offerings of last-minute breaks at boot sale
prices, while Spanish hoteliers work out how four people will fit into
400 spare rooms, while in Greece shopkeepers grieve over the disastrous
season and vie to fleece the few visitors in rip-off tourist traps, the
Big Three tour operators yesterday launched their summer programmes for
1996.
Thomson Holidays, the biggest operator, was not due to launch its
brochure until today. But scrabbling to steal a march on their rivals,
First Choice -- third largest -- sent out a fax yesterday morning to say
they would be launching their programme at teatime last night. In a
retaliatory strike, Thomson promptly opened bookings. Not to be outdone,
Airtours, too, are open for next year's business:
''It used to be January, then it was pushed back to November or
December. Last year, it was August and now they've done it again. They
are like squabbling children. Everybody is confused, and in the long
term its not good for customers or the travel trade.''
Now the Big Three travel agents' have joined in the race, offering the
lure of 10 to 12% discounts for those who book early. Along with the
annual launch came the annual stern warnings about booking early,
booking now, to avoid disappointment. After a decade of expansion,
Airtours -- the UK's second biggest operator -- is reducing the number
of holidays it plans to offer next summer by 10%. The third-largest,
First Choice, has cut planned capacity by 15%. And Thomson Holidays, the
biggest operator is following suit with reduced supply and price rises.
There is, naturally, method in the summer madness, according to
Anderson, an independent travel agent: ''It's got nothing at all to do
with what the customers want,'' he insists, fuming quietly amidst
K2-like mountains of brochures. ''It's all about the big operators' race
for market share.''
If it's not for the benefit of tourists, then what is it all about?
Last year, 10 million package holidays were sold in the UK. For this
year the big tour operators, somewhat optimistically, increased the
number of holidays on offer by around 7%. But wobbly consumer
confidence, the late bookings trend to wait for cheap deals and a long,
hot summer conspired to leave the tour operators with a surplus of
package holidays on their books.
By the end of October, when final figures are known, it will be clear
just how badly the tour operators have been stung, if at all: anecdotal
evidence is that wily customers are still grabbing cheapo deals --
offered simply, in tradespeak, to put bums on seats in the sky -- and
that overall the figures for those who choose to package abroad will not
have fallen much below 10 million. The excess might prove to be in the
extra holidays added on because of over-optimistic projections last
year.
Now, while the tour operators trim the number of holidays on offer for
next year, they remain intent on gouging a bigger slice of market share.
It is that, says Anderson, which is behind the crazy dash to win
bookings for next year:
''It's all bound up with the big companies wanting to increase their
market share. They seem in the process to have lost sight of what the
customer wants. Most people don't particularly want to commit themselves
a year in advance. It's difficult enough to get them to book, without
opening 12 months ahead.'' Last year, he says, an initial flurry of
bookings tailed off and simply died.
''Those who want free child places or a particular hotel will be first
in the queue no matter whether it's August or January when the brochures
are launched.''
Anderson has reason, perhaps, to sound jaundiced: the early launch
causes nightmares for travel agents stuck with a stack of holidays still
to sell for this summer, and with the winter season still to come: ''But
it's not just that. I simply don't see huge numbers wanting to book for
next summer now. It's marketing gone mad. The big travel agents, tied in
with the tour operators, are forced to join the race. They need to hang
on to their market share.
''But everybody is confused. Do you take the discount now for an early
booking or wait for next year's late booking discounts? And, to be
honest, the big tour operators charge more for holiday insurance which
offsets the discounted prices.''
Which all sounds like a Dutch auction. But if the hoidaymaker wants to
plough through the brochures, or hang on for a cheap deal, why not?
''Well, short term somebody gets a discount which is good. Long term,
if this goes on, what will happen is the smaller, more specialist
operators will be pushed out. Which will leave the three big travel
operators and their related travel agents as all you have left. In the
long term it's not healthy for holidaymakers or the industry.''
A spokesman for A T Mays, Scotland's largest agents, was unrepentant:
''It makes sense to book early to get what you want and get a discount
for it.''
Despite the gloom, he says, there has been no big reduction in the
numbers of those flying abroad.
The trend to all-inclusive package holidays continues. Travel fashions
may change, but the big attraction for Scots -- Spain -- remains the
same. It has 40% of the Scottish package market. It remains to be seen
whether the 10% hike in prices for next year, as Spanish hoteliers look
for a bigger profit cut, will erode that share.
While Greece remains, this year anyway, the second biggest holiday
magnet for Scots it may see its share reduce dramatically next year. The
Greek tourism industry acknowledges having a disastrous summer with
revenues down at least 25%. This has been caused by spiralling prices
and an acknowledgment that it cannot match the bargain-basement deals on
offer from its least favourite neighbour, Turkey.
The director-general of the Confederation of British Industry, Howard
Davies, recently argued the case for persuading holidaymakers not to
vote with their feet, urging them to holiday at home rather than abroad.
And while the hot summer has helped boost the domestic market, the
figures to show by what extent are still awaited. The home tourism
market tends to get the second holiday business.
A decade ago, Thomson took 1,000,000 Britons on holiday abroad. This
summer it took 1,000,000 to the Balearics alone. In global terms, world
tourism is set to grow by at least 4% a year over the next decade,
making it the world's biggest ''industry'' by 2000. According to the
World Tourism Organisation, there were 450 million tourists in 1990.
There will be 650 million by the year 2000 and a billion by 2010.
What modern tourism is all about, according to Tourism Concern, a
British pressure group, is growth, growth, growth and to hell with the
consequences. Few of us, they point out, understand the damage tourism
can do to its host country.
Now, as Scots -- bored by Spain, wearied by Greece, and feart of
Florida's drive-by shootings -- begin searching for new destinations,
the tour operators are expanding their range of places for people to
roam.
According to the A T Mays spokesman, long-haul holidays are
increasingly better value for money. As for fears of exotic destinations
being lured into the honeyed trap of mass-market tourism, concerned that
it may yet do to Africa, the Caribbean, Thailand and Malaysia, what it
has already done to Spain and parts of Greece, the question arises: who
cares? Perhaps only those who can afford to travel on scheduled flights
to small, uncommercialised destinations. The split between the posh and
the package-tour peasants remains. While you are a tourist, I, of
course, am a traveller.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
