<HEADLINE>On the road to ruin</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601309</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Steele report on Maybole's pleas for a by-pass to save the High
Street
THE words of Lord James Douglas-Hamilton ring rather hollow in Maybole
as it fights for its survival in the face of a traffic problem which
threatens to choke the life out of the Ayrshire town.
The Scottish Office roads minister responded to criticism of failing
to carry through by-pass proposals for scores of Scottish towns by
saying that the core network must come first and meanwhile traffic will
be calmed with islands and roundabouts which do not cost a lot.
As local councillor Danny McNeill put it: ''A fat lot of good that is
to Maybole as the shops continue to close, the buildings are blackened
and undermined, and the people just stop coming in to the town.''
The ex-Provost of Kyle and Carrick has a bulging mailbag of complaints
from local people about the growing traffic problems in the area as
tourism in the South-west grows and the peace dividend from Northern
Ireland sees goods and passenger traffic using the port of Stranraer
escalating faster than ever.
''We have been waiting for by-passes to be built around Maybole and
Girvan for close on 40 years and each time we think it is about to
happen we slip further down the queue. Both towns should have been
by-passed by last year if the original plans had been carried through.
The routes have been surveyed and some of the groundwork done in the
past. Then nothing.''
The strange paradox in Maybole is that far from fearing a loss of
business by traffic passing them by, local traders believe they could
enjoy a boom if the town became relatively traffic-free and people could
park and walk around.
A trip up the High Street in Maybole illustrates the situation
graphically. At least three or four stops will have to be made in the
few hundred yards through the centre to allow huge lorries, vans or
caravans to squeeze through.
It is a High Street which would have been just perfect for the traffic
of the turn of last century when many of the buildings were put up and
the town grew. It just does not cope with 1995 traffic and local people
shiver at the thought of what things might be like by the year 2000.
Willie Ross, a butcher in the High Street, said: ''The situation is
unbelievable. People have to stand in against the wall to allow some of
the big lorries past and I have seen two lorries scraping against each
other as they try to pass in the main road.
''I have never been in any doubt that we should have a by-pass. People
just take one look at Maybole and decide there is no place to park and
nowhere to shop so they head for Ayr or Girvan. It is choking the town
and one by one the shops are closing.''
Ross is pragmatic about the possibility of a by-pass but called on
some measure to be taken in the town, such as a one-way system. He
added: ''It works when the Open is at Turnberry so it should be tried
all the time. It may not work though as the lorries running up and down
to the ferry get bigger and more powerful.''
Pat Gray, who owns Frills ladieswear shop in the High Street, said:
''The passing trade which we may lose with a by-pass would be balanced
out if people could walk in peace and safety in Maybole.
''I have customers from all over the area and they are finding it
harder than ever to get parked and move about the town. The extra
traffic using the road is good news for someone but not for us in a town
which can't cope with the cars and lorries it gets at the moment.''
Lord James wrote to local MP George Foulkes last week reminding him
that the focus must be on trunk roads and the apparently all-important
''core network'' but offering the heartening news that a Route Action
Plan is under way for the A77.
The RAP is designed to improve safety, amenity, journey times, and
ease of travel by a series of measures targeted at identified locations
where remedial action is required, wrote the minister.
Foulkes said: ''That is all very well where something can be done but
quite frankly there is little that can be done in Maybole because of the
existing roads around the town.
''It is of little comfort to local people in many towns and villages
along the A77 and A76 in South Ayrshire that the Scottish roads network
is getting better. They have to get around in comfort and safety and
their visitors should expect the same.
''Ever since Malcolm Rifkind was at the Scottish Office trunk roads
have been seen as an excellent vote catcher and money has disappeared
from vital by-pass projects to fund projects like the upgrading of the
A74. I will be speaking to local people and councillors and the pressure
will be stepped up.''
Joe Goldie of the Cassillis Hotel said: ''At night you can walk out of
the door and feel the draught of a huge lorry hurtling past at 60mph. It
is only a matter of time before someone is hurt or killed in the town.
''The by-pass must at least be put on the list of priorities or people
will just pass by Ayrshire altogether on their way to places which are
more accessible and more attractive.
''I do not fear a by-pass taking trade away; in fact I believe it
would greatly improve a situation which gets worse every day.''
Isobel Seymour, who brought up three children of her own and fostered
dozens of others in Maybole, said: ''I still have a petition gathered 10
years ago with over 1000 signatures. We called at every door we could
and got two refusals, one businessman who feared loss of trade and one
elderly man who said he had been waiting for a by-pass since 1918 so
what was the point.
''Mothers in the town are in constant danger as they push prams or
walk young children up the High Street. The time is long overdue for
Maybole to be by-passed and flourish at the same time.''
</TEXT>
