<TEXT>
MARGARET HUGHES seeks expert help to pick the best of this year's crop
of gourmet offerings in print
ONE of the fastest selling books in America last year was Cooking With
Rosie, the Oprah Winfrey-inspired cookery book.
Here in the UK the book did not create just as big a stir, but then it
was jostling for position alongside our own breed of celebrities pushing
cookbooks. Except in the case of the UK it is the chefs who are the
celebrities, and putting together a book of their recipes is becoming as
much a prerequisite for success as a television series!
To test the recipes in a selection of the most popular cookbooks, we
asked three chefs Colin Clydesdale, of Stravaigin, in Glasgow's Gibson
Street, Michael Mizzen, of the Glasgow Hilton, and Angus Boyd, of
Mitchells, North Street, Glasgow, their opinions of their colleagues'
offerings.
Here's their selection and verdicts.
FAR FLUNG FLOYD, Keith Floyd, Penguin #9.99
* FLOYD manages to impress viewers by cooking in unusual locations,
but how easy is it to recreate these dishes? Colin and Michael found the
book lacked authenticity. Colin said: ''I have travelled extensively in
the Far East and have never seen any of these dishes being cooked.''
Angus felt the book was short on recipes.
Marks out of 10: 5.
COMPLETE COOKERY COURSE, Delia Smith, BBC Books, #9.99
* EVERYONE agreed this was excellent value for money and the sort of
encyclopaedic book that will remain popular for years. Marks out of 10:
8
RHODES AROUND BRITAIN, Gary Rhodes, BBC Books, #12.99
* GARY Rhodes is very popular at the moment, but will his recipes
last? Michael believed they will: ''This is good down-to-earth cooking,
with easy to follow recipes, good usage of cheaper cuts of meat and
ingredients.'' Angus agreed: ''This is a good book for both serious and
novice cooks.''
Marks out of 10: 7
EAT YOUR GREENS, Sophie Grigson, Network Books, #10.99
* NOT vegetarian but a myriad of different ways to serve vegetables.
Colin said: ''This book is easy to read, recipes are easy to follow,
some ingredients would be difficult to source in Glasgow, but it is
informative and enjoyable.'' Angus admired Grigson's knowledge: ''Best
cooking methods, when vegetables are in season and details on storage
are all very useful.'' Michael admitted even he had learned something.
Marks out of 10: 7
BLANC MANGE, Raymond Blanc, BBC Books, #18.99
* THIS book covers Blanc's latest television series which looked at
the science of food, as well as ways of preparing it. Michael liked the
scientific aspects of the recipes. Colin was baffled as to who would
really want to know the scientific details of the food they are
preparing: ''I disliked the layout of the book and the photography did
not make the food look appetising.'' Angus felt the book was definitely
for the more serious cook: ''I wonder how beneficial the scientist's
notes are, will people mentally digest them as they prepare the
dishes?''
Marks out of 10: 4[1/2]
FLAVOURS OF INDIA, Madhur Jaffrey, BBC Books, #12.99
* THIS book combines recipes with a history of the regions in which
the dishes originate. Colin raved: ''Just looking at this book makes me
hungry! I have used her books before and have always found the recipes
simple, the ingredients easy to get hold of and the results authentic.''
Michael agreed: ''This is more than a cook book. The recipes are very
straightforward and there is a good choice of vegetarian dishes.'' Angus
liked the inclusion of details of mail order suppliers of specialist
ingredients.
Marks out of 10: 8
HAMLYN NEW ALL COLOUR COOKBOOK, Hamlyn, #7.99
* THIS brought a few groans as most of the recipes were tried and
tested dishes. Angus felt it was too basic: ''Even the most
inexperienced of cooks want to try something more adventurous than this
book provides.'' Colin was impressed by the number of recipes, but
little else: ''These are very traditional recipes which will probably
work, but you will not produce haute cuisine.'' Michael added: ''This is
a book for beginners, recipes are easy to follow, but a little old
fashioned.''
Marks out of 10: 4
FLAVOUR OF SCOTLAND, Brian Hannan, Mainstream Publishing, #14.99
* RECIPES from the kitchens of 12 Scottish chefs are compiled in one
book which aims to illustrate the richness of Scottish produce and
inventiveness of its chefs. Michael liked the concept: ''It is good to
have ideas which marry the use of Scottish ingredients with
international ingredients and styles of cooking. The recipes are clear
and easy to follow.'' Colin thought it was a good idea that different
chefs were included: ''There is a good cross-section of styles and
recipes . . . However, it is not for the beginner.'' Angus agreed that
some recipes were a little difficult: ''I did not feel there was a
strong flavour of Scottish cooking. I liked the layout, the recipes were
clear and technical jargon was kept to a minimum.''
Marks out of 10: 6[1/2]
* All books supplied by John Smith &amp; Son, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
