<HEADLINE>Once more, Piers is over the top</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601311</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Piers Morgan's appointment as editor of the Daily Mirror has ruffled
feathers in Fleet Street, observes William Russell
FLEET Street is in terrible tizzy because the editorship of the Daily
Mirror has been bestowed upon Piers Morgan, the 30-year-old editor of
the News of the World. Wherever hacks forgather for a pint the sediment
is being read. Those who drink tea are looking at the leaves for
guidance. What does it all mean?
In the real world, where Fleet Street editors are shadowy figures at
the best of times these days, it may seem small beer. After all, it is
merely a move from a Sunday to a daily tabloid. The problem, however, is
that the two tabloids have different owners. The News of the World
belongs to News International and detaching Mr Morgan from its
employment is a major coup for the rival Mirror Group.
Although editors come and go overnight at the whim of their proprietor
they do not do so at the whim of a rival. News International made clear
yesterday that they intend to hold their man to his contract, said to
have up to another 18 months to run, although in reality a deal will
probably be struck, the contract bought out. A reluctant editor in situ
is unthinkable.
Although it would technically be possible to dump the man in limbo
until it had run out, that is unlikely. Meanwhile the present editor,
Colin Myler, who is to become managing director of both the Daily and
Sunday Mirrors, will soldier on.
The Mirror Group has already provided a home for another ex-Murdoch
man, the legendary Kelvin MacKenzie, editor of the Sun for 13 years. It
was MacKenzie who made the Sun what it was, if not what it is. He now
heads the Mirror Group's television interests, having fled the coop
after an uncomfortable spell in Mr Murdoch's media empire as managing
director of BSkyB television. Mr Morgan was a MacKenzie protege -- he
edited the Sun's Bizarre pop column for some years -- so it looks like
the chicken is coming home to the rooster.
Piers Pughe-Morgan -- he dropped the Pughe when he joined the Sun --
became editor of the News of the World, Britain's largest selling title
in January last year when he was 28 or 29, depending on whom you
believe, and is the youngest Fleet Street editor since Hugh Cudlipp got
the chair of the Sunday Pictorial in 1937, aged 24.
He has proved a great success at the News of the World -- not that he
has put on circulation, the name of the game today being to retain
rather than increase it -- although there were some hiccups as he took
the paper down market and into the mire. Sales for July were 4,684,245,
slightly up on the June figure last year, but the sales for the period
from February to July are down by just under 1%.
The loudest hiccup was in May when he was publicly rebuked by Mr
Murdoch for running a story about the Countess Spencer's treatment at a
private clinic for eating disorders and alcohol addiction. The rebuke
was a bolt from the blue, especially as he had been attracting press
awards galore, like this year's Scoops of the Year award from What the
Papers Say. It was enlarged from Scoop of the Year in recognition of his
efforts in securing a raft of sensational stories like the Princess of
Wales's telephone calls to Oliver Hoare.
But even the Dirty Digger has his limits and Mr Morgan had overstepped
them. The Press Commission rapped him over the knuckles, but editor's
grin and bear such blows. The really painful one was delivered by Mr
Murdoch, whose desire for respectability has led to a rare recorded
instance of a leopard changing its spots. He said, while he would always
support worthwhile investigative journalism as a community
responsibility, it was clear that in this case ''the young man went over
the top''. He would not tolerate News International's newspapers
bringing popular journalism into disrepute, he added.
Since the Sun has been responsible for much of the disrepute, quite
apart from some of the seamier News of the World stories, it is a wonder
he was heard above the sound of glass-houses shattering, but he is a
born-again Christian repenting.
The Morgan list of victims is impressive -- the Bishop of Durham, Alan
Clarke, Hartley Booth, Melvyn Bragg, and Richard Spring were all exposed
for the gratification of his readership and he pandered to their tastes
with tales like Bienvenida Buck's affair with the chief of defence
staff, Sir Peter Harding, who duly resigned, and David Mellor's affair
with Lady Penelope Cobham, as well as the three-in-a-bed romp involving
Richard Spring, Parliamentary Private Secretary to Sir Patrick Mayhew,
the Northern Ireland Secretary, another man and a woman called Odette
Nightingale. The nightingale duly sang.
The problem with that story was Mr Spring, who is divorced, appeared
to have been set up, which is not quite the same as boldly going where
no man has dared, the traditional path of a News of the World reporter.
Troilism is not illegal. But the story gives readers of the Mirror some
idea of what they should look out for when he takes over because he will
undoubtedly bring the morality which has shaped his ends so far to it
too.
His father, Glynne, was in the meat distribution business in East
Sussex and he comes from a comfortable middle-class background in
Haywards Heath. On leaving school, unable to go to Warwick University
because he did not have the right grades and needed to resit some
subjects, he took a year off to work in the City as a clerk at Lloyds.
He then did the journalism course at Harlow Tech, serving his
indentures on the Wimbledon News, where he proved immensely hard-working
and a source of stories, before moving to the Sun in 1988.
He became the pop column writer and a favourite of MacKenzie's who was
said to be grooming him for stardom. An editor's baton was said to be in
his briefcase along with the Filofax and it was on MacKenzie's
recommendation that he got the News of the World job, an appointment
which left the hard men of the made-an-excuse-and-left school trembling
with rage, but not for long.
So what can the Mirror staff expect? Since he sacked some top
executives at the News of the World almost immediately he took over
there will be some shaking in editorial shoes. As for the Mirror
readers, he will almost certainly inject into the paper the virtues and
vices he brought to the News of the World.
His inexperience is no longer an issue. He is, after all, 30, has run
a major national newspaper for almost two years, and while his
achievements as a by-lined writer about the world of pop were mainly
manufactured -- the sub-editors are the unsung heroes of the tabloids --
his reputation as a reporter is unchallenged. He brought in the stories.
The difficulty these days is in telling the Sun and the Mirror apart.
They look alike and contain the same mix of stories, even if their
political stance is different, and tales about TV personalities, large
and small. The Sun has lost the MacKenzie touch and the Mirror has lost
its way. Mr Morgan's accession means we will have to continue taking the
tabloids for some time yet.
</TEXT>
