<HEADLINE>Children encouraged to phone home</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>CHECK OUT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601312</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* TIME was when the whining schoolboy crept unwillingly to school like
a snail, sorrowfully aware he was unable to contact mum or dad if he was
bullied or beaten. BT aim to change all that -- with a barrage of ideas
for phoning home when there's a problem.
In a free guide, they haven't overlooked the possibility that junior
might have blown his or her last 10p on a bag of crisps -- so parents
are urged to acquaint offspring with the reverse charge call. (BT might
usefully have added that this operator-connected service costs #1.80 a
time, plus phone charges.)
Cheaper options include #2 phone cards or a special Phone Home BT
chargecard that can be programmed to ring just one number and is
supplied free. Details of how to obtain the card, and other advice on
keeping in touch, are in Growing Up With BT, from post offices and BT
shops, or by calling 088 800 842.
* TAPPING out a phone number could be difficult, of course, when a
child's glasses have been broken or scratched in a playground
roustabout. With this in mind, High Street opticians Dollond and
Aitchison launch a back-to-school range of Kidsafe lenses made from
extra-strong plastic, hard coated to make them all but unbreakable.
The polycarbonate lenses give extra eye protection and, say D and A,
are lighter and more comfortable. In a range of styles and colours --
some inspired by Disney characters -- they come with a one-year repair
or replacement guarantee. NHS children's vouchers can be used for
Kidsafe.
* CHARLIE Chalk fun factories -- self-contained indoor play areas --
nappy changing facilities, child menus, and high chairs are among family
extras offered by pub-restaurant chain Brewers Fayre. More than 100
stop-overs allow motorway drivers to relax while kids release pent-up
energy. For details of outlets situated within minutes of motorway
junctions and a free map, call 088 600 900.
* ANIMAL compassion charity Viva! is calling on young Scots to back an
autumn rally in Glasgow to protest against crating live animals for
export. Superstar Richard Gere, Damon Albarn of Blur, and Grange Hill's
Ian Rushmere are backing the campaign, which includes a ''Crate Escape''
competition, with prizes from cruelty-free cosmetic and clothing
companies. Posters and a leaflet explaining how to get involved from
Viva! PO Box 212, Crewe CW1 4SD.
* ONCE it was pencil-sharp pleats -- now recycled jean pencils are a
pointed way for teenagers to make a fashion statement. Berol's Eagle
Jeans pencil is encased in genuine denim clothing offcuts reclaimed at
the factory.
After sweeping America, the pencil is now making its mark here through
Morrisons stores and Toys R Us branches in Edinburgh and Aberdeen, with
a recommendation to wear it jauntily behind the ear. A pack of six costs
#1.99. To banish back-to-school blues and encourage writing skills,
Berol offer garish pencil cases and ghoulish skeleton pens to accompany
wacky Yikes stationery.
* GUARANTEED to send kids bananas is a competition running at
Somerfield stores until September 15. Part of a campaign to encourage
families to eat more fruit and vegetables, shoppers are invited to spot
10 hidden bananas and complete a tie-breaker to win a Caribbean holiday
for four. Ten runners-up receive bananas for every pupil and staff
member at their school. Leaflets detailing the competition from fresh
produce sections of all Somerfield's Scottish stores.
</TEXT>
