<HEADLINE>Praise as Fusiliers return to Britain</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601314</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Welch Fusiliers who endured six months of sniping and shellfire
in the besieged Bosnian enclave of Gorazde yesterday won praise from
their commander as they arrived back in Britain.
''Despite the danger and deprivation, I seldom, if ever, heard a
complaint. That is because we all believed what we were doing was saving
lives,'' said Lieutenant Colonel Jonathan Riley.
Tired but elated to be home, the last British contingent of Gorazde
protectors flew into RAF Brize Norton, Oxfordshire, still wearing their
battledress and blue UN berets.
Colonel Riley, 40, revealed details of their hazardous withdrawal from
the Bosnia ''safe haven'' hours before the massive Nato air strikes,
Eighty Fusiliers left from the original Gorazde force of nearly 200
pulled out in darkness to prevent any repeat of the hostage-taking
incident in May when 33 Fusiliers were kidnapped from their isolated
observation posts.
''It was a pretty rapid move out, through a minefield at high speed,
before either side could catch their breath and know what was going on.
We made it to the Serbian frontier in one go and I can't tell you what
it felt like to cross that frontier,'' said Colonel Riley.
The battalion's ''cat and mouse'' tactics included the use of
Welsh-speaking signallers and radio operators to foil any Serb
eavesdroppers listening in to communications.
</TEXT>
