<HEADLINE>'Dramatic advance' for peace. Envoy claims breakthrough with 51%-49% split of Bosnia as starting point for talks.</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601318</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By Our Foreign Staff
UNITED States envoy Richard Holbrooke said yesterday that efforts to
end the fighting in Bosnia had advanced dramatically and reiterated that
a 51%--49% split of the country would be a starting point for
negotiations.
Holbrooke, US Assistant Secretary of State, met Croatian leaders and
Bosnian Foreign Minister Muhamed Sacirbey in Zagreb to brief them on his
talks on Wednesday with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic.
Milosevic announced on Wednesday the Bosnian Serbs had agreed to give
him a veto over terms of a peace deal that would now be bargained out by
a six-man team, three of whom would be from the breakaway Serb
''republic'' inside Bosnia.
Holbrooke described Milosevic's announcement as a breakthrough but
stressed that tough talks lay ahead. ''We agreed that President
Milosevic's announcement that he has formed a single negotiating
delegation with the Bosnian Serbs was a procedural breakthrough,''
Holbrooke told reporters after three hours of talks with Sacirbey.
''We are here to try to bring peace to the region and this has been a
dramatic advance,'' he added.
He said Milosevic had endorsed the American initiative and had already
agreed to a peace plan drawn up by the Big Power Contact Group. The plan
allocates 51% of Bosnia to the Bosnian government and Croat federation
and 49% to the Bosnian Serbs.
''The 51%--49% division is a starting point for negotiations and
mutual adjustments are possible,'' he said.
Sacirbey said Nato air strikes on Bosnian Serb positions had improved
the climate for peace talks but cautioned that Serb heavy artillery
remained a threat to the Bosnian capital, Sarajevo.
''We sense a new attitude (from the Serbs), although that attitude has
not shown itself on the ground,'' Sacirbey said.
Holbrooke was due to return to Belgrade yesterday and travel to
Germany tomorrow to brief the Contact Group as well as European Union
peace envoy Carl Bildt. He said he would then speak to Nato chiefs and
ambassadors in Brussels.
''We want to make sure that all people are on the same wavelength
because we are moving forward very rapidly,'' he said.
Holbrooke earlier quoted Croatian President Franjo Tudjman as saying
serious talking to end the fighting in former Yugoslavia could begin now
that Milosevic had effectively wrested control of negotiations for
Bosnian Serbs.
Diplomats in Belgrade celebrated Milosevic's announcement as a sign
the Bosnian Serbs had bowed to his will. But Serb political sources were
sceptical.
Word filtered out in Belgrade of a second, secret part of the deal
between Milosevic and the Bosnian Serbs that suggested their deal was
more compromise than triumph.
The Bosnian Serb leadership was reported to have won guarantees from
Milosevic that he would protect their interests and achieve certain
minimums in a peace deal, which the Bosnian government and Croats would
quickly reject.
Milosevic was said to have agreed to seek the division of Sarajevo,
the widening of a northern Serb-held corridor in Bosnia, and compact
territory -- which would spell the end of a Moslem presence in the
Gorazde enclave.
Whatever concessions were won from Milosevic by the Bosnian Serbs, the
agreement still appears to vindicate his view that Serbs will win more
in talks than on the battlefield.
Meanwhile, Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic indicated yesterday
that Bosnian government forces may take advantage of Nato air strikes to
retake territory occupied by Bosnian Serbs.
Asked in a German television interview if the Bosnian army would use
the opportunity to recapture lost areas, Silajdzic replied: ''It is the
task of the Bosnian army to liberate its territory.
''But if you think we are exploiting the situation then I think we
know better,'' he added. ''We may fight for our country but we have been
living there for a thousand years, after all.''
Earlier, Silajdzic held talks in Bonn with German Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel. At a news conference after the meeting, he said the
extensive air strikes against Bosnian Serb positions around Sarajevo had
made peace more possible.
''The air raids are raids for peace,'' he said. ''I believe that the
regime in Belgrade will finally understand that the monopoly of force is
gone.''
The Bosnian Prime Minister said he thought Belgrade might now exert
enough pressure on the Bosnian Serbs to bring them to the negotiating
table.
Silajdzic, who later addressed a Bonn conference on genocide in former
Yugoslavia, said he and Kinkel had agreed that plans for the economic
reconstruction of the region should be part of any peace settlement.
''The document should also contain an annex committing the
international community, and those countries that can do something about
that, to actually implement a Marshall Plan in Bosnia when the peace
comes,'' he said.
''For the last three-and-half years, we have been deprived of
civilised life. We have turned into Stone Age people.''
</TEXT>
