<HEADLINE>Chain reaction fills US jails</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROS DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>976601322</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A Republican-led crackdown on crime in America is having a marked
effect on prison populations, as Ros Davidson discovers
AMERICA has been known for violent crime and tough lawmen ever since
the days of the Wild West. But that image has taken on a new potency
with a report that America currently has 5,000,000 convicted criminals
-- enough to populate Scotland -- either behind bars, on probation or
paroled.
The report counts a record 1,500,000 criminals in federal and state
jails, and another 3,500,000 convicted but not behind bars. Criminals at
any one time may soon out-number the country's 6,000,000 full-time
students if the trend continues.
According to the Department of Justice study, the most comprehensive
ever, the number of people incarcerated has tripled since 1980 -- and
within a decade will exceed the population of New York, estimated at
7,300,000. On average an additional 230 people are imprisoned every day,
and more than 1540 new prison beds are filled weekly.
The annual increase, the second largest in history, is the result of
various policy and legislative changes that might be called a
law-and-order ''crack-down'' as the national policy drifts to the right.
Not surprisingly, America's prisons are at least 25% over capacity,
says the report. Even before the new figures, the US jailed a higher
proportion of people than anywhere else except for post-Communist
Russia.
This latest federal report comes as the issue of crime returns to the
national debate. The Republicans' Contract with America calls for
millions of dollars for states to build more prisons. Republicans have
also recently introduced laws that would cut programmes for crime
prevention mandated by President Clinton's crime Bill of last year. The
US already spends an estimated $21bn yearly operating prisons and $5000m
on constructing new ones.
In a similar ''law and order'' push, some states are also withdrawing
more and more privileges from inmates. More prisons are banning TV and
cigarettes. Alabama has even reintroduced ''chain gangs.''
The first 160 inmates on ''rock duty'' -- shackled together at the
ankles --smashed rocks into gravel with 10lb sledge-hammers for 10-hour
shifts in heat that had reached 30C degrees at 9am. Part of a campaign
to reduce crime by making prisons highly unpleasant, the idea has been
adopted in Florida and Arizona, and is being considered in Kansas.
In that vein, the federal report is hailed as encouraging by
conservative politicians, who say it shows harsher measures work, at
least by lengthening prison sentences. Alfred Blumstein, a criminologist
at Carnegie Mellon University, concedes that some criminals are now off
the streets and unable to commit murders. But he cautions: ''We should
think very hard about the trade-off'' -- between tripling the number of
prisoners and a relatively small decrease in crime.
Violent and serious crimes did drop 3% in 1994, according to the FBI.
But there is hardly a clear trend of less crime -- the use of guns by
criminals is also becoming more common. Almost 30% of the 4,400,000
worst crimes reported in 1993 -- murders, rapes, robberies and
aggravated assaults --involved a gun.
Clearly, the increase in imprisonment is in part because of the ''War
on Drugs'' started in the 1980s under President Reagan -- although drug
treatment programmes have been cut back -- and also various new tough
''law and order'' measures. The most infamous is California's ''Three
Strikes'' law, requiring a sentence of 25-years to life for a felon with
a record of two previous serious or violent crimes.
The law is so harsh, one Sonoma County judge refused to impose the
sentencing. Petty criminal Jeffrey Missamore, the father of an infant,
faced 25-years to life in prison for taking eight grammes of marijuana
into jail while serving time for petty theft. He had been convicted
before for receiving stolen property.
Overcrowding in prisons will also lead to more health problems and
violence amongst inmates, says Jenni Gainsborough of the American Civil
Liberties Union. Cells are already being used for more inmates than they
were designed for. ''Hot bunking'', where inmates sleep shifts in a
shared bed, is also being considered in Washington and two other states.
</TEXT>
