<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Russian anger 'unlikely to affect relations with West'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601323</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA is unlikely to allow its anger and humiliation at Nato military
action in Bosnia hamper crucial relations with the West, diplomats and
political analysts said yesterday.
''There will be fresh anti-Western rethoric, calls to oppose Nato
expansion, demands to reconsider the treaty on conventional forces in
Europe,'' said military analyst Irina Kovrinskaya.
''But, in fact, there is little chance things would go beyond that,''
added Kovrinskaya, who works for the Washington-based Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace think-tank.
Top Russian diplomats have complained that Moscow was not consulted on
the Nato attack.
Nationalist groupings in the State Duma or lower house stepped up
their pressure on the authorities yesterday, calling for a special
session to discuss the situation which ''emerged after Nato unleashed
war on the Balkans''.
Russia's demands to halt the operation were not supported in the
United Nations, where most countries backed the strike aimed at
destroying the Serb military potential and infrastructure, said Foreign
Ministry spokesman Grigory Karasin.
''In fact, as a result of the operation, not only Nato but the United
Nations as well appeared as allies of only one side in the conflict.''
Meanwhile, ordinary Russians spoke out against the air strikes, saying
the alliance should have found another way of silencing guns which have
killed thousands of civilians.
''You will never solve anything from a position of violence,'' a woman
in her thirties said as she rushed into the underground at Moscow's
central Kiev station.
Asked to suggest another way of stopping attacks like the Serb shell
which killed 37 civilians in a Sarajevo market on Monday most Russians
still said they opposed bombing the Serbs.
''There is always another way,'' was the opinion of ordinary Russians
questioned on a busy Moscow street. Although confused about the details
of the crisis in former Yugoslavia they were certain air raids were not
the answer. -- Reuter
</TEXT>
