<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DNA tests end mystery of Romanov remains</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601325</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
US experts say they have scientific proof that bones found in a
shallow mass grave near Ekaterinburg in the Ural Mountains belonged to
Russia's last Czar, Nicholas II.
The findings may finally put to rest a 74-year-old mystery about the
fate of Russia's last royal ruler, murdered in July 1918 with his family
at the start of the Communist era by Bolshevik soldiers in the town near
the Asian border.
''We have finally resolved one of the longest-running murder
mysteries,'' said Dr Pavel Ivanov. He was announcing the results of DNA
testing by the US Armed Forces Institute of Pathology.
Ivanov was appointed by the Russian Government to oversee the
investigation to determine if the bones found in the grave in 1979 were
those of Nicholas II.
Two years ago, the Home Office's Aldermaston Laboratory confirmed
through DNA tests, using blood samples from the Duke of Edinburgh and
other relatives, the identities of the Czarina Alexandra and three of
her five children, and the results have not been seriously challenged.
Although most historians believe the bodies of her two other children
were burned beyond recognition, a legend has grown up around Anastasia,
the youngest child, and Alexis, heir to the throne, with pretenders
surfacing periodically.
However a slightly irregular result in the Czar's DNA sequence, an
extremely rare condition known as heteroplasmy, was found in the British
tests, raising some doubts that it was him. The probability of
heteroplasmy occurring was believed to be one in 300 per generation.
In its three-month investigation, the team of US forensic experts
found that the key to proving whether the remains in the grave were
those of Czar Nicholas II was his brother, the Grand Duke George.
His remains were exhumed from the Romanov mausoleum in St Petersburg
and brought to America. They shared a rare genetic anomaly which removed
all doubts about the Czar's identity.
A Russian government commission will now consider how to bury the last
royal rulers of the country and the Russian Patriarchal Church may
proceed with canonising them as martyrs. They were canonised in 1981 by
the Russian Orthodox Church Abroad.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protesters hang China out to dry over rights</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601326</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE world's women told each other today that they can do anything they
set their minds to -- and proceeded to knock down Chinese-imposed
barriers to free speech and challenge global authorities.
Nobel Prize winner Aung San Suu Kyi, who spent six years under house
arrest for fighting for democracy in Burma, set the tone in her
videotaped address to the NGO Forum on Women, the largest ever meeting
of women.
She urged governments to spend ''less on the war toys of grown men and
much more on the urgent needs of humanity as a whole''. Some 3000 people
heard her speak and applauded her for a full minute.
Amnesty International delegates paraded with banners and pictures of
11 women political prisoners, including two in China. They circulated a
petition calling for the women's release and said they would deliver
copies to the governments involved.
Tibetan women who live in the West showed a videotape of Tibetans
forced into exile. Women delegates who came to see the tape grabbed it
back from two Chinese who tried to seize it.
Throughout it all, Chinese security videotaped and took notes
furiously, but only in the case of the Tibetan tape did they attempt to
interfere.
The first working day of the NGO Forum, a gathering of private
activist women held in tandem with the UN's Fourth World Conference on
Women that starts Monday, was everything China had feared.
China insisted that the 10-day NGO Forum be held in Huairou, a small
town an hour's drive from Beijing, in order to limit contact between the
women and ordinary Chinese, who were barred from the site.
However the foreign forum delegations said they would not be
suppressed.
''We have not been silenced anywhere in the world, and we will not be
silenced in China,'' said Pierre Sane, secretary general of Amnesty.
Organisers said about 17,000 participants had arrived in Huairou by
yesterday morning, and that 10,000 others who had hotel reservations
were expected to arrive today.
They had no count of how many were denied visas by China because of
their political or social views.
Suu Kyi, on the other hand, did not seek to attend the forum because
she feared Burma's military rulers would bar her from returning
home.--AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Al-Faran seeks reward for safety assurances.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TIME RUNS OUT FOR KIDNAP TOURISTS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601327</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KASHMIRI guerrillas holding two Britons and two other Western hostages
are running out of patience, Indian officials said today as their talks
with the kidnappers entered a crucial stage.
Last night the Al-Faran guerrillas hardened their position after
handing over evidence that the four captured tourists were alive and
well after more than eight weeks in captivity.
An Indian official said: ''They have hardened their attitude. They
were very angry. They told us they had provided proof that the hostages
were alive and well, and wanted to know what else we wanted from them.
Otherwise, they said, unless something is given in exchange it was all a
waste of time.''
Officials later said the militants and government negotiators had made
contact tonight.
''There is no deadline. There was nothing alarming during today's
contact. We can only hope that there will be a contact tomorrow,'' said
an Indian official. ''The talks have entered a crucial stage.''
This morning Indian negotiators contacted an intermediary who has been
involved in the talks. ''They asked the intermediary to tell Al-Faran
not to harm the captives and that Indian authorities were seeing what
they could do,'' the official said.
Britons Keith Mangan and Paul Wells, American Donald Hutchings, and
German Dirk Hasert were kidnapped in Kashmir early last month.
Al-Faran transmitted messages from the Britons and the German
yesterday, indicating they were all alive and well. The messages came
two days after the American spoke by radio to negotiators.
The hostages' relatives released a statement welcoming Al-Faran's
''humanitarian gesture'' and saying they looked forward to the speedy
release of the men.
Yesterday the militants demanded a gesture from the Indian Government
after agreeing to give firm evidence that the hostages were unharmed.
An official said before today's contact: ''Al-Faran will be waiting
only for a satisfactory answer. If it doesn't come, they're not prepared
to continue with negotiations.''
Al-Faran wants India to free 15 jailed militants in exchange for the
hostages. New Delhi has ruled out a swop but said some Kashmiri
prisoners could be released as part of a regular review of
sentences.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Islamic terrorists strike home as Algiers car bomb kills 10</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601328</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CAR bomb ripped through a crowded working-class district of Algiers
today, killing 10 people and wounding at least 15.
It was the latest in a growing number of car bombs that have been
blamed by the army-backed authorities on Islamic fundamentalists, who
oppose presidential elections due to be held on November 16.
The bomb went off at 11.50am in Mohamed Ounouri Square in the
capital's Bab El-Oued district, a densely populated area near the city
centre and a Muslim fundamentalist stronghold.
The square houses the headquarters of the Algerian security services,
DGSN. Security round the building has been stepped up in recent months
and cars are not allowed to park anywhere nearby.
Algerian Interior Minister Mustapha Ben Mensour rushed to the scene,
the Algerian news agency APS reported. It said 10 people were killed and
15 were wounded.
Bab El-Oued was the focus of a bitter struggle between security forces
and militants of the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) during 1992. In
January that year, the authorities cancelled a General Election which
the now-banned FIS was poised to win.
More than 40,000 people are estimated to have been killed in violence
since the poll was scrapped, and November's planned presidential
election is viewed by the authorities as a way of bringing the country
out of crisis. Their Islamic opponents oppose the poll.
''One would be out of his mind not to expect more killings in the
months ahead,'' said an Algiers-based diplomat earlier this month after
the authorities, headed by President Liamine Zeroual, announced the
election date.
The militants have increasingly turned to car bombs to press their
cause and yesterday, an Algerian newspaper reported that the interior
and energy ministries had imposed strict controls on the use of gas
canisters in an apparent attempt to halt their use in bomb attacks.
Today's attack was at least the fifth car bomb attack this month. The
bloodiest was in January when a suicide bomber killed at least 42 people
and wounded nearly 300.
Gas canisters were used in two bombs which killed seven people and
injured a total of more than 100 people in France in the past two months
and investigators there suspect Algerian militants may be behind them.
The militants accuse Paris, the former colonial power, of supporting the
Algerian government in the North African country's conflict.
</TEXT>
