<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wind back in sails of renovated generator</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601330</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUROPE'S biggest wind generator is producing power for the national
grid again -- more than two years after the Government recommended its
demolition.
A group of private investors have sunk their savings and time into
repairing the 150ft power plant at Burgar Hill, in Orkney, and claimed
yesterday the three megawatt generator could produce up to 10% of the
island's electricity.
Mr Tony Burton, site manager when the machine first produced power in
1988 and now one of the investment team, said the Department of Trade
and Industry had been wrong to write off the project.
That was in December 1992, when a crack appeared in one of the two
blades -- which weigh 65 tonnes and have a combined diameter of 200ft.
Mr Burton said the project had cost #17m by that stage but the DTI had
advised that the generator should be demolished.
''It's a massive source of non-polluting energy and it was crazy to
shut it down for the want of the #30,000 it's cost us to repair it,'' he
added.
Among those involved in the consortium are the sustainable energy
centre at De Monfort University, Leicester, and Aberdeen-based wind
energy company Sustainable Resources.
Mr Richard Gauld, managing director of Sustainable Resources, said:
''In 1992, before the crack developed, it produced almost 10% of
Orkney's electricity, that's the level of power generation we are now
trying to achieve again.
''We are confident we can, and that will earn us around #50,000 a
year, which will more than cover our costs and give us a return on our
investment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Road ahead for Edinburgh traffic. Regional council plans radical pedestrianisation to ease congestion in Princes Street.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>MAP</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601331</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOTHIAN Regional Council, due be killed off next April, yesterday
decided to take most of the traffic in Princes Street with it.
It is now seeking orders for the biggest change to Edinburgh's most
celebrated thoroughfare, banning eastbound vehicles, except buses and
bikes, and funnelling the rest up to Queen Street and through York
Place.
Traffic heading west is unaffected. The council's transportation
committee was told by its convener, Mr David Begg, that Edinburgh should
be looking even further west to Glasgow's example of complete
pedestrianisation of sections of Argyll and Sauchiehall Streets, which
had boosted profits for the shops.
''If Princes Street had been in any other country in Europe, it would
have been pedestrianised long ago. That is largely due to the
conservatism, with a small c, within this city,'' he said.
''I don't think these proposals are radical enough but we are taking
this course because it is a step forward in the right direction.''
Congestion has always been a problem in Princes Street, built 200
years ago not as a shoppers' Mecca but for people to live in and breathe
fresh air away from the stench of the Old Town.
It took Dr George Hazel, director of transportation, to point out what
that means in 1995. On a typical Saturday, it attracts 70,000 people and
10,000 vehicles, mostly cars. The latter manage to knock down at least
one of the former every week. Some of them do not get up again.
Work on the scheme, which will cost #1.2m, will start in the New Year
and should be complete by next August in time for the festival.
How it will affect parking is another matter. Every month, police tow
away 650 cars parked illegally in Edinburgh, but officials believe the
2000 places provided in new car parks since 1993 more than compensate
for the loss of 160 on-street places in the proposals.
The plans were published originally last October and modified after
consultation. New Town residents' groups were not happy and were left to
draw up their own plans in conjunction with officials.
As a result, there will be a series of road closures in Heriot Row,
Dublin, Northumberland, and Glenfinlas Streets, and traffic calming
measures elsewhere.
Cyclists have secured a lane for themselves along Princes Street and
taxi drivers can also drive eastwards, at least from Frederick Street,
and bring fares up from Waverley station.
Mr Begg stressed that the Edinburgh scheme was an experiment and would
be modified in the light of difficulties.
There could be some ahead on Queen Street, planned by James Craig on
similar lines as Princes Street. Its original buildings, long-spared the
onslaught of diesel and petrol exhausts, are much better preserved and
it is the longest sequence of eighteenth century architecture in
Edinburgh.
The Tory opposition, although insisting it was not against measures to
cut down on traffic in the city centre, unsuccessfully asked for a delay
to gather more information about the proposals, particularly as they
affect the West End.
Ironically, they might cause a few headaches to the council's
executioner, the Scottish Secretary, since some of the diverted traffic
will be rumbling past Charlotte Square, within earshot of his official
residence at Bute House.
* Plans for a car-free residential development between Gorgie and
Slateford Roads in Edinburgh were also approved yesterday. It is
modelled on a scheme in Bremen, where residents forsake cars as a
condition of their tenancy but can hire them cheaply from a nearby
garage when needed.
Dr Hazel said nobody thought the idea would take off in Germany but
the builder was inundated with applications. ''This is a very important
experiment to let people see there is an alternative to the way we are
going,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Frank slogan too much for the Royal Mail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601332</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
QUITE frankly, the Royal Mail does give a damn what messages people
put on their franking machines, as the trade union Unison discovered
this week.
Unison, which launched a major campaign to promote public services and
to point out what it sees as the failures of privatisation, wanted its
office franking machines to send out the mail with the message ''Public
Service, not Private Sleaze.''
However, the idea was quickly stamped out by the Royal Mail, which
told Unison's Inverness office that under the authority of the Post
Office Act 1969, it could refuse any mail bearing a franked message
which could cause embarrassment to the Post Office, any Post Office
employee or an addressee.
According to Royal Mail meters policy manager Mike Tamlin, Unison's
message ''expresses a strong political view which could cause
embarrassment to individuals receiving or handling the mail concerned.''
Unison's Scottish secretary Matt Smith described the decision as
political censorship. ''Why can't we promote our product on our mail the
same way that private companies can do with theirs?'' he said.
''It seems that you can promote all sorts of private businesses and
services on the Royal Mail but when it comes to public services, the
management get nervous. Maybe they are still smarting from the defeat of
their own privatisation proposals. They are surely not saying they agree
with private sleaze.''
A Royal Mail spokesman said the ban did not imply that it had taken
any view on the rights and wrongs of the slogan but that it could not be
seen to be associating with any political messages.
''We have a legal duty to ensure such slogans do not cause offence or
embarrassment,'' he said. Slogans of a political, religious or racial
connotation, were banned, he said.
Did that mean the Church of Scotland could not frank its letters with
an uplifting slogan about Christianity? ''Each case would be dealt with
on its individual merits,'' he added cautiously.
Perhaps surprisingly, the political parties in Scotland appear willing
to accept the Royal Mail's position. Neither the Tory Party nor the SNP
carries any message on its franked mail and Labour's merely says
Scottish Labour.
One SNP official was certain he could recall ''It's Scotland's Oil''
being used to frank mail in the seventies but presumably the Royal
Mail's political detection equipment was not fully operational then.
One Unison official wondered how the Royal Mail defined what would be
offensive to the public. He believed, for example, that Scottish
Nuclear's franking message ''Generating a Better Environment for the
Next Generation'' was offensive enough for people who dislike nuclear
power.
As for the Royal Mail itself, it tends to steer clear of controversy
on its franking machines by merely enquiring if people have remembered
to use the post code.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ig guns run out of targets</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601333</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE big guns of the UN's Rapid Reaction Force ran out of Bosnian Serb
targets around Sarajevo 18 hours after first opening fire, a United
Nations official revealed yesterday.
''The last artillery round fired was at 10.40 on Wednesday night
because they couldn't find anything to shoot at,'' he said. ''The
weather has been lousy but mostly it's that the Serbs have now had time
to hide their remaining weapons.
''We're in a counter-battery mode now. If the Serbs fire we'll see it
and fire back. Otherwise, it's probably going to be up to Nato.''
Rapid Reaction Force artillery on Mount Igman, west of Sarajevo, fired
900 rounds against 23 targets in about 18 hours.
Artillery on Mount Igman includes 12 British 105mm artillery pieces
manned by Highland Gunners, eight French 155mm howitzers, and French and
Dutch 120mm mortars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dead giveaway</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601334</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BUCHAREST: Taking your own shovel to a funeral is the latest way to
save money in post-communist Romania. A newspaper report about the high
cost of dying in Bucharest said city cemeteries were allowing burial
parties to bury their own to avoid the fees of state gravediggers. It is
not uncommon to see coffins being carried on car roof racks or even on
trams.
</TEXT>
