<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jury out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601335</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORONTO: The jury has begun considering a verdict in the trial of
31-year-old Paul Bernardo, who is accused of abducting two teenage
girls, forcing them to perform as sex slaves in front of a video camera,
and then strangling them. In one of Canada's most sensational cases,
Bernardo denies killing the girls, but has admitted that he and his
ex-wife abducted and sexually abused them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Volcano plan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601336</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OLD TOWN: As activity by Montserrat's volcano increases, Royal Marines
are developing a plan in case thousands of residents are evacuated to a
nearby island. Today members of Three Commando Brigade Logistic Regiment
are arriving in Antigua to begin work on evacuation centres that could
house some 4500 Montserratians in case officials order mass evacuations
from the tiny island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prince flies in</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601337</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HARARE: Prince Edward has arrived in Zimbabwe for a three-day visit.
