<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fears for future of Gaelic education</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601340</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's much vaunted proposal to extend nursery education
through vouchers to parents could undermine all the recent progress in
Gaelic education, endanger many jobs in Gaelic, and could end up doing
as much damage to the language as the 1872 Education Act.
The warning came yesterday from Mr Finlay Macleod, director of
Comhairle Sgoiltean Araich, the Gaelic Pre-School Playgroups
Association, whose establishment 13 years ago is widely seen as having
done more to save the Gaelic language than any other single measure.
At present, there are 2600 children in Gaelic playgroups and around
1600 in Gaelic medium schools throughout Scotland but Mr Macleod fears
that if the proposal to introduce vouchers is implemented in its present
form the language will start to retreat again.
''Our clear experience is that when children leave a Gaelic playgroup
and go into an English medium nursery class, they will not then go on to
a Gaelic medium primary school. Once we start seeing the numbers of
children in the Gaelic medium schools going down, every person connected
with Gaelic is going to be in a very serious position; television,
teaching, everyone.''
Mr Macleod said that initially he had thought nursery vouchers would
be a major help but now realised they would be damaging. The problem was
that to make a nursery viable under the voucher system, a minimum of 20
children would be needed, and there were many communities where there
would not be 20 children, or if there were, some of the parents would
prefer an English medium nursery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Policeman appeals to Lords over pension aliment</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601341</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR policeman, ordered by three High Court judges to pay his
ex-wife #500 a month of a pension which he will not receive until the
year 2001, plans to appeal to the House of Lords.
The new move was revealed yesterday by Fife Detective Inspector Derek
McEwan, just two days after the judges rejected his appeal against
Kirkcaldy Sheriff Gail Patrick's original ruling.
However, the 42-year-old officer, who lives in Kirkcaldy, already
faces a legal bill of ''tens of thousands of pounds'' and says he will
need the help of a ''sponsor'' to take his battle to the country's
highest court.
Mr McEwan said: ''This judgment will affect not only me but
potentially anyone who is married and has an occupational pension, and
also flies in the face of the clean-break principle.
''At the time of my legal separation approximately five years ago, the
nett proceeds from the sale of the matrimonial home were divided equally
between my ex-wife and me -- approximately #6700 each.''
He claimed that at that time and again two years later, his ex-wife
Anne, also 42, was ''offered and refused in the region of #47,500, that
is #2500 then and #45,000 upon my retirement.
''In effect, because of this judgment, overall she has 'lost'
approximately #15,000 including interest and I will now have to foot her
legal expenses as well as my own, which will amount to tens of thousands
of pounds.''
Mr McEwan also claimed, ''further evidence became available to me
after my divorce hearing which I believe would have been beneficial to
my case but which was not, unfortunately, because of the present legal
system, allowed at the appeal, which I think is unjust.
''In the meantime, I have no alternative but to lodge a note of appeal
to the House of Lords and I am actively seeking a sponsor/sponsors as I
will be unable to bear the substantial costs alone.''
When the couple, who were married for 15 years and have a son and
daughter, were divorced last year, Sheriff Patrick ruled that Mrs McEwan
was immediately entitled to a half-share of her ex-husband's police
pension rights, valued at #58,000.
Mr McEwan, who is said to live with another woman in a house with a
#75,000 mortgage, was ordered to pay the #27,000 by monthly instalments
of #500 with 8% interest but claimed he could not afford to and appealed
to the Court of Session.
Lords Penrose, Sutherland, and Brand said the sole issue was whether
the sheriff had been entitled to make the instalments order and ruled
that she had.
News of the Lords' decision was welcomed by Mrs McEwan, who lives in a
one-bedroom council flat in Methil.
She said that for four years she was unable to work due to ''stress''
and she now survived on just #99 a week from a job as a holiday complex
housekeeper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
