<DOCNO>GH950901-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Developer to revise plans for green belt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601353</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DEVELOPER has withdrawn his appeal to the Secretary of State for
Scotland after a plan to build 10 villas costing #1m each and four
#500,000 flats on green belt land was rejected by councillors.
A public inquiry was scheduled to be held in November. However, it
emerged yesterday that the Glasgow-based City Link Development Company
Ltd will now submit a revised plan to Stirling District Council for the
luxury homes development on grazing land at Mugdock, five miles north of
Glasgow.
A district council official confirmed yesterday that a letter had been
received from an agent acting for City Link, stating that its appeal to
the Secretary of State for Scotland concerning the Mugdock development
had been withdrawn.
Mr Ronnie McLetchie, director of the company, said yesterday: ''We are
re-appraising the site and design, and there will be a new application
going forward.''
The district council had said that the original proposal was contrary
to national planning guidelines and the local development plan.
The plan was also opposed by Strathblane Community Council, Bearsden
and Milngavie District Council, and Central Regional Council, on the
same grounds.
Stirling district's local plan specifically identified Mugdock green
belt to ''protect a key area of countryside from development''.
The council said one of the main concepts behind the approval of
Mugdock as a green belt area was to limit outward expansion from
Glasgow's suburbs and to prevent the merging of Strathblane and
Milngavie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
