<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cancer ward crisis over bed shortage</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH hospital has admitted that it does not have enough beds to
cope with seriously ill cancer and kidney patients.
Chiefs at Ninewells Hospital, Dundee, have revealed that the bed
shortage ''does not allow medical and nursing staff to provide the
quality of care they would wish to provide.''
There is an estimated shortage of 12 beds in the haematology and renal
ward at Ninewells, and patients have had to wait until a bed could be
found for them. Others have been ''boarded out'' to other wards, which a
hospital spokesman said ''impinges on the emergency medical receiving
ward and the other acute medical receiving wards, already under
pressure''.
Dundee Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust has pledged to discuss the problem
with Tayside Health Board in a bid to get extra funding to expand the
24-bed ward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Princess praises dietary research</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess Royal yesterday praised the work of the Scottish
Institute of Sports Medicine and Sports Science and said the research
work they carried out to help elite sportsmen had great spin-off
benefits.
The princess, patron of the institute, was speaking at its second
three-day ''festival'', during which topics discussed by international
experts included exercising in extremes of heat and cold and the
clinical aspects of exercise in diabetes and asthma.
She addressed the conference after listening to a lecture on sports
nutrition by Dr Ron Maughan, reader in environmental and occupational
medicine at Aberdeen University. Dr Maughan highlighted the complexities
of the dietary requirements of sportsmen.
The princess said the institute had a role to play to improve this:
''There are always people who are going to be participants in sport at
some stage in their career and the potential for long-term damage either
through immediate injuries or just ignorance in terms of their own
dietary intake is considerable.''
The princess said that in relation to nutrition she had always been
intrigued by two sets of people, flat-race jockeys and Mongolians.
''Flat-race jockeys don't seem to eat at all and take surprisingly
little exercise,'' she said. ''They could actually lose weight and be
fitter but that is taking a little time to get through to them.
''The Mongolians live on dairy products and meat and nothing else. By
anyone else's standards that would be a diet that would kill you. There
are extremes into which our nutritional knowledge must fit.''
Later, the princess, who is president of the International League for
the Protection of Horses, visited Belwade Farm near Aboyne, a rest and
rehabilitation centre of the league, which she opened in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NHS staff set to take action on pay award. Poll reveals disenchantment over service.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOSPITAL radiographers yesterday voted in favour of industrial action
ahead of next week's peace talks aimed at settling the long-running
National Health Service pay dispute.
Meanwhile, a survey today reveals that people are disenchanted with
the NHS, viewing it as a two-tier system which is in decline.
Underfunding and misallocation of funds were mostly blamed for the
state of the NHS.
Around 13,000 radiographers are now poised to take action in their
fight against a 1% national pay rise, to be topped up by 2% locally.
Around 75% voted for industrial action including strikes. Turnout was
around 9000.
A spokesman for the Society of Radiographers, whose members have taken
industrial action on only three occasions in the past 75 years, said it
was likely members would carry out emergency duties only on selected
days next month.
On Wednesday, it was revealed that 30,000 therapists had voted by a
90% majority for strike action on September 21. Broadly similar ballot
results are expected over the weekend in respect of around 30,000
General Municipal and Boilermakers members and next week from about
350,000 members of Unison.
Against this background, Mr Ken Jarrold, NHS director of human
resources, has called for pay row talks to resume next Monday -- an
invitation that is expected to be accepted by most of the health union
leaders who meet in London this morning.
The position of the non-TUC Royal College of Nursing is less clear
and, while the RCN is expected to attend today's union meeting, the
signs are that it might decide against participating in next week's
proposed talks.
The RCN, which recently changed its rules to allow industrial action,
shows no sign of staging a ballot and is more intent on pressing for 3%
local deals which if sufficiently widespread could be seen as a de facto
3% national deal.
Last night, the RCN was claiming to have received 272 ''3% no
strings'' offers and to be nearing the ''critical mass'' of 300 at which
it plans to start accepting them. However, it concedes that there are
areas like Scotland where 3% without strings is a rarity and where
''much work still needs to be done''.
Commenting on the latest ballot result, Mr Stephen Evans, general
secretary of the Society of Radiographers, said: ''This ballot gives a
clear indication to the Government of the strength of feeling among
radiographers.''
About 95% of those who took part in the NHS poll felt more money
should be made available for health services.
However, only 51% believed a change of Government would affect the
standard of service.
The survey was conducted on behalf of private medical insurers BCWA
(Bristol Contributary Welfare Association).
Market analysts Mintel questioned a nationally representative sample
of 2051 adults aged 18 to 54.
They found evidence that the private health insurance market was
growing as people lost faith with the NHS.
About 6.6 million Britons are now covered by private medical
insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cash inquiry delay denied</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN,MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601361</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW'S Town Clerk has denied there has been political interference
in an investigation of financial irregularities in a number of
Easterhouse community projects.
He was responding to questions from Conservative councillors who,
along with other opposition members, are alarmed that large sums of
public money appear to be unaccounted for.
An auditor's report on the allegations has been passed to the police.
In an unprecedented move earlier this week, all four parties --
Conservative, Liberal, Militant, and SNP -- sent a joint letter to
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth protesting that Militant councillor
Charles Stevenson was denied the right to ask questions when a council
committee was considering the matter.
At yesterday's full council meeting, the Conservative leader,
Councillor William Aitken, wanted to know when the auditor's report on
the matter was first seen by a senior member of the administration.
He also asked if there had been any attempt to suppress or delay
publication of the report's findings. In his view, this would result in
the council losing confidence in the member of the administration who
was responsible and would require to ask for his or her resignation.
However, the Town Clerk, Mr Tom Monaghan, firmly rejected any
suggestion of political interference.
He said he had not circulated the auditor's report to any member of
the council and asserted that there had been no political interference
in respect of that report.
Councillor Aitken said later: ''This matter is going to be pursued
until it comes out in the open in its entirety. The way it has been
handled leaves a very bad taste.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gould accepts damages</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601362</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Labour MP Bryan Gould has accepted undisclosed damages and
costs from London's Evening Standard newspaper over an article attacking
party leader Tony Blair which was wrongly attributed to him.
The Standard, in a joint statement with Mr Gould, acknowledged that
publication of the article -- actually written by Home Secretary Michael
Howard's son -- under his name had caused him ''considerable distress''.
The statement said: ''Readers of the article were seriously misled as
to Mr Gould's view of the present leadership and politics of the Labour
Party and what Mr Gould would be saying in his book, which is about to
be published.''
It added that, for his part, Mr Gould accepted that the paper had made
a ''genuine error'' which it corrected as soon as it was discovered.
The mistake, which occurred earlier this month, happened because of a
mix-up over faxes arriving at the Standard's office in London.
The error did not come to light for several days because neither Mr
Gould, who is now pursuing an academic career in New Zealand, nor the
article's real author, 19-year-old Nick Howard, was in the country when
it was published.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sacked oilman is to be reinstated</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Aberdeen company has been told to pay #21,670 compensation to a
sacked North Sea oil platform supervisor and also ordered to reinstate
him.
Kelvin International Services, of Queen's Terrace, sacked Mr John
Stephenson, of St Josephs Court, Hebburn, Tyne and Wear, in August 1994
for gross misconduct.
Mr Stephenson started work in 1987 with the company, which provides
catering and hotel services to offshore installations.
He was one of the facility supervisors on the Alba Northern platform
operated by Chevron and ran the Bond -- a small room with a serving
hatch, normally open at meal times, which sold sweets, stationery, and
telephone cards.
On May 27, 1994, a mechanic inspecting the roof space above the Bond
found a box containing 200 phone cards.
When a check was made of the BT cards held by the helicopter landing
officer, 600 were found to be missing.
After investigation, Mr Beach, a handyman on the platform, admitted
stealing a box of BT phone cards from the helicopter landing officer's
safe, after the keys had been left unattended, and selling them in the
Bond.
Mr Stephenson was then called to a disciplinary meeting on August 4,
1994, and sacked. His appeal against dismissal failed because Miss
Caroline Black, the divisional director, felt Mr Beach was protecting
the supervisor.
The tribunal, in deciding Mr Stephenson had been dismissed unfairly,
stated: ''The Bond also doubled as an office with the result that the
applicant was not the only person with access.
''The applicant had allowed Mr Beach, whom he trusted, to serve from
the Bond and Mr Beach had undoubtedly sold some of the missing cards.''
A Mr Gordon Fyvie also had keys to the Bond but wasn't interviewed in
connection with the theft and neither was the helicopter landing
officer.
The tribunal added: ''This matter caused us some concern and we were
not convinced that an employer carrying out a reasonable investigation
would have failed to interview either of these gentlemen.
''We are not satisfied that the employer had carried out as much
investigation as was reasonable in the circumstances of this case. The
application therefore succeeds.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drugs death man was told of risks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 23-YEAR-OLD man found dead after taking one of medicine's strongest
painkillers was warned about the dangers of drugs, his father said
yesterday. The drug also left three teenagers seriously ill in hospital.
Mr Daryl Elliott, a father of two children, was found collapsed beside
his unconscious 16-year-old girl friend on Wednesday by his mother at
her home in Birtley, near Gateshead.
His father, Christopher, 46, said he had often warned his son, an
amateur boxer and fitness enthusiast, of the dangers of drugs.
''I told him not to be stupid by taking drugs because he couldn't
train properly.
''I was not surprised to hear about these drugs because he has been
like that before.
''Daryl has come here a couple of times and you could tell that he had
taken something,'' Mr Elliott added.
The morphine sulphate tablets, a pure form of opium, are used in
cancer treatment.
Police said Mr Elliott's girlfriend was lucky to be alive. She
swallowed up to three tablets but survived because she was lying on her
side and not on her back with her airway blocked when she collapsed.
Another girl, a single mother, and a boy, both aged 16 have been taken
off the critical list in the intensive care unit at the Queen Elizabeth
Hospital, Gateshead.
All four victims knew each other and were from the villages of
Wrekenton and Birtley.
Police yesterday issued urgent warnings to parents to check that their
children had not bought any of the fluorescent blue and green tablets.
The alert began when Mr Elliott and his girlfriend were found
suffering from apparent overdoses.
At hospital, it was found the other two teenagers had been admitted in
the early hours of the morning suffering from the same symptoms.
Detective Inspector Gil Smith said of the drug: ''A single tablet is
enough to be life-threatening.
''It is highly dangerous and there may well have been other youngsters
who have bought them. It could still be in circulation.''
Police have urged parents whose children may suffer from vomiting or
sleeplessness to contact a hospital immediately.
Detectives yesterday were questioning a man about the illegal sale of
tablets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Development agency buries poor image with investment and jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LANARKSHIRE is finally moving into what is called its ''post-steel
economy'' with the local development agency yesterday announcing a
successful year for attracting firms to the county.
Mr Ian Livingstone, chairman of Lanarkshire Development Agency, said
they were burying the image of ''darkest Lanarkshire'' with significant
new employment and investment.
LDA's annual report, issued yesterday, said 29 inward investment
projects had been attracted to the county which would lead to the
creation of more than 2000 jobs.
Manufacturing exports from Lanarkshire firms continued to rise and 274
new business ventures were launched with LDA support.
The railfreight link to the Channel Tunnel was running five scheduled
services to the Continent, and Strathclyde Business Park, one of LDA's
biggest successes, had so far attracted 50 firms employing 1000 people.
In addition, Lanarkshire Enterprise Zone -- a series of sites which
give companies tax breaks, rates holidays, and other incentives -- was
beginning to take off. Seventeen companies are moving to the sites,
creating more than 2200 jobs in the next three years.
One criticism of enterprise zones in the past was that they simply
displaced jobs from one part of the country to another. LDA claims its
vetting policies have ensured that as many of the jobs as possible are
new.
The agency spent more than #51m in the past financial year including
#15m on training schemes for the unemployed and #14m on creating the
various business sites.
The next critical phase for the agency is the redevelopment of the
Ravenscraig steelworks site. British Steel has begun demolishing the
buildings and, in a few days, will be issued with the waste licence
which allows it to move the contaminated materials on site.
Much of the contaminated soil will simply be moved to areas where
there will be no building, and grassed over. The concrete in the large
cooling towers will probably be used as bottoming for new roads on the
site and infilling basement areas.
The development agency, with the local council and British Steel, will
start redeveloping the site next year, once British Steel has finished
the initial demolition and decontamination work.
Yet to be decided is when the site's landmark, the large blue
gasometer with Ravenscraig written on the side, will come down.
LDA chief executive Archie Bethel would prefer it was demolished
immediately, to let people know that redevelopment has started. Others
have become quite attached to it and prefer it to remain as a totem for
as long as possible. British Steel has the final say.
Not all the news was good for Lanarkshire last year. Large inward
investments by Samsung and Siemens considered Lanarkshire but plumped
instead for North-east England.
Mr Bethel agreed that such losses were disappointing but said he was
confident that any major mobile investment in Europe would be looking at
Lanarkshire and that eventually their turn would come.
Other bad news was the departure of Hayward Tyler from East Kilbride
and the closure of Rolls-Royce's aero engine design division.
''They are stark reminders that jobs are still being lost,'' said Mr
Livingstone. ''There is certainly no room for complacency.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>WRVS gift to aid diagnosis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE provision of important diagnostic equipment for Ayr Hospital moves
a step closer today with a donation from the Women's Royal Voluntary
Service.
A cheque for #100,000 will be handed over to Mr Douglas Brown,
chairman of South Ayrshire Hospitals Trust, towards Magnetic Resonance
Imaging equipment.
The equipment is being funded jointly by trust and public funds and
will be available to patients in Ayrshire and beyond.
Mr Brown, a former orthopaedic surgeon, said: ''MRI produces a
high-quality image which will allow our surgeons and physicians to make
speedier diagnoses and treatment for our patients.
''It will be especially helpful in orthopaedics, vascular, ENT, and
soft tissue injury and can indeed avoid the need for actual explorative
surgery because of its clarity and definition.
''The support of the WRVS to this hospital is really phenomenal. Last
year, they gave us #80,000, which went on eye equipment.''
Sir Donald McLean, chairman of Ayrshire Medical Support, which is
involved in the project, said: ''The joint investment of over #1m is a
real boost for medicine and importantly patients in Ayrshire.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cleaner dip at seaside</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BATHERS are taking the plunge in cleaner waters in Scotland, according
to a Scottish Office report published yesterday.
In the last seven years, the number of bathing waters meeting EU
standards has increased by 18% in Scotland.
Last year, 70% of waters complied with European standards compared to
52% in 1988.
Scottish Environment Minister Lord Lindsay said: ''Families coming to
the seaside to let their children swim or paddle want the reassurance
that the sea is clean and unpolluted by sewage.''
Over the last two years, all bathing waters on Scotland's east coast
have met European standards and it is hoped that investment will result
in similar results on the Ayrshire coast.
Lord Lindsay launched the report ''Scottish Bathing Waters: Progress
Towards Compliance'' at Arbroath beach yesterday.
Waters at the Angus town failed to meet EU standards before a new
sewage outfall became operational four years ago.
Lord Lindsay pledged the pace of investment to improve waters over the
next 10 to 15 years would quicken and estimated that funds needed would
be around #5000m.
He added: ''The rewards, however, will be bathing water of
unparalleled quality and safety and a sewerage infrastructure ready to
meet public hygiene standards well into the next century.
''The new water authorities have the expertise to implement this
massive programme and the Government expects them to meet the challenge
as efficiently and cost effectively as possible.''
Private sector money is also expected to play a significant role in
the investment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police hunt Marine missing in Falklands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MURDER squad detectives based in Torbay, Devon, last night flew from
RAF Brize Norton to the Falkland Islands, to investigate the
disappearance of a Royal Marine -- 18 months before the outbreak of war
with Argentina.
''A lot of people on the Falklands have been harbouring a secret for a
long time and we are now hoping that we can get to the bottom of it,'' a
spokesman for Devon and Cornwall Police said yesterday.
''We are not sending officers on an 8000-mile journey for nothing.''
Marine Alan Addis, 19, from Hull, went missing on a remote settlement
of the Falklands 15 years ago.
Police hope the sacrifice of British troops in retaking the Falklands
might encourage islanders to search their consciences and, finally, come
forward with the truth of what happened that evening.
In 1980, Marine Addis and fellow commandos took a small steamer from
Port Stanley to the remote North Arm community on East Falkland.
They knew that a ceilidh was to take place and, in those pre-war days
in the Falklands, this was a big night out.
He was one of a party of six commandos training local volunteers to
protect the islands from invasion but their tour of duty was about to
end and they were out for a good time.
There is no doubt that a lot of drink was taken that evening. Most
seemed to have a good time. However, on the journey back to Stanley, it
was noticed that Marine Addis was not on board.
An inquiry was conducted by the local police force -- which at that
time consisted of one man, trained by Devon and Cornwall Police, and one
other.
The initial report suggested Marine Addis must have died in an
accident. However, his body was not recovered.
Mrs Ann Addis, mother of the marine, who is now presumed dead, was not
prepared to let the matter rest and has been campaigning for the
investigation to be re-opened.
As a consequence, the Royal Falkland Island Police, now a force of 17,
did re-open its files and sent a report to the Devon and Cornwall
constabulary -- which has trained the officers who have moved to the
island since the war with Argentina -- and new lines of inquiry were
opened.
In all, more than 50 people were interviewed in the UK. They include
former Marines and one-time residents of the Falklands who had returned
to Britain.
Never at any stage has it been suggested the colleagues of Marine
Addis may have been involved in what is now, clearly, a murder inquiry.
Police suspect residents know more than they have been prepared to say.
As a consequence, Detective Chief Inspector Bob Pennington and
Detective Sergeant Steve Turpin are to continue the inquiry. They will
be followed shortly by two constables who will, via satellite, be able
to link with the Home Office's major incident computer system.
While they are following a cold trail, it was made clear last night
that fresh information had opened up new leads.
A spokesman said: ''We are hopeful that this will lead to a definite
conclusion. At the very least, we would hope to recover Alan's body,
which would bring some comfort to his mother.''
Prior to the detectives visit, Mrs Addis made an emotional plea on
video, urging those who might throw light on her son's death to come
forward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lawyer fails in #100,000 damages bid.  No ruling on who will pay for legal costs.</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601369</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SOLICITOR has failed to win #100,000 in damages from a rival lawyer,
who is said to have described him as ''a conman and an arsehole'', and
he could now face a #50,000 bill for legal costs.
Lawyers and former friends John Justice and Tom Boyd, who practise in
the Angus town of Kirriemuir, fell out over the sale of a local bakery,
and later comments that Mr Boyd is said to have made about Mr Justice.
Mr Justice sued Mr Boyd for #100,000, claiming defamation, in a case
which centred on letters from Mr Boyd to the Law Society, comments made
by Mr Boyd to a woman client, and a statement allegedly made by Mr Boyd
in a local hotel.
However, Sheriff John McInnes has ruled that Mr Justice is not
entitled to damages as he failed to prove that Mr Boyd was motivated by
malice.
The sheriff has reserved his judgment on the question of who will foot
the hefty bill for costs of the six-day action, heard in January, May,
and July this year.
Last night, Mr Justice said that he was contemplating an appeal
against the sheriff's ruling and admitted that he feared ''a potentially
very large'' expenses bill ''in the region of #50,000'' for the failed
action.
Sheriff McInnes accepted that Mr Boyd had described Mr Justice and
another solicitor as ''conmen and arseholes'' in a conversation in the
Thrums Hotel, Kirriemuir, in October 1992.
He criticised Mr Boyd as ''a man who at times is prone to be impetuous
and to use language which is stronger than necessary, with the result he
may offend people, perhaps without realising he has done so''.
Sheriff McInnes added: ''In short, he struck me as a man who may at
times be insensitive to the feelings of others.''
However, the sheriff concluded: ''I am not satisfied that what Mr Boyd
said on that occasion demonstrates malice towards Mr Justice.''
Mr Boyd, a partner in Wilkie and Dundas solicitors, and Mr Justice,
the sole practitioner of Hambley's law firm, were former friends and
their offices are yards apart in the centre of the Angus town of
Kirriemuir.
Mr Justice last night commented: ''I am disappointed at the result. It
was an action which was raised in July 1993 and which has lasted a long
time.
''I have 14 days in which to consider an appeal to the Court of
Session and I will be taking advice from my QC.''
He added: ''A lot of the case hinged on whether malice could be proved
and the letters sent to the Law Society had qualified privilege.
''It was the 'conmen and arseholes' remark that prompted me to raise
an action.
''As a point of principle, I felt that I had to take action to stop
him saying such things again.''
Mr Justice has now sold his house in Kirriemuir and is considering
whether or not to continue his career as a lawyer.
Last night, his rival, Mr Tom Boyd, said: ''The sheriff's decision is
satisfactory.'' He added that an appeal by Mr Justice was ''not
unexpected''.
Asked if he stuck by the description of Mr Justice as ''an arsehole
and conman'' attributed to him, Mr Boyd replied: ''We did not lead any
evidence regarding the allegations made by Mr Justice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Six years for assault on former Hibs player</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN,LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601370</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TEENAGER was ordered to be detained for six years yesterday for his
part in a vicious assault on a former Hibernian footballer.
Ian MacKenzie, 17, admitted kicking 25-year-old Cameron Stevenson on
the head and body to his severe injury and permanent impairment outside
a nightclub in Lothian Road, Edinburgh, on April 16 this year.
The Crown accepted that the brain injuries suffered by the victim had
been caused by stamping and jumping on his head, for which MacKenzie, of
Great Junction Street, Leith, was not responsible.
Temporary Judge Hazel Aronson had deferred sentence for background
reports and yesterday, at the High Court in Edinburgh, told MacKenzie he
had repeatedly kicked his victim as he lay on the ground.
Originally, six men were charged with attempting to murder Mr
Stevenson, who played for Hibernian's second team between the ages of 15
and 17. He was punched and kicked and repeatedly stamped on and jumped
on as he lay helpless on the ground.
He was in a coma following the assault and suffered brain injuries
which have left him with memory and speech difficulties.
During the trial, the jury was shown a video film of the attack,
captured by security cameras on the roof of a nearby department store.
Two other men who were involved in the incident were also sentenced
yesterday.
Paul Fisher, 22, of Hutchison Grove, Edinburgh, who admitted kicking
Mr Stevenson on the body, had sentence deferred for a year. The Judge
accepted that he had not been involved in the more serious part of the
attack which caused the severe injuries.
A third man, James Ketchen, 20, of Wester Drylaw Drive, Edinburgh, was
ordered to be detained for three months after he admitted kicking Mr Ian
Sutherland, in a related incident in Lothian Road, on April 16.
Ketchen, who is already serving seven years for assaults in Edinburgh
streets, was cleared of attacking Mr Stevenson.
Mr Sutherland told the court that he was attacked after trying to get
help for Mr Stevenson. He said one of his attackers told him: ''We are
Hibs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#5m drugs raid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601371</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Police raided a flat in St John's Wood, north London, yesterday, and
seized a million tabs of LSD worth up to #5m, in one of the biggest
raids of its kind.
Drugs squad officers arrested a 45-year-old woman and two men, aged 50
and 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Report highlights crime link with poor housing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601372</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE link between poor housing conditions and an increased level of
crime on some estates is spelled out in a new report by the Chartered
Institute of Housing.
It stresses that the poorest council tenants are six times as likely
to be burgled as those living in affluent suburbs.
Localities rife with crime, says the report, are frequently places
with the least resources to fight back as better-off tenants quit the
area.
To try to improve the situation the institute yesterday called for a
partnership between different groups to improve security, management,
and design on the UK's housing estates and substantially reduce crime in
the process.
It highlighted Dundee District Council's schemes, especially on the
Whitfield estate, to tackle crime and anti-social behaviour.
Housebreaking and total reported crime there had been cut while
security patrols had helped reduce vandalism costs by 60%.
However, the report claims that, in general, council housing has
become the preserve of the poor.
Ms Christine Laird, chief executive of the institute, said: ''Lack of
resources for design, security, and management initiatives has produced
a lack of resistance to crime on the poorest estates.
She warned: ''We are in the process of creating not only crime-ridden
estates of last resort but also a tenure of last resort, namely local
authority housing.''
Shelter Scotland said the report did not sufficiently address the
place local authority housing had in Scotland.
Many Scots still chose to live in council housing -- a choice which
was increasingly being denied to them by lack of Government investment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Motorist left flat as AA mistimes its response</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A STRANDED motorist picked up the roadside telephone, pressed the
button for the AA -- tagged the Fourth Emergency Service -- and got the
speaking clock . . . repeatedly.
Finally, the frustrated driver, who had elderly passengers, including
one who was disabled, hit the button marked police, only to get the
unobtainable tone.
Mr Ross Wilson, a Windsor-based chartered accountant, who is in
Scotland on holiday, eventually raised the alarm by using a mobile
telephone to alert the motoring organisation's headquarters in
Basingstoke, Hampshire.
A recovery van turned up after 45 minutes at the lay-by near Fenwick
Moor, on the A77 Glasgow to Stranraer road, where AA box number 517 is
sited.
Mr Wilson, 46, who was with his wife, youngest son, and
parents-in-law, from Blantyre, said: ''It would be funny if it wasn't so
serious. I was flabbergasted to find the only response to hitting the
buttons was to be told the time or to get nothing at all.''
He had tried to contact the AA after turning in to the lay-by because
of a puncture and finding he could not remove the wheel.
Mr Wilson said: ''At least it happened in broad daylight and, thanks
to the mobile telephone, we did not have to drive on with a flat tyre.''
Yesterday, the AA admitted the telephone fault had been known for ''a
couple of days'', and said an investigation into the circumstances was
under way.
A spokesman for the organisation, which champions its advanced
technology in a drive for greater safety, said: ''We deeply regret that
it was out of action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fans urge Celtic to abandon tie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CELTIC have been urged to pull out of their European Cup Winners' Cup
first-round clash with Georgian club Dynamo Butami -- by their own
supporters.
The club has asked fans to delay booking tickets to the war-torn
region -- which has also been hit by a diptheria epidemic -- for the
first leg on September 14.
Civil war has been raging in Georgia since 1991 and the country's
leader was injured in a car bomb explosion this week in the capital
Tbilisi.
Mr Gerry Madden, of the Celtic Supporters' Association, said: ''Maybe
Celtic should just say they'll pull out of the tournament for the safety
of the players.
''If it's unsafe for the fans to travel, then it must be unsafe for
the players as well and they too have families. Perhaps this is an
occasion when Celtic should make a stand.''
The official party will fly to Tbilisi then take a hazardous six-hour
drive to reach the Black Sea resort of Batumi but Mr Madden said the
difficulties of making the trip would not deter the fans.
''If Celtic do play the tie, they know there is no way they will stop
supporters travelling, because people who have made their minds up will
do their best to get there.
''It would be hypocritical of me to tell supporters not to travel
because if possible I will be there but I would say to anyone wishing to
go to take as much protection as possible.''
Celtic, whose request to have the tie switched to another venue was
turned down by Uefa, still are waiting to hear from security adviser
George Douglas, who has visited Georgia to assess the situation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Syndicate to take on pools firm</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601375</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE syndicate which lost out on a #2.3m pools jackpot when a coupon
collector failed to put on their line, has raised the money to take on
Littlewoods in the civil courts and is hiring a top QC.
The dreams of the five ScottishPower workers in Falkirk were shattered
when Littlewoods, which never received the winning coupon, refused to
pay out and insisted it did not employ collectors.
The pools giant claimed: ''They are the agents of the client, not
Littlewoods.''
Yesterday, Mrs Mary Ferguson, wife of syndicate member John, from
Dunipace, Stirlingshire, said: ''We have now raised the #35,000 to take
on Littlewoods.''
The syndicate's Glasgow-based solicitor, Mr Cameron Fyfe, confirmed:
''I am now consulting a QC in regard to a civil court action on behalf
of the syndicate.''
Collector Cameron Baxter, 27, of Stirling, pled guilty at the High
Court in Edinburgh, last week, and will be sentenced this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Braveheart star given role for SNP too</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE,SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601376</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FILM star Mel Gibson is being pressed into the cause of Scots
independence in a leaflet campaign based on his role as William Wallace
in the film Braveheart, which has its European premiere at Stirling on
Sunday.
His picture appears on a leaflet which SNP activists will distribute
outside screenings of the film, proclaiming that ''independence isn't
just history''.
The star's photograph is central to the SNP handbill, gazing out from
the leaflet in a plea: ''Independence -- we need it more than ever.''
The party made it clear yesterday that it was not advocating the
broadsword as a way forward, pointing to its wording in the cinema
handbill: ''Today it's not just bravehearts who choose independence --
it's also wise heads, and they use the ballot box.''
The SNP plans to distribute the leaflet outside cinemas all over
Scotland to build on the sentiment generated by the Hollywood treatment
of the patriotic hero.
They have even taken the precaution of making use of a specific
photograph of Mel Gibson in the central role which is not copyright of
the film-makers themselves.
However, SNP chief executive Michael Russell said yesterday that he
expected no intervention from the film-makers, as party canvassers were
planning to hand out the leaflets around screenings without making
trouble.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Sticky tape' teacher awaits ruling on future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601377</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE headmaster who gagged a pupil with sticky tape and was convicted
of assault will not know his career prospects for another two months.
Alex Christie, 46, was convicted of assault and fined #350 at Falkirk
Sheriff Court on June 12 after the classroom incident in February.
Christie, head of Carmuirs Primary School in Falkirk, is suspended on
full pay pending investigations by his employers, Central Regional
Council, and the General Teaching Council.
Yesterday, it emerged that the region was waiting for the outcome of
the GTC's investigation, which was not expected for two months.
A region spokeswoman said: ''We are awaiting the result of the GTC
investigation.
''Any decision we might make would be pointless if, for example, Mr
Christie were struck off.''
An outcome is expected by late October or early November.
The headmaster was standing in for another teacher at the school when
he gagged the 10-year-old boy for being a chatterbox.
He made the young pupil stand for 10 minutes before removing the tape.
The youngster's mother reported the incident to police.
Mr Christie has refused to comment until disciplinary proceedings are
complete.
</TEXT>
