<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000158</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000158</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peak of hot air ballooning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601378</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO balloonists hopped over Britain's highest mountain yesterday --
and set a new record on the way.
No-one had ever managed to fly a hot air balloon over the summit of
Ben Nevis before.
Pilot James Ireland and team leader Christian Brown of Richard
Branson's Virgin Ballooning Team became the first men to make the flight
over the Roof of Britain.
Mr Ireland said: ''It was an incredibly difficult flight because of
the shifting wind currents as you rise through the glen. We made it in
the end but it was touch and go whether we would get over the summit.''
Low cloud covered the top of the ben at the original launch time of
5am, so the team waited to see if the weather improved. At 6.30, Mr
Ireland decided to give it a try, although the clouds were still within
a few feet of the lofty peak.
As the 94ft-tall balloon neared the summit of the 4406ft high
mountain, a sudden gust of wind threatened to blow it off course.
Mr Ireland, one of only a handful of professional hot air pilots in
Britain, needed every bit of his years of ballooning experience to avoid
getting swept away from the peak.
However, he pulled the craft around and cruised over the summit,
missing the cairn on top by inches.
Mr Brown said: ''It is a great feeling to do something no-one else has
done before. The only disappointment was that there was nobody on the
summit as we went over -- but it was early in the morning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000159</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000159</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Holiday price war breaks out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601379</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 1996 summer holiday price war broke out yesterday -- only days after
most of the brochures were sent out.
After leading high street travel agent Going Places announced 10% off
many prices, rival A T Mays yesterday said it would cut up to 12% from
several Mediterranean packages.
The reductions will apply to the thousands of holidays which go on
sale today following the launch of brochures by most leading tour
operators this week.
Early bookers can cancel out the near-10% increase in Spanish prices
that the companies have been forced to introduce.
Later, Going Places and rivals Lunn Poly announced discounts of up to
12%, with Going Places later raising its cuts to 14% on some holidays.
Mays' 12% discounts apply to Sunworld's Greece and Beach Villas
brochures and also to First Choice's Freespirit holidays, selected
Cosmos breaks, and Inspirations' Balearic Islands and Spanish mainland
holidays.
It is also taking 10% off brochure prices of virtually every other
leading holiday company, including Thomson, Airtours, and First Choice.
''With fewer holidays on offer for next summer, this is a good time to
book early,'' said Mays' managing director Jamie Moffat.
Launching Thomson's brochures on Wednesday, managing director Charles
Newbold had been scathing of the quality of British resorts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police team warns there is nowhere to hide for dealers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601380</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DRUGS traffickers were given a blunt message by Chief Constable Leslie
Sharp yesterday -- there will be nowhere to hide in Strathclyde.
Mr Sharp was speaking at the launch of the enforcement phase of
Operation Eagle, the Strathclyde Police initiative to reduce the supply
and demand of drugs and end the misery they cause.
For the next 90 days, Mr Sharp's officers will be increasing their
efforts to crack down on dealers and enforce drugs legislation through
both covert and high-profile police operations.
The chief constable, speaking at a drugs seminar in Ayr organised by
the local police in an area which had 13 drugs-related deaths last year,
warned dealers that every officer under his command was committed to
this important phase of the operation.
He said: ''We have vast resources at our disposal and by targeting
them all at the drugs dealers, I have not the slightest doubt we shall
make a very significant impact.''
Mr Sharp said officers had been given specialist training and that the
necessary equipment to tackle dealers would be available to the 15
divisions of the force.
Detective Chief Superintendent Kevin Orr, newly appointed force drugs
co-ordinator, said: ''Dealers or traffickers in Strathclyde should be in
no doubt that they will be tracked down and brought to justice.
''We will be using the most modern and sophisticated equipment
available -- vehicles, surveillance and communications equipment, and
hydraulic machinery -- to open doors of homes which are sometimes like
fortresses to protect drug dealers.
''Doors don't get kicked in any more, they get opened up quietly and
the police are in before anyone knows what is going on and can try to
get rid of evidence.''
Mr Orr said many young officers showed extraordinary bravery in drugs
operations by blending in with the scene and making test buys of drugs.
The chief constable praised public response to Operation Eagle but
called for more assistance during the enforcement phase which would rely
heavily on information from the community.
''We realise that during an operation of such a nature, many people
who use drugs for their own personal use are likely to come to our
attention. I make no apology for that as such persons are breaking the
law, are an invaluable source of information about drugs dealers, and
can be referred to counselling and rehabilitative centres,'' he said.
Mr Sharp called for an end to the ''dithering and agonising'' over the
question of legalising or de-criminalising drugs and for everyone
concerned to get on with the job of doing something positive about drugs
problems.
Dr Leo Murray, consultant in the accident and emergency department at
Ayr Hospital, painted a black picture of the local drugs problem:
''Almost every day, I have to deal with young people who have decided to
get aff their heids with a cocktail of substances.''
The seminar heard that the Scottish Office has re-affirmed its support
for Operation Eagle and the battle against drugs and Sheriff Neil Gow,
QC, said the bench would be playing its part in the process.
The sheriff added: ''I am in no doubt that sentences will be getting
heavier to reflect society's unwillingness to accept people who deal in
drugs.''
Mr Jack Drummond, uncle of Andrew Stoddart, one of three young men who
died after taking ecstasy at Ayr's Hanger 13 last year, gave the family
perspective and said Andrew's parents live ''just an existence'' having
failed to come to terms with their son's untimely death.
He thanked local police officers for their help and assistance when
Andrew died and called for more Government money to be put into fighting
the drugs war.
Mr Drummond ended with a stark message: ''A generation of fine young
people are being destroyed by drugs. Please do not take the risk, don't
put your parents through the pain and trauma and remember, if you don't
buy the sellers can't sell.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forsyth orders mandatory drug testing for prisoners. Tougher action planned as crackdown on abuse problem in jails and on the streets gets under way.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN HOME AFFAIRS CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601381</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRISONERS in Scottish jails are to face random mandatory testing for
drugs, backed up by punishments for refusal or testing positive,
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth announced yesterday.
His plan to crack down on what is now acknowledged as a running sore
inside prisons, causing tensions and violence, has the support of the
independent prisons inspector, Mr Clive Fairweather, who stated
separately: ''I think it would be dangerous to leave it much longer.''
Speaking from Shotts prison, which along with Glenochil was once
recognised as the most volatile in the Scottish system, Mr Forsyth said:
''I am determined to tackle this problem.
''Drug abusers need support to enable them to recover from their
addiction and the Scottish Prison Service has a number of programmes
which aim to provide that. But these need to be accompanied by a clear
message that drug taking in prison will not be tolerated.''
Mr Forsyth was responding to concerns expressed by Mr Fairweather in
his annual report.
Both men rejected suggestions that there was a clash of ideologies
between them over prison numbers.
Mr Forsyth made his position clear in an interview in The Herald on
Monday that there was a duty to make more prison space available in
Scotland to meet the disposals of the courts, while a central point in
Mr Fairweather's annual report, issued yesterday, was that fewer people
should be sent to prison.
However, Mr Forsyth said they were in agreement that people who had
committed serious or violent offences should be given long sentences
while there were others now in the system, such as fine defaulters, for
whom prison was inappropriate.
The idea touted by some Labour politicians that the courts should look
at overcrowding before determining prison sentences was unacceptable.
From their respective viewpoints, both men emphasised the need to set
in place regimes and programmes in the prisons which would allow drug
misusers to tackle their addiction with a clear objective of putting
people back into the community who had dealt with their problems and
were less likely to reoffend.
Asked where the extra money would come from to run testing and
rehabilitation programmes, Mr Forsyth said it would come from the
taxpayer who was already paying more than #26,000 a year for each
prisoner and had the right to expect value for money. That included
getting prisoners off drink and drugs.
He added that, at the first opportunity, he would introduce the
mandatory urine testing powers by statutory instrument, the powers to do
so having been given in the Criminal Justice Act.
He had asked the SPS chief executive, Mr Edward Frizzell, to bring
forward a phased programme with the aim of testing 10% of prisoners a
year.
He rejected the idea that random urine testing would cause
instability. The Home Office experience in the eight English prisons
where it had been done was that many prisoners welcomed it.
In a wide-ranging report, Mr Fairweather earlier said it was probable
that the extent of drug abuse in some Scottish prisons could be greater
than in the community as the concentration of those involved in the drug
culture was greater. He singled out boredom in even the best of prisons
as a potent factor.
The prison reform group, Sacro, welcomed Mr Fairweather's recognition
that fewer fine defaulters and short-term prisoners should be kept
inside by developing more alternative schemes.
Labour's Scottish home affairs spokesman, Mr John McFall, MP for
Dumbarton, said: ''There is a hollow ring to Mr Forsyth's statements
because there is no real commitment to new resources. If he is going to
convince us that he is Granny and not the Wolf, he will have to come up
with more positive measures backed up with new money.''
Former prisoner and editor of The Prisoners' Handbook, Mr Mark Leech,
said of Mr Forsyth's drug-testing measure: ''While it is to be applauded
in principle, in practice it will lead to dangerous situations
developing and possibly to riots like those last seen in the late
1980s.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601382</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Meanwhile, the Borders textile town of Hawick was plunged into gloom
last night with the announcement of another 100 job losses at the
knitwear company Pringle of Scotland.
There will be 92 job losses among production and warehouse workers in
Hawick, plus nine job losses at Berwick. The Galashiels finishing site
is to close and in addition Hawick and Berwick will go on to a four-day
week from this Monday.
The redundancies follow a total of 500 Scottish job cuts by the parent
company Dawson International in May -- nearly 100 in Hawick -- which
also saw Dawson managing director Nick Kuenssberg and Pringle managing
director Graham Hayward leaving with severance deals worth more than
#1m.
In addition to the Pringle cuts Hawick has suffered, this summer has
seen the loss of nearly 150 other jobs at Dawson United Brands and a
major abattoir.
Last night, provost Myra Turnbull said: ''The latest Pringle
redundancies are a body blow to Hawick and the four-day week is also bad
news for families and will have a knock-on effect on shops and other
businesses in the town. I had a meeting with Pringle's new managing
director Peter Forrest after the May job losses and we all hoped then
that those painful cuts would be the end of it. Today's news is
desperately disappointing.''
Pringle, which announced substantial operating losses earlier this
year for the first time in its history, describes yesterday's cuts as
part of a series of measures to reduce costs and improve operating
efficiency.
A Pringle spokesperson said that, without giving cast-iron guarantees,
the management team believed yesterday's measures should see the end of
job cuts and an upturn in the fortunes of Pringle and its remaining 1300
workers. Pringle bosses will have a meeting in Hawick today with Mr
Harry Donaldson, chief textiles negotiator of the GMB union.
Mr Donaldson said last night: ''We will do everything we can to resist
these redundancies and I will be seeking a change of heart tomorrow.
Most of the men and women involved earn around #300 a week and will be
going into the job market with very small redundancy payments in a town
that has been hit by a succession of job losses in the past six months.
There will be significant hardship.''
</TEXT>
