<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#650m order for British jets will safeguard 2500 jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601383</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Aerospace yesterday won a #650m order to supply regional jets
to Belgian national carrier Sabena.
The deal will safeguard 2500 jobs -- including 400 at Prestwick -- at
a time when BAe is in the throes of a major regional aircraft upheaval.
Sabena is taking 23 BAe RJ85s which are built by the company's
regional jet subsidiary Avro.
The lion's share of the jobs, around 1900, are at Woodford, near
Manchester, where the 82-seater jets are assembled. The rest are at
Prestwick where the wings are built, and Filton, Bristol, where the
central fuselages are made.
Four of the jets will be delivered to Sabena by the end of 1995 and
all will have been delivered by the end of 1998.
News of the deal was welcomed at Prestwick by the head of public
affairs, Mr Peter Black. He said: ''This is great news on several
fronts. It will be more work coming through the door and will safeguard
jobs and increase our viability when we are competing with other
manufacturers. Sadly, I cannot say it will create new jobs.''
Avro's chief executive, Mr Michael Donovan, said: ''This order is a
major export achievement for the UK aerospace industry and for Avro in
particular.
''It helps underpin the remarkable progress our employees have made in
the turnaround of BAe's regional jet business.''
The order is just the boost BAe needs as it strives to get the EU to
agree its joint venture scheme with ATR, the Franco-Italian aircraft
manufacturer.
The scheme, announced last January, is expected to mean the loss of
1000 BAe jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ScottishPower pulls out of new #25m electricity station project as Government grant is refused. Human remains for generating plant</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID,ALF YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601384</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOSPITAL waste, including human remains, will be part of the fuel for
a new electricity generating station planned for Scotland next year.
Dundee District Council is negotiating for finance for the #25m plant
to replace its incinerator at Baldovie.
This will be necessary to meet EU emission rules which come into force
in December, 1996. It would mean severed limbs, diseased organs and
aborted foetuses joining other waste to feed power into the grid.
However ScottishPower, one of the parties originally involved, said
last night that it had pulled out after the project failed to get a
Government grant awarded for power-generation using non-fossil fuels.
Meantime, Baldovie has given a lifeline to Greater Glasgow Health
Board, whose eight hospital incinerators will have to close because of
interim regulations which come into force from the end of this month.
Only an eleventh-hour agreement with Dundee District Council --
expected to be concluded over the next few days -- will solve a problem
that the board has been trying unsuccessfully to head off for the past
four years.
The Baldovie incinerator is the only municipal one in Scotland,
licensed to deal with clinical waste, of which Glasgow produces 14 tons
a day.
Every day from October, the yellow-bag waste, which includes human
tissue, used dressings, hypodermic needles, radioactive isotopes, and
drugs, will be uplifted and driven across Scotland in sealed containers
to Dundee.
An attempt by a commercial firm to build an incinerator in Yoker,
Glasgow, with the health board as a principal client, ended when
planning permission was refused after a campaign by residents in the
area.
Lack of open space has made it impossible to build a conventional
incinerator within the city to meet the board's needs. Other boards with
larger landward areas have found it easier -- Ayrshire and Arran has an
incinerator at Crosshouse Hospital, near Kilmarnock, which is modern and
conforms to current requirements, and also accommodates Argyll and
Clyde's clinical waste.
Lanarkshire has an incinerator at Hartwoodhill Hospital, currently
undergoing commissioning. Lothian, Tayside, and Grampian are also
accommodated at Baldovie.
However, hospital managers are concerned that protracted negotiations
between the board and Glasgow District Council have come to nothing
after four years. They are also disturbed by the cost of the deal, which
could be as high as #700,000 a year and ties them for 10 years.
The board also could face legal opposition to the move from a company
called Bio-Sure, which is marketing a steam-sterilisation process. It
believes the contract would be in contravention of European guidelines
that the waste should be disposed of as close to the source as possible.
Bio-Sure director Mr Stuart Byron -- former chief executive of Ross
Hall Hospital -- said last night that it could be cheaper for the board
to contract to have a new technique provided locally than transport it
to Dundee.
An interdict to halt the contract was one option being considered,
although it would not seek to stop waste actually being sent to Dundee
after the deadline has run out.
The battle for the lucrative clinical waste disposal market is a
complex one. Various technologies are competing -- some have been
canvassed by the health board and rejected. Board sources yesterday
dismissed claims being made last week by a Clydebank company that it was
ready to sign up for a microwave destruction plant.
''There are several techniques which can prepare the waste to make it
fit for landfill dumping, on the premise that incineration is like using
a sledgehammer to crack a nut,'' said Mr Colin Clark, a lecturer in
civil engineering at Strathclyde University and expert on waste
disposal.
''Microwaving involves chopping up the waste and passing it through an
augur -- a hollow Archimedes screw. It is subjected to microwaves which
heat it up until it comes out the other end disinfected.''
In another version, Continuous Feed Augur, hot oil pumped along the
inside of the screw boils the waste to 100 degrees Celsius or more.
Gasification -- which Glasgow District Council was offering to the
Health Board at one time -- simply involves loading the waste into a
furnace and heating it with extremely hot air, rather than flames.
''It is starved of oxygen and when it reaches a certain temperature it
degrades, leaving a small amount of residue.''
Other methods include liquid disinfection, where the waste is soaked
in chlorine dioxide, passed through the Archimedes screw and pressed in
order to get the liquid out of it; and radio waves, which are emitted in
an oven to heat the waste up to disinfection levels.
Trusts from Tayside Health Board are expected to abandon Baldovie in
favour of a new plant being opened in mid-September by ScotSafe in
Arbroath.
A consortium of nine trusts from Tayside, Highland, Grampian, and part
of Forth Valley will send 5000 tons a year to go through the Continuous
Feed Augur system. A ScotSafe spokesman said the process reduced the
waste by 70% in volume and 30% in mass. What came out the other end
resembled the contents of a Jiffy bag and was ''as clean as a
freshly-washed salad.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Body found in boarded-up flat.  Neighbours demand to know why housing officials failed to realise pensioner was dead.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601385</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE body of a elderly man has been discovered in a boarded-up Glasgow
tenement flat where it lay unnoticed for several weeks.
Neighbours have demanded to know why housing officials failed to
realise anything was wrong and boarded up the flat a month ago.
Pensioner William Smith, 74, a single man who had lived in Winning
Row, Shettleston, for over 20 years, was reported missing by his sister,
Mrs Margaret Blake, of Haghill, three days ago after she had not seen
him for three months.
Police broke into the Scottish Homes-owned flat yesterday and found Mr
Smith's decomposing body. A police spokesman said it appeared that he
had been dead for several weeks, possibly months.
Neighbours Mary and Albert Horton, who moved into the top floor of the
tenement in March, said they had reported a burst pipe in the flat a
month ago.
Mr Horton said he had only seen Mr Smith on a couple of occasions but
had been concerned about his well-being.
''We heard rushing water and went down to the Scottish Homes office. A
plumber came and got into the flat through a broken window, then the
flat was boarded up at the back. ''Some kids put a brick through a
window and the rest of the house was boarded up. The police came and
looked through the letter box. I didn't know the old boy was in there.''
Mrs Horton said she had felt something was wrong. ''Call it women's
intuition but I was worried about the old man. It's a terrible thing
that has happened.''
Another neighbour, Mr James Jeffrey, said he had assumed Mr Smith had
been taken to hospital when the house was boarded up.
He said he had lived in the close next to the dead man's for 21 years
but said Mr Smith kept himself to himself.
''You usually saw him out at night going to the bakers to get pies.
No-one bothered because you don't think anyone's there if they boarded
the house up.
''A social worker came round here a week ago and knocked on the
door.''
Mr Michael Devlin, housing manager of Scottish Homes Gallowgate
office, confirmed a housing officer had called at the flat on August 14
but had no authority to force access.
''On August 16 an abandoned house report was drawn up but the
procedure is to wait 28 days before another report is filed and we can
legitimately gain access to the house.''
Mr Devlin said Mr Smith was not the sort to have left a broken window
or a burst pipe unattended and was a frequent visitor to the Scottish
Homes office.
''He came in here a lot to speak to people and got to know the
receptionist very well. When he went out he would walk up and down the
Gallowgate. He was very well known in the Parkhead area.''
A spokeswoman for Strathclyde Regional Council social work department
said it would investigate reports that a social worker had recently
visited Mr Smith.
Last night police informed Mrs Blake of her brother's death.
A spokesman for Scottish Homes said last night: ''We have launched a
full and detailed inquiry into the circumstances of this incident.
''Until our investigations have been completed and the full facts are
known, it would be inappropriate for us to comment further, other than
to express our obvious concern.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tagged offender is arrested again</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601386</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the first offenders to be tagged under new trials of an
electronic monitoring system has been arrested again, it was learned
yesterday.
The 29-year-old man, from Norfolk, was detained yesterday following a
theft allegation. He was not charged but given police bail until next
Thursday.
The man wore a court-imposed tag on his wrist, designed to trigger an
alarm and warn the private monitoring company if the offender ventured
out of his house during the curfew hours.
A Home Office spokesman said he could not comment on a particular case
but emphasised that the tagging technology was designed to monitor
curfew conditions. It did not compel an offender to respect such
conditions, he said.
The National Association of Probation Officers said the monitoring
equipment was working but it was concerned that the demands of the tag
on offenders were unrealistic.
''It is highly unlikely that offenders with chaotic lifestyles will be
able to adjust to the conditions of house arrest,'' assistant general
secretary Harry Fletcher said.''For many, the tag sets them up to
fail.''
It is thought that only four orders have been made in two of the three
pilot areas, Norfolk and Manchester, since the courts there were given
the power to impose tagging orders at the beginning of July.
No orders have been made in the third pilot area, Reading.
The nine-month trial is expected to cost #1.4m.
Tagging was used previously on defendants on bail in London,
Nottingham, and North Tyneside in 1989 before being abandoned because of
technical problems and cost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Young people's plight 'ignored'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601387</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Labour accused the Government of ignoring the growing plight of young
people out of work.
Figures released yesterday by Shadow Employment Secretary Harriet
Harman showed 216,000 young people under the age of 25 had never had a
job or a place on a training scheme.
Seasonally-adjusted figures for last month put the number of young
people who are unemployed at 647,100 -- a rise of 32,000 since April.
The unemployment rate among the under 25s currently stands at 15.5% --
almost double the rate for the overall workforce of 8.3%.
According to Labour's figures, youth unemployment rose between April
and July in every region apart from East Anglia, where the total
remained static.
At a Westminster news conference, Ms Harman described the figures as
''scandalous'' and said they represented the emergence of an alarming
trend which the Government ignored at its peril.
''This is not a statistical blip,'' she said. ''Many young people are
in danger of being alienated from the rest of a society which appears to
offer them little or no future.''
She said Labour would be presenting its own package of measures for
tackling the problem at the party's conference in October.
New proposals currently under consideration include raising the VAT
threshold for small businesses if they take on a young unemployed person
and lifting the 16-hour rule which prevents people claiming unemployment
benefit if they are studying for more than 16 hours a week.
The party is also further developing its plans for an environmental
task force, unveiled last year by Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown.
Other measures in the package include a #75-a-week tax rebate for
employers who take people who have been out of work for two years or
more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Grief of wife's death shattered bank manager</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601388</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COURT heard yesterday of the ''tragedy'' of a bank manager who
became a tramp and an alcoholic because of grief over his wife's death.
Dingwall Sheriff Court was told former TSB manager Alastair Chisholm,
62, has been ''on the road'' for the past three years.
As Chisholm sat gaunt, unshaven, and tieless in the dock, dressed in
grubby and crumpled sports jacket and trousers, fiscal David Hingston
told Sheriff James Fraser: ''This is a tragedy you see sitting before
you.
''It is distressing that a man of his background finds himself in this
position.''
Chisholm, of no fixed abode, admitted that on the previous day he
caused two breaches of the peace in nearby Muir of Ord by frightening
girls aged eight and nine as they walked home separately from school
through a park at lunchtime and later in the afternoon.
He was lying asleep in the grass with his tweed cap over his eyes when
he was wakened by the passing girls. The former bank manager got to his
feet and walked towards them. They ran off.
Added the fiscal: ''I can't see what the interest was. He has only one
previous conviction and no history of interfering with children. He had
not been hanging about the school.
''I think it was just a case of a chronic alcoholic being disturbed
out of his sleep.''
Defence lawyer Roger Webb said Chisholm, who received a pension of
#470 a month, delivered to his brothers' home in Smith Avenue,
Inverness, had changed when his wife died 15 years ago. He retired in
1975.
He added: ''He has been on the road for the past three years, living
rough.''
Sheriff Fraser fined him #100 and no time to pay. With no money on his
person, Chisholm was taken off to the police cells, then to Porterfield
Prison in Inverness to face the option of seven days behind bars. His
brother is presently on holiday in Norway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A toast to an advertising breakthrough</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGINTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601389</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S official. Whisky drinking is no longer the remit of old bearded
men in torn woolly jumpers but a sure sign of a younger modern man keen
to commit. The television premiere tonight of an advertisement for
Bell's whisky breaks broadcasting history as well as shattering
entrenched stereotypes.
Viewers across Scotland and the north of England will watch a man in
his late twenties explain to his friends in a chic modern pub that he
will still be there for them. Just a little more distant, now that he
has found true love, though not with the bottle.
The #2m campaign for Bell's eight- year-old blend, run by United
Distillers, does push the idea that the most famous Scottish spirit is a
cool drink for a late twenty and thirty-something crowd. However, it
does not desert their more regular clientele.
To illustrate the idea of their drink as a product of refinement and
quality, the advert will show the different stages of whisky distilling,
cut between a young man's decision to commit to his sweetheart.
This contrast between the ''craft'' and the ''crack'' will be the
focus of a campaign which begins with a 60-second advert tonight, then
uses a 40-second advert 25 times over the next two weeks.
Those who receive Border Television will be the first people in
Britain to see an actual whisky advert on television. The advert will be
broadcast for the first time at 8.15pm during an episode of The Bill.
Though never banned by law, liquor companies entered into a voluntary
agreement not to advertise. However, pressure has been exerted over the
past couple of years to end the ''gentleman's agreement''.
Alcohol Concern remains worried that the adverts will encourage young
people to drink spirits at an earlier age.
A spokesperson for Bell's whisky said: ''We think people will be
surprised at the end of the advert when they discover that it is
actually advertising whisky.
''It's really quite subtle. The two strands are saying to younger
people, not young people -- as it is the 25 to 30 age group we are
looking towards -- to think again about whisky. It is relevant and it is
a quality product.''
Scottish viewers of Channel Four will see the advert at 9.15pm during
Ellen while viewers of STV can view it during Shogun at 9.20pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No forecast of weather figures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WEATHERMEN may be among the more prescient members of society but they
were taking no wagers yesterday on how many records had been broken by
the month of August. Driest, sunniest, and warmest were just three of
the bets being laid by those of us who favour a wager.
''It's too close to call at the moment,'' said a spokesman at London
Weather Centre, where forecasters were waiting for the last spot of
drizzle, the final burst of sunshine and for dusk to settle.
''We are waiting for the last figures to come in and even then it will
take some time to be sure,'' said the spokesman.
''There will probably be little more than a decimal point here and
there. There will be some individual records broken but it is very
difficult to predict.''
Britain was heading towards its driest August on record until the past
week, when light showers passed through most parts of the country.
Even so, experts say only 25% of the average rainfall for the month
fell on England and Wales. Some places had only 10%.
In Scotland, Glasgow experienced only 21% of the average rainfall for
the month while for Aberdeen and Lerwick it was one of the driest on
record.
There is no doubt that Britain had one of its best Augusts and it was
as good as the scorching summers of 1947 and 1976.
The hottest day was on August 1, when 94F was recorded at Heathrow
Airport. Temperatures in the month were in the 80s and 90s until the
final week.
Glasgow got close to its highest temperature -- 88F recorded in August
1975 -- when August 11 hit 86F. Aberdeen, however, made it into the
record books again when it hit 86F on August 21, while Kirkwall had its
hottest day yet for August with 76F on the 25th.
London had its sunniest month on record with 287 hours of sunshine
compared with 273 in 1989. Parts of the West Country, West Midlands, and
southern England are expected to equal or surpass this figure.
Glasgow will not be able to beat its August 1947 record when no rain
fell on the city. Scotland and Northern Ireland were also wetter than in
1947.
A Glasgow Weather Centre spokeswoman said the city had, however,
smashed its sunshine record for the summer with 730 hours compared with
the previous best of 643 in 1977.
Meanwhile, the spokeswoman said that September looked like starting
off on an unsettled note. However, she added that she was hopeful that
September, which is traditionally a good month in Scotland, would not
disappoint people.
Bookmakers, you have been warned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Workers' guarded welcome for Mitsui. Japanese in #56m move for Babcock</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT,WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601391</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS by Babcock International to sell a 75% controlling stake in its
energy division to Mitsui Engineering and Shipbuilding Company of Japan,
will have no adverse effect on the 3000 UK employees involved, including
some 929 in Renfrew and Dumbarton, it was claimed yesterday.
Executives of both companies took pains to stress that the #56m deal
would strengthen the prospects of the division, which will trade under
the new name of Mitsui Babcock Energy Ltd, thereby making existing jobs
more secure.
The news was greeted with ''guarded optimism'' by many of the workers
at Babcock's three operations in Renfrew and Dumbarton.
The partial withdrawal from its traditional base in power station
boiler, steam generator, and nuclear component manufacture comes at a
time when Babcock's boiler orders are at their highest for some years.
The takeover could become total as there is an option to sell the
remaining 25% shareholding to Mitsui (MES) within the next five years
for a further #12.5m.
Babcock chairman Dr John Parker welcomed the agreement as an important
development for both partners. As a result, Babcock's former energy
division would now be in a stronger financial position, enabling it to
better exploit its potential in world power generation markets.
This, he said, should be to the benefit of employees, customers, and
UK exports, as well as allowing Babcock to concentrate more actively on
its other key businesses. These include Rosyth Dockyard, which it
already manages and is currently bidding for, and several former BR
workshops, including Springburn, in Glasgow.
MES president Jiro Hoshino said that by combining the expertise of
both companies, advantage could be taken of opportunities in the global
market place, allowing MBE to ''grow the business''.
He declared himself very impressed with the strength of Babcock
technology and the commitment of its people.
MBE will continue to be headquartered in the UK under the chairmanship
of MES main board director Ken Saeki. The existing management team, led
by chief executive Duncan Fox, who operates from the Crawley, Sussex
site, is to remain in place, and Babcock group chief executive Nick
Salmon will remain on the board of MBE in a non-executive capacity.
Tokyo-based MES is a major international engineering and shipbuilding
group with a market capitalisation and network approximately five times
that of Babcock, which is itself a multinational with companies in 25
countries, contracts in 40, and about 11,500 employees.
The 929 employees at Renfrew and Dumbarton are perceived by many
people to be the rearguard of the Babcock operation, which once boasted
a local workforce of about 9000.
Paisley North Labour MP Irene Adams expressed hope that the move would
not spell ''another false dawn'' for the workforce who, she said, had
worked under the ''shadow of unemployment'' for too long.
CBI Scotland director Lex Gold said it was inevitable that
''alliances'' such as the one between Babcock and Mitsui would become
more common in an increasingly competitive global market place.
Mr Howard Jordan, chief executive of Scottish Engineering, said he was
''disappointed'' that control of a Scottish-based company had gone out
of the country.
Mr Cox assured The Herald that the company's manufacturing plant and
technology centre in Renfrew, and its tube plant at Dumbarton, which
between them employ 929, would continue to play ''a very important
role'' under the new regime.
Two of four Chinese boiler contracts signed in June, worth about
#125m, should guarantee work for at least two years at Renfrew.
Mr Graham McMillan, acting staff convener at the Renfrew manufacturing
plant, said the mood among the workers was ''more optimistic'' than it
had been for a while.
One worker, who declined to be named, said: ''The mood among staff is
one of guarded optimism. The problem with our business is that it is
very capital intensified and companies such as Babcock need financial
muscle to compete on the global market. It would appear we now have that
with Mitsui's intervention.
''While we have been through bad times and suffered more cutbacks than
we care to remember, this increases the optimism for the future.''
Another worker, on a more pessimistic note, said: ''Management are
telling us that Mitsui's involvement is great for the company but the
reality is that Babcock is finished.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>More drama for Taylor as eighth marriage goes sour</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601392</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ELIZABETH Taylor revealed yesterday that her marriage to her seventh
husband, former construction worker Larry Fortensky, is in trouble.
They met in the Betty Ford Clinic in California in 1988 where they
were both being treated for alcohol problems.
In a statement they said: ''We both need our space for a while so we
have agreed to a trial separation. We both hope this is only
temporary.''
Perfume company Elizabeth Arden cancelled the launch of her latest
fragrance Black Pearls but she says it will be coming out next year.
The 63-year-old actress is 20 years older than Fortensky.
Hollywood's veteran Daily Variety columnist Army Archerd said:
''Though they call it a trial separation, he has moved out.''
British film director Michael Winner said: ''As someone who has been
in love with Elizabeth Taylor for more than 40 years, I am very sad.''
Taylor had achieved stardom and fame but not happiness. ''When the
glitter and glamour is over you go home to a house and then it is you
and the person you are with that matters.''
Richard Burton's sister-in-law Betty added: ''It doesn't surprise us
at all. I didn't think it would last. I don't think any of us did.''
Fortensky was constantly at her side when she fought a life-and-death
battle against viral pneumonia in April 1990. They married in October
1991 at Michael Jackson's Neverland estate in California.
Critics described the marriage as ''beauty and the beast'' but Taylor
said: ''This time, with God's blessing, it's for keeps. He is the least
greedy man I have ever met.
Taylor's love life has always been tempestuous and sparked as many
headlines as her acting career.
Her husbands were hotel heir Conrad 'Nicky' Hilton, British actor
Michael Wilding, film producer Mike Todd, who died in a plane crash,
singer Eddie Fisher, actor Richard Burton, whom she married twice, and
then US politician John Warner.
London born of American parents, she began her career in Los Angeles
aged nine as a child actress in the film There's One Born Every Minute,
and achieved fame as the star of National Velvet.
She won Oscars for Butterfield 8 and Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf
but in recent years has concentrated on Aids charity work.
She has been dogged by ill-health for many years with back problems,
weight problems, and drink and drug problems. She has undergone two hip
replacement operations.
Taylor is estimated to have a personal fortune of more than #100m, and
one of the most fabulous collections of jewellery outside a royal
family.
The couple reportedly signed a pre-nuptial deal limiting his share of
the money to #2m should the marriage fail. Her four children pressed for
the agreement, according to reports
Her greatest love was Burton, who lavished her with diamonds, furs,
homes, and the yacht Kalizma, worth millions of pounds.
They met when they appeared in the film epic Cleopatra in 1962. Two
years later, she divorced her fourth husband Eddie Fisher and within 10
days had married Burton.
They were great stars, great lovers and, of most concern to the
film-makers, great earners, pulling down an estimated $100m.
Burton indulged his wife's love of diamonds and spent fortunes on
rings, necklaces and other jewellery. The most famous items were the
69-carat Idol's Eye diamond, made into a ring, and a #370,000 diamond
and ruby necklace once owned by Shah Jehan, builder of the Taj Mahal.
Their marriage lasted for 10 years, the longest of her marriages, but
in June 1974 they found life together impossible and divorced.
As well as the weddings, Miss Taylor has been engaged at least twice,
turned down an offer of marriage from the late billionaire publisher
Malcolm Forbes, and enjoyed a close friendship with actor George
Hamilton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman who killed baby walks free</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN who killed her baby by swinging him by his feet into the
stairs was allowed to walk free from the Old Bailey yesterday.
Suzanne Oatley was suffering from post-natal depression when she
killed 11-day-old Alexander in what Judge Gerald Gordon called a tragic
case. He imposed a two-year probation order on condition that
37-year-old Oatley receives medical treatment.
Oatley, of Hinchley Wood, Surrey, had admitted infanticide. The
secretary and linguist, who has worked in South America and the Middle
East, was unable to cope when her son was born.
''Perhaps we should have him adopted. I wish it was just the two of us
again,'' she told medical staff, referring to her lover, Mr Alan Lewis,
40, with whom she was besotted, said Mr Richard Horwell, prosecuting.
During her unplanned pregnancy, Oatley had sought an abortion, telling
doctors Mr Lewis did not want the baby. However, she later changed her
mind and told her GP he was being very supportive.
In fact, said Mr Andrew Trollop, defending, Mr Lewis had been
supportive throughout the pregnancy.
The international quantity surveyor had flown back from Nigeria, where
he was working, for Alexander's birth and because of Oatley's behaviour
took over the day-to-day care of the baby, to whom he was devoted.
Just 11 days after the birth, Mr Lewis went out for a quick drink
after caring for the baby all day. When he returned, he found Oatley and
the baby lying at the bottom of the steps. The baby died soon afterwards
in hospital from severe head injuries.
Mr Trollop said Mr Lewis and her parents stood by her. She now hoped
to start again with Mr Lewis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000174</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000174</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charterhouse headmaster resigns</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601394</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE headmaster of one of Britain's best-known public schools has
resigned, its governors said last night.
Mr Peter Hobson, head of Charterhouse School, Godalming, Surrey, left
because of ''personal reasons and ill-health'', according to chairman of
the governors Sir Anthony Laughton.
''I cannot add to the reasons that have been given for his
resignation,'' he said.
''The reasons we have given for his resignation are a matter of
confidence between him and the governing body.''
He said the circumstances that led to Mr Hobson's resignation were not
being investigated by police, adding: ''Why should they be involved in a
matter of health and personal reasons?''
Mr Hobson resigned as head of the #12,000-a-year school just days
before the new term starts next week. The first parents knew was a
letter received on Wednesday from the school's governors.
In it, Sir Anthony said his resignation had been accepted ''with
sadness''. Mr Hobson had served the school well during his two years as
headmaster, taking many new initiatives.
''It is a matter of great regret that he will not be at the school to
see them mature,'' it said.
The headship had been taken over by the school's second master Clive
Carter, and the governors' letter said they had ''total confidence that
the school's high standards will be maintained during the forthcoming
year under his leadership''.
Mr Hobson's departure came as another leading public school, Dulwich
College, south London, faced up to the suspension of its headmaster.
Mr Anthony Verity is understood to have been accused of sexual
harassment by a secretary at the school.
Mr Hobson, 50, who is married, arrived at Charterhouse -- founded in
1611 and one of the country's most expensive boarding schools -- two
years ago, after spending seven years as head at Giggleswick School,
North Yorkshire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dairy threatens to move in row over car park</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601395</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAJOR Scottish dairy company has threatened to relocate a Midlothian
depot employing 85 people if it fails to get local authority support for
a planning application for a car park.
The application has annoyed district councillor George Purcell, who
said yesterday he did not believe the business of East Kilbride-based
Robert Wiseman Dairies would be jeopardised if the application, which is
contrary to two local plans, was rejected.
''I am not too happy about the tone of the letter,'' said Mr Purcell,
who represents the ward at Loanhead where the company runs an operation
at Edgefield industrial estate.
In a letter to this week's planning committee, agents for the company,
seeking a change of use of agricultural land to parking space, said:''If
Wisemans do not obtain planning permission in respect for this strip of
land, then they will have no alternative than to relocate from Loanhead
where they rely on the local workforce.''
On Wednesday, the committee agreed by seven votes to four to grant
consent to the application which is being opposed by a number of
householders who claim the extension would increase noise and pollution
from lorries.
Planning officers recommended the application be refused as contrary
to the adopted Local Plan for the area and to the approved Lothian
Region Structure Plan. Mr Purcell said he fully supported this.
In the agents' letter, the company said it had suffered severe space
restrictions at the depot.
It emphasised it would include landscaping and screening measures and
maintained the industrial estate was well established before
construction of houses in nearby Mayshade Road.
Managing director Robert Wiseman said in a letter the company could
not allow the current situation to continue.
''Over the years, we have been a significant employer at Loanhead and
if we had no option but to relocate our operations, then this would have
a significant effect on the future of our workforce.''
In July, Robert Wiseman Dairies, which the previous month had bought
the Scottish milk distribution business of the Co-operative Wholesale
Society for #6.6m, announced it was to close a CWS dairy employing
around 70 workers in Titwood Road, Glasgow.
At the time, Mr Wiseman said the creamery did not meet the high
standards customers demanded and he also claimed the dairy had been the
subject of repeated complaints from residents over noise and traffic
movements.
The Loanhead planning application will now go to a joint planning
liaison committee representing Lothian local authorities and is expected
to be debated later by the full council. It may be called in by the
Scottish Secretary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lang gives power bid all-clear</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE, CITY EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601396</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE #1000m hostile bid by Glasgow-based ScottishPower for English
regional electricity company Manweb is to be allowed to go ahead.
Trade Secretary Ian Lang yesterday unexpectedly declined to refer the
bid to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission on the advice of the Office
of Fair Trading.
It is a decision which will be seen as seriously undermining the
position of Professor Stephen Littlechild, the controversial electricity
regulator who had argued for a referral.
The Trade Secretary also waived through, again on the advice of the
OFT, the two other electricity mergers where terms have been agreed,
Hanson's #2500m offer for Eastern Group and the #1100m bid from Southern
Electric International of the US for South Western Electricity.
In the stock market shares of the regional electricity companies
immediately soared in the expectation of a free-for-all in the sector as
predators move in, especially from the US where several power giants are
believed to be eyeing up the utilities.
Manweb itself rocketed 93p to 971p. This compares with a bid value of
around 980p in cash and shares but is well above the all-cash terms of
915p.
There had been strong speculation that the ScottishPower bid, the
first by a power generator for a distributor, was in particular likely
to be put before the MMC.
Professor Littlechild said it should be referred because it would
reduce the number of companies he compares to monitor competitiveness.
Mr Lang accepted that it raised different issues to the other two
takeovers. But he said the industry regulator can make licence changes
to satisfy concerns raised by vertical integration, which would result
from Scottish Power owning Manweb.
He had accepted assurances from ScottishPower to agree to appropriate
licence amendments.
Undertakings signed by ScottishPower included agreeing not to sign
contracts to supply Manweb with electricity, to make clear to customers
which company they were dealing with, and to ensure that Manweb sold its
stake in the National Grid when it is floated.
The Trade Seretary's decision was welcomed by all the electricity
companies including Manweb, whose finance director, Mr Stuart Siddall,
said the company was never relying on a referral and pointed to the
movement in its share price as justification that the ScottishPower
terms undervalued the company.
But the electricity go-ahead brought a storm of protest in some
political and trade union circles. Labour's industry spokesman, Mr Brian
Wilson, said it was another slap in the face for power customers who are
the captive market for these monopolies.
''By doing nothing Mr Lang has given the green light for a takeover
free-for-all without regard for protecting consumer interests,'' he
said.
The Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union's acting general
secretary, Mr Ken Jackson, said: ''This decision is sure to plunge the
industry into a further period of chaos and uncertainty as rumours
abound about further takeovers and mergers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tutu's lesson for Bosnia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601397</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Most Rev Desmond Tutu, Archbishop of South Africa, spoke yesterday
of his deep distress over the situation between Bosnians and Serbs --
but said lessons could be learned by looking at events in his own
country.
The archbishop was speaking in St Andrews, where he is leading a
Scottish Episcopal Church conference which is discussing the way forward
for the church in the twenty-first century.
''No-one who saw the Sarajevo marketplace scenes could have failed to
be moved and filled with revulsion.
''One just longs so desperately that people would realise that the
things that unite us are actually a great deal better than the things
that separate us,'' he said.
He gave said South Africa could be praised for saying: ''Look here,
there are people of different races, of different cultures, of different
religions, and affiliations, who are coming together, seeking to be one
nation, when everything has conspired to separate them.
''That kind of nightmare they have had has ended, and this one will
also end if we are looking for the things that unite us.''
The archbishop said he was full of deep anguish and agony looking at
television pictures of the elderly, and of children looking so
bewildered.
That, he said, showed the tremendous depths to which people could sink
while there were still ''wonderful things'' of which humanity was
capable, and the world had to be constantly reminded.
He said that out of such a cauldron of suffering, if the leaders could
get their act together, it would be possible for something new to
emerge.
Earlier, speaking alongside the Swilcan Bridge at the eighteenth hole
at St Andrews, Archbishop Tutu said he was delighted to visit
Scotland,''a lovely country'' for the conference, and to thank the
Scottish people for their support in the struggle against apartheid.
Prayer support from Scotland, he insisted, had helped his countrymen,
coupled with vociferous support from young Scots, in particular, in the
anti-apartheid movement, along with the boycott of South African goods.
The archbishop concluded his visit by confessing that he had been a
golf caddie as a boy -- in ebullient style admitting that he was good at
most sports . . . from the comfort of his sofa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boat death</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601398</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
One man died and another was taken to hospital last night after their
boat capsized on rocks at Boyne Bay, near Banff. Lorry driver Alexander
Johnston, 59, of Main Street, Portsoy, was dead on arrival at hospital
in Elgin. Mr John Bromham, 65, of Reading, was detained overnight for
observation in a Banff hospital. The two men had been on a fishing trip.
Mr Bromham swam ashore and raised the alarm. Mr Johnston was winched
onto a rescue helicopter from RAF Lossiemouth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950901-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950901-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>950901</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Missing diver is found alive</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601399</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DIVER was found alive yesterday 10 hours after he went missing in
Loch Long.
Mr Cameron Bell, 32, managed to crawl ashore and was found by a
passing cyclist while police divers were still searching the waters
where he had gone missing earlier.
Rescuers said he must have spent most of the time in the water and had
done very well to survive. Diving experts called it ''a miracle''.
Semi-conscious after his long ordeal, Mr Bell was taken by ambulance
under police escort to a decompression chamber at the Royal Navy's
submarine base at nearby Faslane.
Last night, a spokesman at the base said Mr Bell's condition was
''much improved''.
Mr Bell, a professional diver who runs a sports company in East
Kilbride, had been taking part in a late-night dive with three friends
off the loch's Ardgarten Point when he went missing about 1.30am.
His companions saw his torch go out. They then saw it come back on
again but when they went to investigate it was shining on the bed of the
loch with no sign of Mr Bell.
Helensburgh inshore lifeboat, coastguard auxiliaries, and Ministry of
Defence police launches began a search and a helicopter was scrambled
from the Royal Navy's HMS Gannet base at Prestwick. They were joined
later by a police underwater team.
As the hours passed, the rescue services began to fear the worst but,
at 11.30am, Mr Bell was discovered on the verge of a lochside road two
miles south of Arrochar by holidaymaker John O'Connor.
Mr O'Connor, 48, a PE teacher from Morpeth in Northumberland, said:
''I saw him lying on the verge, face down, with his hands out and a
knife in one hand, and I turned him on to his side.
''I said a prayer, hoping he wasn't dead, but I really thought he was
at first. His breathing was quite good but his pulse rate was quite slow
and his extremities were very cold.''
Last night, one of Scotland's most experienced divers told how easy it
was to become disoriented while under water. Mr George Mackie added that
diving in deep water could quickly affect your responses, making them
much slower.
''I don't know much about this incident at Loch Long but it looks to
me like a classic case of someone getting into difficulties and then
becoming more and more disorientated. It sounds like a miracle that he
managed to get ashore and survived.''
Mr Bell and his companions had planned to dive in an area where the
water was 18 metres deep. However, the spot beside the loch where he was
found was close to a trench 50 metres deep.
If he accidentally exceeded the depth he had intended to dive at, he
was likely to have suffered an ''O2 Bend'' attack, caused by oxygen
poisoning, which would have led to disorientation and intense pain.
Last night, one of the other divers in the group, Mr George Lees, 36,
of Marywood Square, Glasgow, said: ''It was an unfortunate incident.
These things happen very infrequently. I have not seen Gordon but I have
been told by the medical staff at Faslane that he is better. I am very
tired and, of course, very relieved it's all over.''
Other members of the diving party were Mr Brian Fallon, 34, of
Tanzieknowe Avenue, Cambuslang, Glasgow, and Andrea Russell, 29, a
female police constable with Strathclyde Police.
</TEXT>
