<HEADLINE>EU monitor team reported alive and well. Bombs drive Serbs to peace table</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>976601400</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NATO warplanes pressed on with fresh raids on Bosnian Serb targets
yesterday but a senior US envoy said serious peace negotiations were now
under way thanks to an ''immensely important'' breakthrough.
As the warplanes struck yesterday, Bosnian Serb television showed
pictures of five EU monitors alive and in Serb hands. All five were
believed to have been killed on Wednesday. A senior Bosnian Serb
official said later they had been released.
On the diplomatic front, US special envoy Richard Holbrooke said
agreement by the Bosnian Serbs that Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic
could speak for them had paved the way for the first substantive peace
talks in 16 months.
Twice during the day yesterday, RAF Harrier jump jets and Jaguar
strike aircraft took off fully ''bombed-up'' from their base at Gioia
del Colle in southern Italy, but had to return because of low cloud.
A senior military source said last night: ''There are likely to be
real fireworks tomorrow if the Bosnian Serbs do not pull back, and that
looks unlikely.''
General Ratko Mladic, the Bosnian Serb army commander, was understood
to have ordered troops to hide equipment in populated areas.
However, the military source added: ''There are still plenty of
targets and large-scale attacks are expected.''
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, in a letter to UN special envoy
Yasushi Akashi, said there was no need for air strikes as Bosnian Serbs
had no wish to target safe areas.
US military officials said reports suggested the air strikes had
halted Bosnian Serb shelling of Sarajevo but there were no indications
heavy weapons were being pulled back.
At Nato southern command headquarters in Naples US Navy Captain Jim
Mitchell said: ''These operations include air strikes, air cover,
reconnaissance, and of course search and rescue operations are
continuing for the two French pilots.''
The pilots ejected from their Mirage 2000 fighter-bomber when it was
shot down by a Bosnian Serb missile on Wednesday. French authorities
said they are known to be safe.
Bosnian Serb radio said yesterday's Nato attacks hit two sites
north-east of Sarajevo. It claimed several civilians were killed in the
raids ''in an area where there were neither military nor industrial
facilities''.
TV staff said the pictures of the five EU monitors with Bosnian Serb
officials were taken yesterday.
The information minister of the self-styled Bosnian Serb ''republic'',
Miroslav Toholj, said the men and their translator and driver had later
been set free and had already left Serb-held Bosnia. He did not say
where they had gone.
The missing EU men are three Spaniards led by the Spanish head of the
EU observation mission in the former Yugoslavia, an Irishman and a
Dutchman.
President Bill Clinton yesterday called for a negotiated end to the
war in Bosnia and said the Nato military campaign was sending a clear
message to Bosnian Serbs that the killing of innocent civilians must
end.
''The war in Bosnia must end, but not on the battlefield, rather at
the negotiating table,'' Clinton said in a brief speech at Hickam Air
Force Base after arriving in Honolulu.
Nato said it would not call off the biggest operation in its history
until the siege of Sarajevo was lifted.
A senior US officer at Nato headquarters in Naples said Operation
Deliberate Force would go on ''24 hours a day until we are told
otherwise''.
Setting out its terms for halting the raids a senior Nato official
said: ''We are not talking about the noose being loosened, the noose
must be taken away, not just loosened around the victim's neck.''
He said Nato and UN commanders demanded the removal of all heavy
weapons around the Bosnian capital, the reopening of the airport,
guaranteed access to routes in and out of the city and the restoration
of electricity and other utilities.
New Serb promises to remove heavy weapons threatening Sarajevo and
other safe areas such as Tuzla and Gorazde would not be good enough this
time. ''Safe areas must become exactly that -- safe,'' he said.
German Tornado jets were called upon yesterday to fly their country's
first potential combat mission since the Second World War but they had
to return to their base at the Italian town of Piacenza due to an
unspecified technical hitch.
American special envoy Richard Holbrooke, speaking in Belgrade, said
serious negotiations were finally under way thanks to an ''immensely
important'' procedural breakthrough engineered by Milosevic.
Holbrooke said that until Wednesday night, there was no-one from the
Bosnian Serb side who could talk for them and who accepted a plan drawn
up by the Big Power Contact group as a starting point for negotiations.
Milosevic announced on Wednesday the Bosnian Serbs had agreed to give
him a veto over terms of a peace deal that would now be negotiated by a
six-man team, three of whom would be from the breakaway Serb
''republic'' inside Bosnia.
Holbrooke said both the Bosnian Serbs and government side now agreed
to the 51:49% split of Bosnia.
''But they have very, very different ideas of which side gets what
parts of the country and this is going to be a very tough negotiation
but finally, as of last night, it's under way,'' he said.
</TEXT>
