<HEADLINE>Leaders tackle Ulster impasse. Leaders in bid to end Ulster deadlock</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT,ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>976601401</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE British and Irish Prime Ministers will seek to give fresh impetus
to the faltering Northern Ireland peace process at a Chequers summit
next Wednesday after Sinn Fein leaders declared yesterday, on the first
anniversary of the process, that it was ''in crisis''.
The two Governments announced that the summit between Mr John Major
and Irish Prime Minister John Bruton will go ahead despite earlier fears
that it might have to be delayed because of lack of agreement on the
next step.
Several telephone calls between the Prime Ministers earlier this week
appear to have overcome this hurdle. It now looks as though the two men
will call for an international commission to oversee the decommissioning
of weapons in the province.
Leading Sinn Fein negotiator Martin McGuinness, speaking at a news
conference at Westminster, ruled out the IRA handing over a single gun
as a gesture to break the talks deadlock.
He said they would regard that as ''an act of surrender''.
Mr McGuinness said: ''There is no way under, over or around this
issue. The British Government must abandon its attempts to get an IRA
surrender and demonstrate wisdom and courage in moving the peace process
beyond this stagnant stage.''
Both he and Mr Gerry Adams in Belfast said the process was now ''in
crisis''. However, the British and Irish Governments believe that an
international commission might be the way to start talks on
decommissioning.
The next obstacle to be overcome will be whether the British
Government gives the all- clear to talks between the Northern Ireland
political parties in parallel with talks on setting up a commission or
insists on its establishment before the talks can begin.
Even then, it is highly unlikely that the Unionist parties will agree
to sit down with Sinn Fein before IRA guns and bombs have been disposed
of under the eye of the commission.
British and Irish Government sources were cautiously optimistic
yesterday that ways would be found to inch the process forward.
However, Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew accused Sinn
Fein and the IRA of inflexibility and said the republicans had to
''remove the shadow of the gun'' from the search for peace.
He said all the flexibility shown in the last year had been by the
British Government while IRA and Sinn Fein stuck to saying they had a
tradition of not giving up arms -- ''Not exactly new thinking is it?''
Democratic Unionist leader Ian Paisley denounced the idea of an
international commission as ''a sell-out''. He said: ''It is not
acceptable to the people of Northern Ireland that the IRA are to be
elevated on to the plane where they shall sit down at a table because
they have arms and dictate the policy that is going to govern Northern
Ireland.''
Ulster Unionist spokesman Ken McGuinness was more restrained. He told
BBC Radio 4's The World At One programme: ''The IRA keep on talking
about surrendering. Nobody else has talked about that. What we have
talked about is the transition from the terrorist mode to the democratic
mode''.
Some encouragement for the two Governments has come from the perhaps
unlikely source of Mrs Bernadette McAliskey, who as Bernadette Devlin
was a nationalist MP at Westminster in the 1970's.
She said in a newspaper interview yesterday that the war was over and
the IRA would be unable to activate its only threat of resuming violence
''because people love the peace''.
Both Prime Ministers will be hoping she is right.
* The anniversary was marked in Glasgow with the launch of a campaign
group demanding the release of all so-called political prisoners held in
Northern Irish prisons, writes Alison Daniels.
Last night, a former republican prisoner, Felim O'Hagan, who served 17
years of a life sentence in the Maze prison before being released in
May, joined the campaign group Saoirse holding a vigil in George Square.
The group, an offshoot of a republican-founded organisation in
Northern Ireland, called on Scots to add their voices to those across
the sectarian divide demanding the release of 700 men and women, both
loyalists and republicans, held in jails in Northern Ireland, Britain,
and the United States, whom it described as political prisoners.
* Candle-light vigils were held as thousands of Sinn Fein supporters
took to the streets across Northern Ireland to mark the midnight start
of the IRA ceasefire one year ago.
The largest rallies were in Belfast and Londonderry. In Belfast,
rallies were held outside Army and police bases while in Londonderry
several thousand people marched from the Fort George army base to Free
Derry Corner in the Bogside.
